# PREFACE: Four Years. Daily.

Before AI was the question, I built governance under fire.

I have stood inside a Fortune 500 Client during due diligence and written down what nobody else wanted on paper. The deal did not close. Months later the company collapsed amid financial and tax fraud investigations, with regulators and prosecutors moving in. The findings I had recorded held up. That was not a victory. It was a confirmation that the work had been the work that needed doing, at the time it needed to be done, before anyone with subpoena power arrived.

I have walked into shipyards that the global economy had already condemned, where the order book was thin, the receivables were old, the suppliers were owed and the bank was deciding whether to keep the gates open until the next quarter. I have worked inside steel operations and tire operations whose accounting systems described what management wished were true rather than what was. I have served Clients whose strategic plans were authored to satisfy a board, not to govern a business.

I have been part of teams that sold operating units overnight, because by morning the entity that owned them would no longer exist in a form capable of selling anything. I have written the assignment language, the consent forms, the side letters and the disclosure schedules, knowing the documents I produced would be the only record left when the lawyers gathered to argue what had happened. I have prepared for arbitrations and for litigation that was never filed, because the file I built in advance made the claim unprofitable to bring.

I did not step onto well-run ships. I stepped onto ships that were taking water, whose captains had stopped reading the gauges, whose owners were preparing the lifeboats for themselves. The work was not to admire the engineering. The work was to identify, on the day I arrived, which compartments could still be sealed, which crew could still be trusted, which records could still be reconstructed and which obligations had already become claims looking for a defendant.

That is the foundation this book stands on. Four years of daily AI work sit on top of thirty-five years of governance, risk management and compliance work that began long before the present technology arrived, and that taught me what governance is for. AI changes the surface of the problem. It does not change the problem. The problem is always the named human, the recorded decision, the preserved evidence and the obligation that does not move.

## A note on the shape of this book

For a long time I carried the outline of a different book. Thirty-seven chapters, several appendices, a title with the weight I wanted it to carry. It was meant to gather everything I had been trying to say about AI, work, judgment, governance and responsibility. A magnum opus, or at least a very determined outline.

Then I wrote a simpler sentence about how things should be built. Human-made, for Easy Work, Simply Done. And I realized, somewhat inconveniently, that the sentence might be the whole book.

The phrase came back to me through Soetsu Yanagi’s The Beauty of Everyday Things and the mingei tradition he helped name. Ordinary things. Bowls, cloth, paper, tools. Things made for use, held in the hand, repaired when they break and returned to service without ceremony. That is a better model for AI workflows than most of what is sold as innovation. Not the spaceship, the bowl. Not the magic trick, the tool. Not the grand demonstration, the ordinary act of making work easier while keeping judgment intact.

That was the uncomfortable part. Thirty-seven chapters arguing for the bowl, shaped like a spaceship.

AI does not wait for the ground to stop shifting. By the time a theory is polished, the tools have changed, the workflows have changed and the people doing the work are already carrying the consequences. So I compressed the project. I kept the chapters that earn their place and wrapped up what was finished, and I left the rest for a later edition that the work itself will decide whether I need. This is also why the book leans on doctrine that does not depend on which regulation is in force this season or which tool shipped this quarter. The regulation will move. The tools will move. The named human, the recorded decision and the preserved evidence will not.

There is a Japanese repair, kintsugi, that mends a broken bowl with gold, showing the crack rather than hiding it, until the seam becomes the most honest part of the object. That is the whole of what I have been trying to say. Do not hide the break. Show the repair, and the hand behind it. The applause is optional. The liability is not.

So this is the shorter book. A bowl, not a spaceship. Made for use, and meant to be repaired in the using.

## A note on AI and this book

This book argues that AI must be used with discipline, with Informed Intent and with a named human carrying Final Liability for what is produced. The book itself was written that way. I worked heavily with AI throughout: drafting, structuring, stress-testing and refining, under intent specifications I wrote and against evidentiary standards I set. Every chapter, every line, passed through my judgment before it appeared in this manuscript. The AI was a tool. The doctrine governing its use was mine. The book sets out what that practice requires of any author, any deployer and any organization using AI for serious work.

Any mistakes in this book are mine and mine alone, not OpenAI’s, Anthropic’s, Google’s, Perplexity’s or any other provider’s. Where the book is useful, much of the credit goes to the people who have built and continue to build these models. NotebookLM in particular helped during research and synthesis. The book practices what it argues: I am the named human.

I am also indebted to the designers, engineers and researchers who built the AI systems that assisted this work, and to the vast, uneven human archive on which those systems depend: a corpus assembled not by design but by accumulation, comprising works licensed and unlicensed, attributed and anonymized, compensated and uncompensated, preserved and appropriated. These materials were created by individuals whose labor, imagination and legal rights have, in many cases, been collapsed into the abstraction we now call “data,” a term that obscures both origin and ownership.

This project is therefore entangled with a set of unresolved questions: what constitutes use versus extraction, influence versus incorporation, and innovation versus derivation. The outputs produced with these systems cannot be cleanly separated from the conditions under which their training data was gathered, nor from the legal and ethical ambiguities that continue to surround that process.

