The chapter has named deployment as a governance decision rather than a product milestone. The distinction is structural. A product milestone is a stopwatch act. The team finished. The interval is reported. The instrument is put down. A governance decision is a clock act. The decision is recorded. The cadence begins. The clock runs continuously for as long as the system runs. The organization that built its deployment program on the stopwatch logic put the instrument down at the moment the clock was supposed to start, and is now operating without a clock.

The chapter has named the seven questions that have to be answered before deployment. What harms the deployment is trying to prevent, what residual risk is acceptable and on what basis, what evidence supports the risk judgment, what controls must be operating at deployment, who can pause, who can roll back and what would change the organization’s mind. The seven questions converge on a single artifact, which is the deployment record. The deployment record is what the audit, the regulator, the litigant and the Client will examine. The same artifact will be examined by different inquirers in different forums, each asking some version of the same question, which is whether the organization thought about the seven things before deployment or after.

The chapter has located the deployment moment in the synthesizing AI assurance literature. The Approve, Communicate and Deploy triplet in the 2026 CSET Operationalizing brief is the literature’s structural name for the deployment-as-governance-decision posture this book develops. Approve records the decision. Communicate distributes it to the parties who must operate under it. Deploy starts the clock. The convergence between the two vocabularies is useful because it tells the practitioner that the deployment-as-governance-decision posture is where the assurance literature, read together, lands. The organization that has been through Approve, Communicate and Deploy, in that order, has done what the field recommends. The organization that treated deployment as a single act, run by stopwatch against a calendar, has not.

The chapter has named the triad at the deployment moment. Slow AI, Informed Intent and Final Liability converge in the deployment record. Each is doing distinct work. Each fails recognizably if the other two are absent. The deployment record is the artifact in which the three are joined. The discipline of building the record before deployment is what produces the governance the inquiry will eventually ask for. The chapter has connected forward to Chapter 9 on Informed Intent, sideways to Chapter 16 on Running the Governance, which develops the design function the General Counsel performs after deployment, and back to Chapter 5 on the inspection points the deployment record specifies, Chapter 6 on the scope the deployment record presupposes and Chapter 7 on the sign-for verb the deployment record carries.

