# CHAPTER 9

## Informed Intent

> *Those who employ their intellect before they see are denied a real comprehension of beauty.*
>
> *Soetsu Yanagi, The Way of Tea*

**The doctrine of Informed Consent entered medical ethics through the Nuremberg Code and the trials that produced it. A patient may authorize a procedure only if they have been given an accurate account of what the procedure involves, its risks, its alternatives and its consequences, at a level they can actually evaluate. A signature on a consent form without those conditions is not consent. It is paperwork. The doctrine did not arise from a preference for thorough documentation. It arose from the discovery that authorizations given under conditions of informational asymmetry, time pressure and authority produce results that no civilized legal system can defend.**

AI governance is now at the same point. The authorizations are being given. The forms are being signed. The board resolutions are being filed. And the humans whose names are on the authorizations are being briefed under conditions that would not meet the Informed Consent standard in any jurisdiction that has adopted it. Informed Intent is the transposition of that older doctrine into the governance of machine systems. It names the conditions under which a human authorization of an AI deployment can be treated as genuine rather than formal.

The transposition is not exact, and the difference is worth stating so it is not mistaken for carelessness. Informed Consent protects the subject of the procedure: the patient who will bear the consequence in their own body. Informed Intent protects, and binds, the authorizer: the principal who will answer for a system that acts on other people. The patient consents to a risk run on themselves. The authorizer signs for a risk run on everyone the system will touch. The two doctrines share one structure, that an authorization is genuine only when the person giving it had the conditions to understand it, but they point the obligation in opposite directions. Informed Consent guards the person acted upon. Informed Intent holds the person who set the action in motion. This book takes the medical doctrine for its structure, not for its beneficiary.

Slow AI and Final Liability are the two doctrines at the center of this book. Slow AI says govern the process deliberately: make the gears visible, build the evidence architecture before the system operates, treat every design choice as a governance decision. Final Liability says a named human carries the outcome regardless of how many systems, vendors and automated layers stand between the authorization and the consequence. Together they form the book’s governing argument.

But they leave a gap. You can govern the process and assign liability without the human who authorized the deployment ever actually understanding what they authorized. The signature is present. The board resolution is filed. The governance documentation is complete. And the person whose name is at the top of the accountability chain has a confident, fluent understanding of the system that is almost entirely wrong.

That gap is not hypothetical. It is the default condition in most AI deployments. Executives are briefed on AI systems the way they are briefed on financial instruments: in summary form, by people who have strong incentives to make the system sound manageable, at a level of abstraction that produces confidence without comprehension. The briefing produces wissen. The authorization requires verstehen. The gap between them is where governance fails before it begins.

Informed Intent is the connective tissue between the two doctrines. It is the requirement that the human who authorizes an AI deployment must actually understand what they are authorizing, at a level adequate to the consequences the authorization may produce. It converts Final Liability from a legal assignment into a substantive standard. A liability that is assigned to a human who was never given the conditions to understand what they were authorizing is not accountability. It is blame.

The parallel is not metaphorical. The medical Informed Consent doctrine exists because the legal system concluded that an authorization given without adequate understanding is not binding on the party that gave it, and is not exculpatory of the party that received it. The same conclusion is coming for AI. The executive who authorized the deployment under a briefing optimized for confidence rather than accuracy is not going to be treated, when the regulator or the court arrives, as having given a genuine authorization. The documentation will not save them. Informed Consent teaches what the documentation must demonstrate.

## Kennenlernen: To Get to Know

Kennenlernen is a German verb that joins kennen, to know by familiarity or acquaintance, with lernen, to learn. In ordinary use it means to get to know a person, a place, a subject or a practice. It implies a relationship that develops over time through repeated encounter. You do not kennenlernen something by reading about it once. You return to it. You encounter it in different contexts. You develop the kind of familiarity that produces discrimination, the ability to recognize when something is wrong, or different, or not what it was before.

German provides a sharper vocabulary for the different modes of knowing than English does. Wissen is factual knowledge: knowing that something is true. Kennen is knowledge by acquaintance: knowing something the way you know a city you have lived in. Verstehen is understanding: grasping the reasons and structure behind the facts. Erkennen is recognition: seeing what something is, often after prior acquaintance, in conditions that make it harder to see. These are not synonyms. They are distinct epistemic states, and the differences between them matter precisely when the stakes of getting them confused are highest.

AI systems produce wissen at scale and with enormous fluency. They generate facts, summaries, analyses and recommendations in language so polished that the output reads like understanding. This is the Demon Cat problem: the system has approximate knowledge of many things and delivers it in a voice that sounds certain. The person receiving the output cannot easily tell whether the confidence is warranted. And the person authorizing the deployment of that system is operating one level above: not reading the outputs but reading a description of the outputs, at a further remove from the underlying reality.

Informed Intent uses kennenlernen as its epistemological model because it names what adequate understanding requires. The authorizing human must have gotten to know the system, not downloaded a briefing about it. That means encountering it in operation, not only in presentation. It means understanding its failure modes, not only its capabilities. It means being able to recognize, when an output is presented, whether it is within the scope of what was authorized and within the quality of what was promised. That is a higher standard than most AI governance frameworks set for human oversight. It is the correct standard.

## What Informed Intent Requires

Informed Intent is not a subjective standard. It is an evidentiary one. The question is not whether the authorizing human feels they understand the system. The question is whether the record demonstrates that the conditions for genuine understanding were present before the authorization was given.

The pre-deployment specification is the primary instrument of Informed Intent. A specification that defines the system’s authorized purpose, acceptance thresholds, action scope, data access boundaries, escalation conditions and oversight mode is not merely a technical document. It is the written record of what the authorizing human said yes to. Its adequacy as a governance document depends on whether the person who approved it understood each of those elements at the level required to have made a genuine decision about them.

A specification approved by someone who does not understand what an acceptance threshold is cannot be said to have been authorized in the Informed Intent sense. A risk appetite statement signed by a board that has not been briefed on what the specific risk categories mean for this specific system is a form, not a decision. The signature represents legal authorization. Informed Intent requires something more: the conditions under which the signature represented actual judgment.

Those conditions have three components. First, the authorizing human must have been given an accurate account of the system’s capabilities and limitations, including its failure modes, not only its performance metrics. A briefing that presents only the accuracy score and the efficiency gain has not provided an accurate account. Second, they must have been given enough time and access to develop familiarity, not merely receive information. A thirty-minute board presentation on a system that will process fifty thousand decisions per month is not adequate preparation for authorization. Third, the authorization must have been given by a person with the competence to evaluate what they were told. A board that lacks the technical literacy to assess the quality of the information it received cannot provide Informed Intent regardless of how much time it was given.

The TEVV plan is the test of the specification’s adequacy. If the specification was genuinely understood by the authorizing human, the TEVV plan should be assessable against it: every test objective should trace back to a governance commitment the authorizing human made. If the TEVV plan cannot be read as the operationalization of the specification’s commitments, the specification was either inadequate or not understood. An auditor examining the pre-deployment record looks for this traceability. Its absence is a finding.

## Inferred Intent

Informed Intent has a precise opposite, and naming it sharpens the standard. The opposite is Inferred Intent: the condition under which the system proceeds without an explicit account of what it is being asked, and the human proceeds without an explicit account of what s/he is asking. Each side reads the other and fills the gap with assumption. The model infers purpose from context, prior outputs and the shape of the prompt. The user infers capability from fluency, confidence and the absence of refusal. The two inferences ratify each other. No one wrote down what was being authorized.

Inferred Intent is not a failure of either side in isolation. It is a structural failure of the exchange. Informed Intent requires both sides of the interaction to be explicit: the model must be given an account of what it is being asked at the level of specification adequate to the consequences, and the human must have an account of what s/he is asking at the level of comprehension adequate to take responsibility for the answer. The first half is the intent specification. The second half is the authorizing human’s competence to evaluate it. Either half alone is insufficient. A precise specification approved by a person who did not understand it is not Informed Intent. A competent person issuing instructions the system is not equipped to receive accurately is not Informed Intent either. Both halves must hold, and the record must show they did, before the authorization is genuine.

## Prompt Engineering as Governance

The AI governance community has spent considerable energy on prompt engineering as a technical discipline: the craft of constructing instructions that produce high-quality outputs from language models. The governance community has been slower to recognize that prompt engineering, properly understood, is a governance act. The prompt is the intent specification. It defines what the system is authorized to do in the specific context of a specific interaction. Its adequacy as a governance instrument depends on exactly the same standards that apply to any other intent document.

Intent engineering is prompt engineering done with the rigor and documentation standards that governance requires. The distinction is not technical. It is evidentiary. A prompt produced by iterating on outputs until they look right is not an intent specification. It is a calibration exercise. It does not document what the system was authorized to do. It records what made the outputs acceptable to the person who was looking at them at the time. An auditor cannot assess whether the prompt reflected a genuine governance decision because no governance decision was made. The acceptable output was found by trial. The acceptability criteria were never written down.

Intent engineering requires the acceptability criteria to be written before the prompt is constructed. What must the output achieve? What must it not produce? What populations will it affect? What harm categories are out of scope? What oversight applies before the output reaches a consequential use? These are governance questions. The answers to them constitute the intent specification. The prompt is the technical mechanism by which the intent specification is communicated to the system. The prompt can be revised. The intent specification governs which revisions are permissible and which would change what was authorized.

This sequencing requirement is not procedural formality. It is the structural condition under which Informed Intent can be demonstrated. If the intent specification was documented before the prompt was constructed, the authorizing human’s understanding can be assessed against the specification. If the specification was produced after the prompt, by reverse-engineering what the prompt was designed to do, the governance record is reconstruction, not documentation. Evidence produced after the question was asked is not audit-grade. The same principle that governs the pre-deployment specification governs the intent document at the interaction level.

## The Audit of Informed Intent

The audit question for prompt engineering as governance is not whether the outputs looked reasonable after deployment. It is whether the intent specification was adequate before deployment. These are different inquiries with different evidentiary requirements and different findings.

An audit that examines outputs and asks whether they were acceptable has examined compliance with an implicit standard. An audit that examines the intent specification and asks whether it was adequate has examined governance. The difference is the same difference that runs through every chapter of this book: the difference between a framework that describes what governance should look like and a record that proves it operated.

The audit of Informed Intent looks for four things. It looks for the intent specification, documented before deployment, specifying what was authorized and what was not. It looks for evidence that the authorizing human had the conditions to genuinely understand the specification: the accurate account of capabilities and limitations, the adequate time and access, the competence to evaluate what they received. It looks for the TEVV plan as the operationalization of the specification’s commitments, traceable back to each governance decision the specification records. And it looks for the monitoring and re-validation record as evidence that the Informed Intent standard was maintained through the system’s operational life, not merely satisfied at deployment.

The absence of any one of these is a finding. The absence of the intent specification means the authorization was not recorded. The absence of evidence that the authorizing human had the conditions for genuine understanding means the authorization may not have been genuine. The absence of the TEVV plan’s traceability means the specification may not have been adequate. The absence of ongoing re-validation means the system may have drifted from what was authorized without the authorizing human being in a position to know.

## Counterfeit Familiarity

The failure mode that Informed Intent is designed to prevent has a name: counterfeit familiarity. It is the condition in which a human believes they understand a system well enough to authorize it because they have received fluent, confident information about it, without having developed the actual acquaintance that genuine understanding requires.

Counterfeit familiarity is not dishonesty. It is the natural product of the briefing culture that governs most executive and board interaction with complex technical systems. The briefing is optimized for comprehensibility, which means it is optimized for the reduction of complexity. The reduction of complexity produces confidence. The confidence produces authorization. The authorization produces liability. The liability attaches to a human whose understanding of what they authorized was constructed at a level of abstraction that would not survive contact with the actual system in operation.

The Demon Cat, as described in Part I, is the AI system’s version of this problem: approximate knowledge of many things, delivered in a voice that sounds authoritative. Counterfeit familiarity is the human version. The executive who authorized the deployment does not know that their understanding is approximate. Neither does the system. The approximation compounds through every layer of delegation between the authorization and the consequence.

The organizational conditions that produce counterfeit familiarity are the same conditions that produce the feudal governance problem described in Chapters 14 and 22. Information travels upward in forms optimized for senior audiences: summary, abstracted, polished, stripped of the uncertainty and qualification that would communicate genuine complexity. Liability travels downward to the people who are closest to the operation and furthest from the protection of rank. The person at the top authorizes with counterfeit familiarity. The person at the bottom operates with full knowledge of the system’s actual limitations. When something goes wrong, the authorization at the top is treated as genuine and the failure at the bottom is treated as the problem.

Informed Intent breaks this pattern by requiring that the conditions for genuine understanding be present before authorization is given. It does not require the authorizing human to become a technical expert. It requires that they be given an accurate account of the system’s capabilities and limitations rather than an optimized one, that they be given adequate time and access rather than a presentation, and that the authorization be given by someone with the competence to evaluate what they received. These are governance requirements, not technical ones. They are assessable, documentable and auditable. They produce a record that demonstrates genuine authorization rather than a form that records the appearance of it.

Final Liability can only be meaningfully assigned to a human who was given the conditions to understand what they were authorizing. A liability assigned without those conditions is not accountability. It is exposure. The distinction matters when the system fails, when the regulator inquires, when the insurer evaluates the claim and when the court assesses whether the human whose name is on the authorization actually bore the responsibility that name implies.

## What This Chapter Has Done

The chapter has defined Informed Intent and traced it to the medical doctrine of Informed Consent, while distinguishing the two by beneficiary. Consent protects the subject. Intent binds the authorizer.

The chapter has named the conditions under which an authorization can be treated as genuine rather than formal, and the counterfeit familiarity that defeats them.

The chapter has shown that Informed Intent is what makes Final Liability real, the standard that converts governance documentation into governance.

The medical profession learned this the hard way, over decades, at the cost of real patients. The AI governance profession does not have decades. The doctrine is on the shelf. The only question is whether the authorizing human reaches for it before the authorization is given or after the consequence arrives. Informed Intent is what makes Final Liability real rather than formal. It is the standard that converts governance documentation into genuine governance. The signature at the top of the accountability chain either reflects a human who gave genuine Informed Intent, or it reflects the same paper that did not save the medical profession before the doctrine was named.

**Final Liability rests with the Human.**

