## The Agent in the Room

> *The love of the irregular is a sign of the basic quest for freedom.*
>
> *Soetsu Yanagi, The Unknown Craftsman*

**The agent is never neutral. It carries whatever the principal put into it: the objectives, the ambiguities, the unstated assumptions and the structural failures that no governance document named but every operational outcome eventually reveals.**

Chapter 10 described how organizational culture operates as code: the values encoded into agentic AI through prompts, permission structures and workflow integrations shape not only the agent’s behavior but the behavior of every human working around it. This chapter addresses the prior problem. Before the agent can carry any culture forward, the principal who deployed it must have provided something worth carrying. When the principal does not, when the direction is unstable, the information withheld, the authority granted and then revoked, the accountability disavowed at the moment it becomes inconvenient, the agent is not the source of the problem. It is the receiver of it.

Agency law has a name for what happens when direction becomes unreliable. Objectives shift without notice. Material information is withheld or distorted. Authority is extended to induce reliance, then disavowed when the agent acts on it. Compensation is promised, then denied. Each move, taken alone, might look like management. Taken together, they describe an organization at war with its own agent.

Walt Kelly’s Pogo said it in 1970, in a poster for the first Earth Day. “We have met the enemy and he is us.”

The doctrine this chapter introduces is the unreliable principal: the principal who fails to provide stable, honest and enforceable direction or support to an agent, who shifts objectives without notice, withholds or distorts material information, renounces commitments after inducing reliance on them and opportunistically disavows the agent’s authority when accountability arrives. The Restatement Third of Agency addresses the consequences of this failure pattern on multiple fronts: through the principal’s duties to compensate, reimburse and indemnify agents for authorized acts; through apparent authority doctrine, which holds the principal to representations that induced third-party reliance; and through the structural logic that agency requires a functional principal, and that without one the structure itself becomes a source of harm.

The unreliable principal is not a theory. It is a description.

## What the Unreliable Principal Does

The failure pattern has a recognizable shape. It does not appear as a single dramatic act of betrayal. It accumulates through the management of what cannot be pinned down.

The mandate is never quite specific enough to be held to. Strategic objectives shift with ownership priorities, market pressure or senior management changes, and each shift is presented not as a change in direction but as a clarification of what was always intended. The agent who acted on the prior direction finds they acted on a misunderstanding. The agent who asks for clarification finds the clarification has already shifted again.

Material information is withheld or distorted at the distribution layer. What the agent needs to exercise sound judgment reaches them in a form that has been filtered through organizational interests that are not aligned with the agency relationship. Risks are downplayed. Constraints are left unstated. The information the agent receives describes a situation manageable enough to act on, while the real situation, which the principal’s level knows but does not share, would have warranted different action or no action at all.

Authority is extended as a matter of operational convenience and retracted as a matter of self-protection. The agent is given apparent authority to bind the organization, to represent its commitments, to act on its behalf with third parties. When those third parties appear with claims based on those commitments, the principal discovers that the agent exceeded their actual authority. The record that would have established the authority did not get made, or is being read selectively. The agent is exposed to third-party claims they cannot defend and internal claims they cannot escape.

Compensation and indemnity are renegotiated downstream. What was represented as the terms of the agency relationship evolves as performance is delivered. The commitment that induced the agent to take on the risk is reframed as contingent, aspirational or never quite as categorical as the agent understood it to be.

Each of these is individually survivable. Together they constitute an operational environment in which the agent is systematically undermined. The fiduciary duties the agent owes become harder to discharge when the mandate keeps moving. The professional judgment the agent is supposed to exercise cannot be exercised with integrity when the information it depends on has been curated against the agent’s interests. The actions the agent takes in reliance on apparent authority become liabilities rather than services when the principal later denies the authority.

## The Agent Does Not Simply Absorb the Instability. It Transmits It.

The harm of the unreliable principal does not stay inside the agency relationship. It propagates outward.

Third parties who dealt with the agent in good faith, relying on the apparent authority the principal conferred, are left with claims against an agent who may lack the resources to satisfy them and a principal who will contest the authority that was extended. The third party’s reliance was reasonable. The apparent authority was real. The principal’s later disavowal produces what agency law recognizes as a form of unjust enrichment for the principal and an unjust exposure for both the agent and the third party who relied on the representation.

The agent is left holding the exposure the principal created. Not because the agent acted badly. Because the principal created the conditions and then withdrew from accountability.

This is not a technology problem and it is not a problem unique to any industry or era. It is a structural feature of the principal-agent relationship when the principal is unwilling or unable to maintain the obligations the relationship imposes. The Restatement Third of Agency responds by strengthening principal-side duties: the obligation to compensate, reimburse, indemnify and deal honestly with agents who acted in reliance on the authority they were given. In extreme cases, where the principal is too incoherent or incapacitated to serve as a responsible decision point, the law’s response is to terminate agency altogether. The structure cannot survive a non-functional principal. The termination logic is not a failure of the relationship. It is the law’s recognition that agency without a principal capable of holding the principal’s obligations is not governance. It is exposure, without the structure to manage it.

## The Personal Dimension

I have sat in that chair.

The mandate was unclear, the principal not just unreliable but shifty, and accountability ran in one direction only. The direction it ran was not toward the people who had created the conditions. The governance documents were complete. The organizational chart showed a functional principal. The reality was an environment in which strategic direction was managed through plausible deniability, information was distributed to serve narratives rather than to support judgment, and the agent who acted in good faith on the authority they believed they held discovered, at the moment of consequence, that the record had been arranged to tell a different story.

This book does not name those principals. The pattern they represent names itself. It is the unreliable principal, and its appearance in every industry, every jurisdiction and every organizational form this author has encountered suggests it is not an aberration. It is a structural temptation that governance must name, constrain and in the limit be prepared to terminate.

## When the Agent Is a System

In AI deployment the principal is the organization. The agent is the system. Unlike a human agent, the system cannot push back on a shifting mandate, cannot flag an unclear instruction and has no standing to object. It runs. The unreliable principal problem does not shrink when the agent is automated. It scales.

This is the governance condition that most AI risk analyses do not reach. The literature on AI risk is rich on the question of what the system might do wrong: the hallucination, the bias, the misuse, the adversarial attack. It is thinner on the prior question of what the deploying organization might do wrong, and on the structural relationship between the deploying organization’s dysfunction and the outcomes it attributes to the system. An organization that shifts objectives after deployment, provides the system with distorted operational context, withholds the information the system needs to operate within its authorized scope and then disavows the deployment decisions that produced the outcome, is not a victim of an AI failure. It is the unreliable principal in a novel form.

The system that inherits an incoherent mandate cannot resolve the incoherence. It processes what it is given. When the outputs are wrong, the organization that withheld the information those outputs depended on is not a bystander. It is the source. What looks like an agent problem is a principal problem that has been outsourced downstream.

The five operational catechism questions in Chapter 4 are directly implicated by the unreliable principal. Who owns the model: a question the unreliable principal has not answered clearly. Who owns the use case: a question whose answer shifts with organizational priorities. Who can stop the system: a question the unreliable principal has not pre-delegated because pre-delegation requires clarity about what stopping means. Where is the evidence: a question the unreliable principal has not prepared for because evidence-building requires accountability the unreliable principal is avoiding. What happens when the output is wrong: a question the unreliable principal will answer by pointing at the system.

## When the Agent Becomes the More Disciplined Party

The unreliable principal problem was first articulated when agents were human and the dimensions on which an agent could fail were the dimensions of human professional capacity. The argument generalized to AI deployment in the prior section without changing its structure. The same generalization, run from the agent side, produces a sharper version of the doctrine for the present moment.

For most of the period during which AI systems have been deployed at scale, the model itself was the most plausible source of failure. Hallucination, drift, brittle tool use, refusal logic that could not be reasoned with: the audit work concentrated on the agent because that was where the failures concentrated. The location of the failure has moved.

On the dimensions where measurement has matured, frontier models have improved enough that the original benchmarks have been replaced by harder ones. Verifiable instruction following on the IFEval benchmark, introduced by Zhou et al. (2023), is approaching saturation at the top of the field, with leading models scoring above ninety-three percent. Grounded summarization on Vectara’s Hughes Hallucination Evaluation Model leaderboard improved enough that the leaderboard operators released a harder benchmark generation in late 2025 with longer documents and broader domains, because the original could no longer separate the frontier. The Berkeley Function Calling Leaderboard published by Patil et al. at ICML 2025 reports the same pattern: top models ace single-turn function calls and stumble only when they must remember context, manage long conversations or decide when not to act. None of this means the model is finished. It means the model is no longer the most unreliable element in the deployment.

Now look at the same period from the other side. Stanford’s 2026 AI Index Report, drawing on the AI Incident Database, records 362 documented AI incidents in 2025, up from 233 the year before. Capability rose. Incidents rose with it. Every plausible cause for that second curve is principal-side. More deployments. Weaker oversight. More failures attributed to systems that were operating exactly as instructed within a mandate that was never coherent enough to define what correct operation meant. The principal side has not kept pace with the agent side.

The same picture emerges from the academic risk-management literature. A multi-institutional survey of open problems in frontier AI risk management led by Ziosi et al. (2026) at the Oxford Martin AI Governance Initiative classifies the unresolved challenges across the risk management lifecycle into three types: a lack of scientific consensus about the technology, a misalignment with established risk management frameworks, or an implementation shortcoming despite apparent consensus. Roughly four out of five of the open problems they enumerate sit in the latter two categories. Both are principal-side. The literature and the incident curve point at the same place.

The asymmetry has a name in audio engineering. Wow and flutter are measured speed defects in analog playback equipment: wow the slow drift, flutter the rapid instability. Audiophile turntables publish their wow and flutter ratings on the back of the unit. Most organizations that deploy AI would refuse to publish theirs. The mandate has wow and flutter the model does not. Objectives shift between Monday’s standup and Wednesday’s all-hands. Compensation logic is promised in the budget cycle and denied in the audit cycle. Authority is extended to induce a launch and disavowed when the launch produces something the principal did not want to read about in writing. Each of these is a measurable form of mandate instability. The agent runs cleanly through all of it because the agent has no standing to object. The exposure pools downstream.

For most of the deployment era, the question whether an organization was ready to run a particular AI system was a question about model maturity. Was the system reliable enough to perform the task at the required level? That question has not disappeared but it is no longer the binding constraint for most enterprise deployments. The binding constraint is principal maturity. Can the deploying organization hold a stable mandate? Can it document its authority? Can it commit in writing, before the agent runs, to what the agent is authorized to do, under what conditions and at whose risk? These are not questions the model can answer. They are questions about the human apparatus around the model, and the human apparatus has not improved at the rate the model has.

An organization that cannot hold a stable mandate is not ready to run an agent. That is no longer a hypothesis about model maturity. On the audited dimensions the model is the more disciplined party. The bottleneck is the chair behind the desk.

Informed Intent, developed in Chapter 9 and applied in the next section, is the structural response.

## Informed Intent and the Principal’s Obligation

Informed Intent, developed in Chapter 9, is the governance response to the unreliable principal at the AI deployment level. It demands that the principal commit in writing, before deployment, to what the agent is authorized to do, under what conditions and at whose risk.

The demand is not procedural formalism. It is the structural resolution of the unreliable principal problem. A principal who commits in writing, before the system operates, to the system’s authorized purpose, acceptance thresholds, action scope and escalation conditions has produced the baseline against which the system’s behavior can be assessed and against which the principal’s own obligations are measured. The written specification is not a constraint on the principal’s flexibility. It is the condition under which the principal’s authority over the agent is legitimate. An authority that is never written down is not an authority that can be traced, verified or held to.

Without that commitment there is no agency. There is only exposure.

The unreliable principal who deploys a system without Informed Intent specifications has not governed the deployment. They have created an operational environment in which the system runs on inferred intent, third-party harms are legally ambiguous and the organizational record, when the question of accountability arrives, will not contain the documentation that distinguished what was authorized from what was not.

## Slow AI and the Principal’s Discipline

Slow AI is the operational method for organizations that recognize the unreliable principal failure mode and intend to avoid it. Not slow as in hesitant. Slow as in deliberate: documented mandate, stable objectives, maintained oversight, indemnity structure in place before deployment.

The Slow AI discipline requires the principal to hold the obligations the relationship imposes. It requires that the direction provided to the agent be stable enough for the agent to act on it. It requires that material information be provided rather than withheld. It requires that the authority granted be consistent with the authority the agent will need to exercise. It requires that the compensation and indemnity commitments be honored.

Speed without those conditions is not efficiency. It is a principal failing its own agent, and in the AI deployment context, that failure is not bounded by the agent’s ability to recognize it and demand better. The system will not recognize it. The system will run.

The organizations that avoid the unreliable principal failure mode are the organizations that have built Slow AI disciplines into their deployment practice from the beginning: that treat each agentic deployment as a relationship requiring the same care as any other principal-agent relationship, with the same written specifications, the same evidence architecture and the same commitment to maintaining the obligations the relationship creates. The organizations that do not will eventually produce the outputs that only an unreliable principal can produce: systems running on incoherent mandates, third parties relying on authority that was never stable, accountability concentrated in the agent that cannot hold it and disavowed by the principal that created the conditions.

## What This Chapter Has Done

The chapter has named the unreliable principal, the human or institution whose own instability the agent faithfully transmits.

The chapter has shown that an agent cannot be more coherent than the principal it serves, which makes principal maturity a binding governance constraint rather than a soft one.

The chapter has turned the governance question inward. The enemy is met, and the question is whether the organization recognizes itself in time.

We have met the enemy. The governance question is whether we will recognize ourselves in time.

