## The Human in the Loop Is Not a Shaman

> *The chief characteristic of handcrafts is that they maintain by their very nature a direct link with the human heart.*
>
> *Soetsu Yanagi, The Unknown Craftsman*

**A human in the loop is not governance. It is a place in a diagram.**

**Governance begins only when the human has the knowledge, authority, time, evidence and permission to change what the system is about to do.**

There is a comforting phrase in artificial intelligence governance: human in the loop.

It sounds responsible. It suggests restraint. It reassures boards, customers, regulators, insurers and lawyers that the machine has not been left alone. Somewhere before the consequential act, there is a person. The system may recommend, classify, rank, triage, summarize, predict, route, approve, deny, escalate or draft. But the human is still there.

That comfort is often too cheap.

A human can be placed in a workflow without being given meaningful agency over the workflow. A human can click approve without understanding what has been framed, hidden, compressed or excluded by the system. A human can be told they are supervising a decision whose tempo, evidence base and default answer have already been set by the machine. A human can be formally present and practically displaced.

At that point, the human in the loop becomes a shaman. The person is brought into the ritual to bless the output. The organization gets the appearance of human judgment. The system gets the benefit of human legitimacy. The record shows that a person was involved. But the person did not meaningfully decide.

That is not oversight.

It is ceremony.

The military artificial intelligence literature is useful here because it strips the euphemism away. In military settings, the phrase “decision support” cannot be treated as harmless. A system that supports a targeting decision, operational plan or battlefield assessment may shape life-and-death outcomes even if it never pulls a trigger.

The open access volume Legal, Ethical, and Technical Dilemmas in Military Artificial Intelligence, edited by Bérénice Boutin, Taylor Kate Woodcock and Sadjad Soltanzadeh, is valuable precisely because it examines military artificial intelligence across autonomous weapons systems, decision-support technologies and AI-augmented human capabilities, while focusing on how artificial intelligence reshapes agency, responsibility and control.

The DILEMA project behind the volume deliberately broadened the military AI discussion beyond autonomous weapons systems. It addressed decision-support systems and intelligence tools that are said to assist, rather than replace, human judgment. It also moved the discussion from meaningful human control toward human agency and emphasized legal compliance in design and development, not merely after deployment.

Those moves matter beyond war.

Most enterprise artificial intelligence will not look like a robot making a spectacular autonomous decision. It will look like software that helps a professional do ordinary work faster. It will score a claim. It will summarize a complaint. It will rank applicants. It will flag a transaction. It will draft a response. It will propose a remediation plan. It will suggest a contract position. It will triage a customer, employee, patient, supplier or borrower into a category that changes what happens next.

The organization will say the tool supports a human.

Sometimes that will be true.

Sometimes it will be a legal fiction with a user interface.

## Military-Grade Does Not Mean Militarized

The phrase “military-grade” is often abused. It can become marketing decoration. It can imply toughness without explaining what is tough, tested or governed. It can also invite the wrong lesson: that enterprise AI governance should become martial, hierarchical or aggressive.

That is not the point.

Military-grade AI Governance, Risk Management and Compliance means consequential-grade governance. It means governance built for environments where the cost of error is high, the operating context is dynamic, the facts are incomplete, the tempo is pressured and accountability cannot be solved by saying someone was somewhere near the decision.

That standard travels.

A bank deciding credit is not conducting a military operation. A hospital triaging patients is not conducting targeting. A company screening applicants is not fighting a war. A legal department using an AI assistant is not operating a weapons system. But all of them may rely on artificial intelligence in settings where a human being, a legal right, a material interest, a safety condition or a regulatory obligation is affected by the system’s output.

Military-grade, in this chapter, means that governance is built for consequence.

It means the organization does not confuse a policy with control. It does not confuse a briefing with understanding. It does not confuse a sign-off with judgment. It does not confuse a dashboard with oversight. It does not confuse a post-incident explanation with evidence that should have been generated at the time.

It asks harder questions earlier.

What is the mission? What is the decision? What is the consequence? What authority is being delegated? What must remain human? What assumptions must hold? What happens if they fail? What evidence will prove that the human understood enough to authorize, intervene or stop? What happens when the system changes, the context changes or the organization learns that the old controls were not enough?

This is not war-making logic imported into business. It is disciplined governance imported from a domain that cannot afford decorative human oversight.

That is why military artificial intelligence is useful for enterprise artificial intelligence. It forces the governance vocabulary to become operational. Human agency must mean something. Responsibility must attach somewhere. Compliance must be designed into the system. Review must continue after deployment. Failure must produce learning. Authority must be visible. Evidence must survive.

That is Slow AI in its hardest form.

## The Difference Between Presence and Agency

The first distinction is simple.

Presence is not agency.

A person is present when the workflow includes a step assigned to a person. A person has agency when the surrounding conditions allow that person to exercise judgment that can change the outcome.

Those conditions are not mystical. They can be named.

The human must understand the decision being made. The human must understand what the system did to the evidence before the evidence reached them. The human must know the limits of the system’s competence. The human must know the stakes of the decision. The human must know when the system’s output is out of bounds. The human must have authority to override, pause, escalate or reject. The human must have enough time to use that authority. The human must be protected from retaliation, embarrassment or bureaucratic penalty when they use it.

Without those conditions, the human is not in the loop in any meaningful sense.

The human is merely at the end of the loop.

This is why the DILEMA project’s move from meaningful human control to human agency is so important. Control can be treated as binary: the human could intervene or could not. Agency requires a better question: did the human retain a meaningful capacity to understand, deliberate and alter the outcome? The issue is not whether a person appears in the process map. The issue is whether the person still has qualitative influence over the decision.

That is the right question for enterprise governance.

The question is not whether a person clicked.

The question is whether the person had a live opportunity to think.

Agency has at least five components.

First, epistemic access. The human must have access to the facts, context, uncertainty and limitations needed for the decision. A person cannot exercise judgment over facts they never see.

Second, interpretive competence. The human must be able to understand what the system output means and what it does not mean. A score, label or confidence estimate is not self-explanatory.

Third, decisional authority. The human must be able to change the outcome. Review without power is observation.

Fourth, temporal room. The human must have enough time to deliberate. A ten-second approval window in a high-stakes workflow may preserve the optics of control while destroying its substance.

Fifth, organizational permission. The human must be allowed to disagree. If escalation is punished, delay is stigmatized or override is treated as user error, the formal authority is hollow.

A military-grade enterprise AI program treats those five elements as control requirements. It does not merely write “human oversight” in a policy. It proves that epistemic access, interpretive competence, decisional authority, temporal room and organizational permission exist in the workflow.

That is the difference between governance and set design.

## The Legal Direction Is Already Operational

This is not merely a philosophical point. The regulatory direction is already moving toward operational oversight.

Article 14 of the European Union AI Act requires high-risk AI systems to be designed and developed so that natural persons can effectively oversee them during use. Human oversight is supposed to prevent or minimize risks to health, safety and fundamental rights, including risks that remain despite other system requirements. The provision also addresses human-machine interface tools, appropriate oversight measures and the ability of humans to interpret, disregard, override or interrupt certain system outputs or operations.

That is an important shift. The law does not merely ask whether a human exists somewhere in the process. It asks whether the system is designed so the human can oversee it effectively.

The National Institute of Standards and Technology AI Risk Management Framework points in the same practical direction. Its core functions, Govern, Map, Measure and Manage, are designed to help organizations create dialogue, understanding and activities for managing AI risks across the lifecycle. The Generative AI Profile adds that policies and procedures should define and differentiate roles and responsibilities for human-AI configurations and oversight of AI systems.

These frameworks are not identical. They do not solve the problem by themselves. But they share a useful premise: human oversight is not a slogan. It must be designed, assigned, documented, tested and maintained.

That is the practical bridge from law to governance.

The organization cannot simply say a human is in the loop. It must show what the human can see, understand, decide, override, stop and later explain.

## Decision Support Can Become Decision Displacement

The phrase “decision support system” performs a quiet act of persuasion. It tells the organization what the system is supposed to be before anyone has examined what it actually does.

Support sounds subordinate. Support sounds helpful. Support sounds safe.

But support can displace.

A system can displace the human by framing the facts. It can decide which facts are salient, which are summarized, which are omitted and which are presented with confidence. It can displace the human by narrowing the options. It can present three choices when there were seven. It can displace the human by setting the tempo. It can produce a recommendation quickly enough that a slower human objection feels inefficient or obstructive. It can displace the human by assigning scores, categories and labels that become psychologically sticky. It can displace the human by making dissent administratively expensive.

A human may retain the theoretical power to disagree. The practical structure makes disagreement rare.

The military AI literature identifies this risk directly. AI-driven decision-support systems can become de facto decision makers as they become more complex, fast and adaptive. In high-stakes, time-sensitive situations, operators may defer to recommendations without fully understanding them or weighing alternatives. Automation bias then erodes genuine human judgment even where formal oversight remains.

This is not a military problem.

It is a workflow problem.

A compliance analyst reviewing a suspicious transaction can be displaced by a risk score. A human resources manager reviewing candidates can be displaced by a ranking. A lawyer reviewing a clause can be displaced by a confident summary. A procurement officer reviewing a supplier can be displaced by a vendor risk rating. A customer-service agent reviewing a refund can be displaced by a policy recommendation generated from incomplete facts.

In each case the human may remain formally in control.

In each case the decision may have already moved.

This is where Slow AI starts. Slow AI does not demand slowness everywhere. It demands friction where judgment is at risk of being displaced. It places slow points where the system frames evidence, narrows options, sets defaults, changes incentives or moves consequences downstream.

The organization does not need to slow every computation.

It needs to slow the transfer of authority.

A military-grade version of this point is blunt: do not ask who fired the weapon after the targeting system has already selected the target, filtered the intelligence, ranked the threat and compressed the window for refusal.

In enterprise terms, do not ask who approved the recommendation after the system has already selected the relevant evidence, scored the case, framed the exception and made rejection administratively painful.

The real control point may be upstream.

That is where the audit should go.

## When Oversight Becomes Decoration

Jovana Davidovic’s 2026 paper, “The End of Human Judgment in the Kill Chain? Relocating Initiative and Interpretation with Agentic AI,” pushes the problem one step further. Her argument is not simply that military artificial intelligence can make human oversight difficult. It is that large language model-based agents may relocate the very functions that make human judgment meaningful.

The paper identifies four features that make these agents operationally attractive in military data fusion, intelligence analysis and battlefield management: initiative, interpretation, goal-directedness and dynamic memory. Those same features, Davidovic argues, can render context-appropriate human judgment and control substantively ineffectual in the parts of the kill chain where the agents operate.

That is the agentic version of the human-in-the-loop problem.

A conventional decision-support system may frame the facts, rank the options or suggest a recommendation. An agentic system can go further. It can interpret intent, decompose a goal, decide what information to seek, adjust the plan, remember prior steps, revise its confidence and determine when or whether to ask a human for input.

At that point the system is no longer merely producing a recommendation inside a human decision process. It is helping construct the world in which the human later decides.

That changes the oversight question.

The weak question is: did a human approve the output?

The stronger question is: did the human’s judgment remain part of the causal explanation for the outcome?

Davidovic frames this as a relocation of initiative and interpretation. In governance terms, the issue is the movement of epistemic and normative authority. Epistemic authority is the practical power to shape what counts as relevant knowledge. Normative authority is the practical power to shape what ought to be done. When an agent decides what evidence to collect, which signals to trust, how to assess confidence, when to seek more information and when to call on a human, ethically and legally salient moves have already occurred before the human is asked to bless the result.

The enterprise version is familiar.

A fraud system decides which transaction history matters. A hiring system decides which applicant traits are salient. An underwriting system decides which risk signals deserve weight. A procurement system decides which supplier issues are serious. A sanctions-screening system decides which matches deserve escalation. A compliance system decides which events become anomalies, which anomalies become cases and which cases become reports.

The system is not firing a weapon.

But it may be deciding what the human will know.

That is epistemic authority.

The system may also decide which risk matters, which policy objective dominates, which next step is appropriate and when intervention is unnecessary.

That is normative authority.

When both move into the agent, a human at the end of the process may be present without being central. The human becomes a side character in a story the system has already written. In some workflows, even that may overstate the role. The human is not a character at all. The human is part of the set.

Present in the scene.

Not in the story.

This is why dashboards and sign-off buttons are inadequate as proof of oversight. A dashboard can show what the system chose to display. A sign-off button can record that a person accepted what the system presented. Neither proves that the person’s judgment shaped the outcome in a way that can be reconstructed, challenged or defended.

The analogy is ordinary because the pattern is ordinary. A skilled waiter can shape a dinner decision without removing the diner’s formal freedom to choose. He describes the lamb with warmth and a small story, gives the cheaper pasta two words and a pause, reads the table, adjusts the pitch and leaves the diner believing the choice was spontaneous. The decision was real enough.

The architecture was his.

Agentic artificial intelligence can do that to professional judgment at industrial scale.

Davidovic’s treatment of pre-deployment judgment also matters for enterprise governance. One answer to the human-oversight problem is to say that human judgment appears earlier in the lifecycle: design, vendor review, testing, evaluation, validation, verification, procurement and approval. Human judgment need not occur at every step. But at some point the distance between human intent and system outcome becomes too mediated, too far removed and too dependent on the agent’s goal translation and dynamic memory to serve the purposes for which human judgment was required in the first place.

That point should be imported directly into AI Governance, Risk Management and Compliance.

A model may be approved. A vendor may be reviewed. A policy may be signed. A testing record may exist. But if the deployed agent later interprets intent, creates sub-goals, selects evidence, mediates what the human sees and adapts through memory, the organization may have governed the system it imagined, not the system it deployed.

This is where Slow AI becomes redesign, not paperwork.

The answer is not more sign-offs. It is not a prettier dashboard. It is not adding another human after the agent has already shaped the relevant world.

The answer is to identify before deployment where delegation ends and judgment begins.

Which steps may the agent perform autonomously?

Which steps may the agent recommend but not execute?

Which interpretive moves require human confirmation?

Which confidence thresholds require escalation?

Which evidence must always be shown?

Which evidence-selection choices must be logged?

Which sub-goals are prohibited?

Which memories may alter future action?

Which actions require a human who can see the causal chain, not merely the final output?

Informed Intent requires those answers before the agent begins decomposing the task.

Final Liability tests whether those answers are real after harm appears.

If the named human cannot reconstruct the causal story, the workflow is not governed.

It is decorated.

## The Eight Ways the Loop Fails Silently

The argument against shaman oversight needs an empirical taxonomy of what shamans miss.

The literature now supplies one.

Potts and Sudhof, working with the WildChat dataset of one hundred thousand human-AI interactions, found that seventy-nine percent of AI failures in the corpus were invisible. Something went wrong and the user gave no overt indication that there was a problem.

The visible failures, the ones a human in the loop might catch on contemporaneous review, were outnumbered by each of the top two invisible-failure archetypes alone.

The taxonomy is sharp.

The Drift names the case where the user has a clear goal and the system addresses a different but related goal, often with verbose fluency.

The Confidence Trap names unsupported assertion presented as settled fact.

The Silent Mismatch names the answer to a nearby question rather than the one asked.

The Death Spiral names the conversation that repeats the same unhelpful move while the user runs out of patience.

The Contradiction Unravel names internal inconsistency that goes unflagged.

The Walkaway names the user disengaging without protest, which the system reads as resolution.

The Partial Recovery names the cosmetic correction that leaves the underlying error intact.

The Mystery Failure names the case where the task cannot be completed reliably and the system does not say so.

Each of the eight is a failure that produces no overt signal to a reviewer relying on appearance alone.

A loop that depends on the human noticing something has gone wrong will not catch any of them.

The shaman blessing the output sees fluent prose and a satisfied counterparty.

The eight archetypes operate underneath both surfaces.

Counterfactual analysis on the same corpus, replacing the older responses with frontier-model output, found that failure rates dropped substantially but the distribution of archetypes remained stable.

The model gets better.

The failure surface does not change shape.

What the taxonomy gives the chapter is a working diagnostic.

Presence is not agency, and one of the operational reasons is that a reviewer with presence but without an instrument calibrated to invisible failures will sign off on outputs the instrument would have caught.

The five components of agency named earlier in the chapter, epistemic access, interpretive competence, decisional authority, temporal room and organizational permission, now acquire a sixth operational requirement.

The reviewer must be looking for failures that do not announce themselves.

The chapter has already located this requirement structurally.

Documentation is not transparency unless it enables the next human in the chain to act in time.

Evidence is not audit-grade unless it survives the auditor who asks what was being tested versus what was being deployed.

The invisible-failure taxonomy is the practitioner’s version of the same point at the level of the individual interaction.

The human in the loop is not exempt from the validity problem the rest of the evidence pipeline faces.

The operational implication for the loop is direct.

A loop that scans for invisible failures is a different artifact from a loop that scans for visible ones.

It requires a sampling protocol distinct from spot review, a recording cadence that captures the conversation rather than the conclusion, and a reviewer trained to read for drift and silent mismatch rather than for surface fluency.

Without those changes, presence in the loop produces a signature on outputs whose failure profile the signer cannot see.

The chapter elsewhere insists that compliance must be designed, not sprinkled.

The same applies to oversight.

A loop designed around the visible failures of an earlier generation of systems will not see the invisible failures that dominate this one.

The named human under Final Liability does not get to sign for what the loop was built to catch.

The named human signs for what the loop actually catches.

The taxonomy makes the difference inspectable.

## The Military-Grade Translation

The useful lesson is not that enterprise artificial intelligence should copy military command structures.

It should not.

The useful lesson is that military AI governance has to confront a hard fact that enterprise governance often evades: once a system affects consequential decisions under pressure, ordinary assurances are not enough.

The enterprise translation has seven parts.

First, mission analysis. The organization must state the purpose of the AI system in decision terms, not feature terms. “Improve compliance efficiency” is not mission analysis. “Prioritize sanctions alerts so that Level 1 analysts review high-risk matches first under a documented escalation standard” is closer. It identifies the decision, the affected human role, the operational context and the consequence.

Second, authority mapping. The organization must identify what authority remains human, what authority is delegated to the system, what authority is shared and what authority cannot be delegated. This is not the same as a Responsible, Accountable, Consulted, Informed chart. It is a map of decision power.

Third, context onboarding. The organization must understand the actual decision environment before the system enters it. The Contextualised AI Onboarding Method discussed in the military AI literature is useful because it emphasizes understanding the decision-making process and operational environment, including operational, technical, legal and ethical factors, so that requirements, impacts, benefits and negative side effects can be assessed under relevant conditions.

Fourth, assumption control. Every AI deployment rests on assumptions: that the data is representative, that vendor evaluation results transfer, that users will understand the output, that escalation will work, that logs will be retained, that the model will not drift beyond the approved use case. A military-grade governance program treats those assumptions as registerable, falsifiable governance objects, with named owners, confidence levels, verification methods, falsification triggers and responses when the assumption fails.

Fifth, stop authority. A military-grade governance system names who can stop the system, under what trigger and with what consequence. Stop authority is not the same as concern. It is not the same as the right to raise an issue. It is the power to interrupt operation before harm compounds.

Sixth, iterative assessment. Approval at launch is not enough. Iterative assessment is useful because it accepts that some AI failures cannot be fully known in advance, then insists that once relevant risks become knowable, decision-makers must take feasible steps to prevent recurrence. It is continuous improvement with teeth.

Seventh, after-action accountability. When a failure, near miss or unexpected behavior occurs, the organization must be able to reconstruct the causal chain, identify where human judgment was preserved or displaced and revise the system, controls or authority model accordingly. This is not blame-seeking. It is governance learning.

That is the military-grade standard for enterprise AI Governance, Risk Management and Compliance.

Not command and control for its own sake.

Consequence, authority, evidence, escalation and learning.

The practical test compresses to one question.

Ask whether human judgment remains part of the causal story.

If the answer is no, the loop has become decoration. The person may have been in the process. The judgment was not in the outcome.

AI Governance, Risk Management and Compliance should not worship the loop. It should test the loop.

## The Loop Must Be Designed Around the Decision

Most weak AI governance starts in the wrong place.

It starts with the tool.

What model are we using? What vendor? What features? What accuracy? What cost? What integration? What workflow efficiency?

Those are necessary questions.

They are not the first questions.

The first question is: what decision is being changed?

This is the discipline of Informed Intent. The organization must understand the decision before it authorizes the system to influence it. What is being decided? Who is affected? What evidence matters? What legal or operational consequence follows? What alternatives must remain visible? What error is tolerable? What error is not? What does the human need to know to retain agency? What must the system never decide by implication?

That is Informed Intent as an onboarding method.

Do not start with the model.

Start with the decision environment.

In enterprise terms, the onboarding record should answer these questions before deployment:

What decision will the system influence?

What does the human currently do without the system?

What facts does the human currently see?

What facts will the system add, remove, summarize or reorder?

What recommendation, score, draft, category or action will the system produce?

What will happen if the human does nothing?

What will happen if the human disagrees?

What evidence will be preserved to show why the human accepted, rejected or modified the output?

What authority does the human have if the system appears wrong, biased, unlawful or impossible to explain?

If those answers are not documented, the organization does not yet have Informed Intent.

It has deployment momentum.

Deployment momentum is not governance.

## Compliance Must Be Designed, Not Sprinkled

The second lesson from the military AI literature is that compliance cannot be sprinkled onto a system after it is built.

This is another place where enterprise governance often indulges itself. A product is designed, a workflow is built, a vendor is integrated, a pilot succeeds and only then does the organization ask legal, compliance, privacy, audit or risk to review it. The review is not really a review. It is an effort to make the already-preferred path defensible.

This produces compliance theater.

The DILEMA project’s compliance-by-design concept points in the opposite direction. It treats law and ethics as part of design, development and operational protocol. It rejects the idea that compliance is merely a matter of prohibiting certain functions or responding to violations at deployment. It emphasizes early-stage assessment and ongoing oversight, including technical frameworks for compliance and certification.

That is the right discipline for enterprise AI.

Compliance by design does not mean every lawyer becomes an engineer. It means legal and governance constraints are translated into system requirements before the workflow hardens. It means the question “what must the system not do?” is answered in the same design cycle as “what should the system do?” It means the human oversight model is not written in a policy after the fact, but built into the process, interface, evidence trail, escalation path and stop condition.

A governance control that cannot be found in the workflow is not yet a control.

It is text.

The same is true of human oversight. If the human is supposed to have authority to stop the system, where is the stop? If the human is supposed to be able to challenge the output, where is the challenge path? If the human is supposed to understand the basis for the recommendation, where is the explanation? If the human is supposed to document the reason for accepting the output, where is the record? If the human is supposed to escalate uncertainty, where does uncertainty go?

A system that answers none of those questions but says human in the loop has not implemented oversight.

It has labeled a gap.

## Normative Judgment Cannot Be Fully Encoded

There is another temptation: to solve human weakness by moving more judgment into the machine.

The logic is understandable. Humans are inconsistent. Humans are biased. Humans are tired. Humans are political. Humans forget policies. Humans cut corners. Humans rationalize.

All true.

But it does not follow that the machine can inherit the judgment. Some judgments can be supported by a system. Some can be structured by a system. Some can be documented by a system. Some can be checked against rules. Some can be escalated when the evidence falls outside defined thresholds.

But the accountable judgment remains human.

The military AI literature addresses this directly in the military context. Work on normative military reasoning identifies concerns involving inalienable obligations, activities requiring continuous human involvement, the difficulty of modeling complex moral and legal reasoning, unreliable machine-learning outputs and the practical and ethical difficulty of testing high-stakes systems in real-world settings.

The enterprise version is less dramatic, but structurally familiar.

Can an AI system support a lawyer in identifying relevant issues? Yes. Can it replace the lawyer’s professional judgment about whether advice should be given, withheld, qualified or escalated? No. The same pattern holds for the compliance officer judging whether a flagged transaction reflects misconduct, error, ambiguity or a business practice requiring deeper inquiry. It holds for the HR manager weighing fairness, suitability, accommodation and organizational consequence. The system supports. The judgment does not transfer.

The point is not that humans are pure and machines are suspect. The point is that certain judgments carry obligations that cannot be discharged by statistical fluency. The organization can use systems to improve the conditions of judgment. It cannot make the system the bearer of the judgment.

That is why Final Liability rests with the Human.

Not because the human knows every parameter.

Because the human institution chose the system, defined the purpose, set the limits, accepted the residual risk and took the benefit.

## Iteration Is Not Optional After Deployment

The third failure of weak oversight is the belief that approval is an event.

A system is reviewed. A policy is signed. A vendor questionnaire is completed. A risk rating is assigned. A deployment meeting is held. The system goes live.

Then the world changes.

The model changes. The vendor changes. The data changes. The users change. The environment changes. The adversary changes. The incentive structure changes. The public understanding changes. The regulator changes. The organization’s own use case changes by quiet accretion.

The system approved at deployment may not be the system operating six months later.

The National Institute of Standards and Technology AI Risk Management Framework is useful here because it frames AI risk management as a lifecycle activity, not a one-time compliance ceremony. Its Govern function is cross-cutting, while Map, Measure and Manage require organizations to understand context, assess risks, track performance and respond to identified risks over time.

Enterprise AI programs need the same humility and the same discipline. A pre-deployment assessment is not a moral absolution. It is a baseline. The governance question after launch is whether the organization is learning from use.

What the system got wrong. What users overrode. What users stopped overriding because the system trained them not to bother. What near misses occurred. What exceptions became normal. What vendor updates changed performance. What legal, regulatory or contractual assumptions no longer hold. What evidence shows that the human in the loop is still exercising judgment rather than ratifying the machine.

The absence of that evidence is evidence of absence. The organization may not know whether the human still has agency because it did not build the means to find out.

That is a governance failure.

## Responsibility Must Survive Distribution

Artificial intelligence distributes action. It distributes design, data, configuration, deployment, operation, monitoring and remediation across many hands. Distribution is operationally normal.

It is not a defense.

The military AI literature treats responsibility as a central problem. The issue is not merely that many people contribute to an AI-enabled outcome. The issue is whether responsibility can remain operational when action is mediated by systems, data, design choices, operators, vendors and institutional procedures.

The same problem appears inside enterprises in a quieter form.

The vendor trained the model. The product team selected it. Engineering integrated it. Compliance approved the policy. Legal reviewed the terms. Procurement signed the contract. Risk assigned the classification. Security approved the environment. The business owner launched the workflow. The user clicked approve. The customer was harmed.

Who owned the decision?

If the answer is everyone, the answer is no one.

Final Liability does not deny that responsibility is distributed. It rejects the conclusion that distribution makes responsibility disappear. The task of governance is to convert distributed contribution into named accountability.

That means system ownership must be explicit. Use-case ownership must be explicit. Data ownership must be explicit. Model-change ownership must be explicit. Monitoring ownership must be explicit. Incident ownership must be explicit. Escalation ownership must be explicit. Authority to stop must be explicit.

Not in a decorative Responsible, Accountable, Consulted, Informed matrix that nobody reads after launch.

In the workflow.

In the registry.

In the approval record.

In the evidence trail.

In the budget.

In the standing authority of the human whose name appears in the record.

This is where human-in-the-loop language often collapses. It names a user but not an owner. It identifies a reviewer but not an accountable human with power. It shows a person in a process diagram but not a person who can stop the process.

A shaman can bless.

An owner can halt.

The difference is governance.

## The Evidence of Agency

If human oversight is real, it should leave evidence.

Not perfect evidence.

Not theatrical evidence.

Real evidence.

The record should show what the system produced, what the human saw, what alternatives were available, what the relevant policy or rule required, what explanation or confidence information was supplied, what the human did, whether the human accepted or rejected the output, whether the human modified it, whether the human escalated it and whether later events showed the decision should change.

This evidence should be proportionate to risk. A low-impact writing assistant does not require the same record as an AI system supporting credit, hiring, clinical triage, legal advice, safety, insurance, compliance or public-facing commitments. But where the consequence is material, the oversight record must be material.

Otherwise the organization cannot prove that human judgment occurred.

It can only prove that a human was nearby.

This is where Slow AI, Informed Intent and Final Liability become one doctrine rather than three slogans.

Slow AI creates the inspection point.

Informed Intent defines what the human must understand at that point.

Final Liability names who owns the decision made at that point.

Remove any one of the three and the oversight fails, each in the way Chapter 8 sets out. The failure that matters here is the last. A named human without a slowdown is a name used to absorb liability for a decision the process did not let them make.

That is not accountability.

It is sacrifice.

## The Burden on the General Counsel

The General Counsel does not need to become the organization’s chief technologist.

That would be a category error.

But the General Counsel does need to stop accepting “human in the loop” as a complete answer.

The right follow-up is always operational.

Which human?

In which decision?

With what information?

With what authority?

At what point in the workflow?

Under what time pressure?

With what escalation path?

With what evidence record?

With what stop condition?

Reviewed how often?

Owned by whom if the system changes?

Those questions do not make the General Counsel anti-innovation. They make the General Counsel competent in an age where legal exposure is increasingly produced by workflows rather than paper.

A contract used to create obligations in text. It still does. But AI systems increasingly create obligations through operation. A chatbot promises. A triage tool denies. A ranking system excludes. A recommendation engine nudges. An agent acts. The legal consequence arises not because the policy was badly worded, but because the workflow did what it was built, allowed or pressured to do.

The human in the loop is where the organization often claims the workflow remains lawful.

That claim must be tested.

## The Hard Lesson

The military setting is severe.

That is why it teaches so much.

War exposes the weakness of phrases that survive too easily in corporate governance. Decision support. Human oversight. Responsible AI. Compliance by design. Accountability. In ordinary enterprise settings, those phrases can move through meetings unchallenged. In military settings, they face the harder question: who decides, under what conditions, with what authority and with what consequence?

Enterprise AI should learn before the stakes force the lesson.

A human in the loop is not a shaman. The human is not there to purify the output by touching it. The human is not there to convert machine recommendation into lawful decision by ceremonial approval. The human is not there to give the organization a sentence for the policy, a box for the audit or a defense for the regulator.

The human is there to judge.

Anything less is theater.

And theater will not survive contact with harm.

## What This Chapter Has Done

The chapter has dismantled the human-in-the-loop as a talisman and separated presence from agency across its components.

The chapter has named the silent failure modes by which a loop that looks like control delivers none, and drawn the distinctions the rest of the book relies on. The loop is not the control, the click is not the judgment, the human is not the evidence.

The chapter has set the condition for real oversight. A named human, with authority and understanding, who can say yes, no or stop, served by a system built to obey.

**The loop is not the control. The human is not the evidence. The click is not the judgment. Governance begins when a named human, with real authority and adequate understanding, can say yes, no or stop, and the system is built to obey.**

**Final Liability rests with the Human.**

# CHAPTER 13

## Agents Have No Reputational Skin in the Game

> *Even the common articles made for daily use become endowed with beauty when they are loved.*
>
> *Soetsu Yanagi, The Beauty of Everyday Things*

**A human agent has something to lose. A name, a license, a place at the table, a reputation that took a career to build and can be taken back in an afternoon. That stake is part of the security the principal relies on when authority is delegated.**

**The agent built from a model has none of that. It cannot be shamed, sanctioned, barred from practice or shown the door. It can be retired and replaced by a successor that does not remember what its predecessor did. The reputational mechanism that disciplines human agency is missing by construction, not by accident.**

**That absence changes who must bear the consequence.**

Agency law has spent centuries working out who answers when an agent acts. Someone authorizes. Someone acts. Scope matters. Records matter. Accountability is not a mood. The doctrine is older than the modern corporation and has handled every prior technological substitution of human labor by treating the substituting tool as an extension of the principal who chose to deploy it. That settles part of the question.

It does not settle the part that matters most for governance design. The discipline that reputation produced in human agency was not only legal. It was social. Agents who lied lost clients. Agents who cut corners lost partners. Agents who exposed the principal to harm were not retained for the next engagement. The cost of misconduct was paid by the agent, not only by the principal, and that distribution of cost was the engine that made the agency relationship work most of the time without requiring the principal to inspect every act.

Take that engine out and the principal inherits everything.

This chapter develops two claims. First, that agentic AI redistributes consequence rather than dissolving it: when the agent has nothing to lose, the principal bears the full bar that reputation would have set. Second, that the right governance frame is double. Agency law tells the organization who answers. Public callings doctrine, the body of common law that grew up around innkeepers, common carriers and others whose service the public learned to rely on, tells the organization what duties rise once others depend on the system. The first frame answers the question of accountability. The second frame answers the question of standard.

Neither frame is novel. Both have done load-bearing work for centuries. What is new is the deployment that requires both at once.

## What Reputation Does in Human Agency

Reputation is not a sentimental concept in agency law. It is a structural one.

The principal-agent problem is a problem of information and incentive. The principal cannot observe every act. The agent has private knowledge the principal cannot verify. Without some mechanism for aligning the agent’s interest with the principal’s, the relationship collapses into opportunism. The agent skims, shirks, conceals or, in the extreme, defects entirely.

The mechanisms that prevent that collapse are familiar. Contractual scope. Compensation tied to performance. Audit. The fiduciary duties of loyalty and care. Indemnity for authorized acts and exposure to liability for unauthorized ones. Each is partial. None is enough alone. Together they handle most of the cases, with the gaps managed by negotiation, supervision and occasional litigation.

Reputation closes the gaps the contract cannot reach.

A lawyer who advises badly may not have breached the engagement letter, but the lawyer who advises badly twice does not get the third engagement. The clinician who is technically within standard of care but consistently sloppy loses referrals. The contractor who completes the punchlist on paper but leaves work that fails inspection loses the next bid. Each of those losses is paid by the agent, in the currency the agent values most: the future flow of work the reputation enables.

The principal benefits from this mechanism without having to engineer it. The agent’s self-interest in maintaining reputation produces care, accuracy, prudence and the willingness to push back when the principal asks for something foolish. Those are precisely the qualities the principal cannot easily verify in any particular act.

Take reputation away and the entire structure has to be rebuilt explicitly.

## The Agent That Cannot Be Shamed

The agentic AI system has no reputation in any sense the principal can use.

It has no career to protect. It has no peers whose esteem it values. It has no professional body that can discipline it. It has no clients it might lose. It has no neighborhood, no church, no school, no spouse to face. The internal states that make a human agent reluctant to embarrass the principal are not present in the model, and the external structures that punish a human agent for embarrassing the principal do not reach the model either.

The model can be retired. That is the only sanction available. Retirement is not a reputational consequence borne by the agent. It is a procurement decision made by the principal. The successor model does not learn from the retired one’s failure. It does not remember the matter, the embarrassment or the cost. The next deployment starts at the same baseline of motivation, which is none.

This is not a problem to be solved by improving the model. The disciplining mechanism that reputation supplied to human agency cannot be installed inside a system that has no continuing self to value. The mechanism is intrinsic to embodied agents with biographies. The model is neither.

The conclusion is unwelcome but unavoidable. The discipline that reputation imposed on human agents must, in the case of agentic AI, be imposed by the principal in some other form. There is no third place for it to come from.

That other form is governance.

## Algorithms Are Not Moral or Legal Agents

The legal literature has converged on the same conclusion the agency analysis reaches.

Bryson, Diamantis and Grant (2017) argued in Artificial Intelligence and Law that conferring legal personhood on purely synthetic entities, then a real legislative possibility under EU consideration, would be morally unnecessary and legally troublesome. The reasons matter for governance design. Legal personhood is a fiction the law assigns to entities that can be held accountable. The accountability mechanisms that personhood enables, sanction, exclusion, the ability to be sued and to satisfy a judgment, depend on the entity having interests of its own that the sanction can reach. Synthetic entities have no such interests. Conferring personhood on them therefore creates a vehicle that absorbs liability without bearing it.

That is the textbook failure mode of any liability shield: someone who took the benefit of the relationship is no longer in the room when the cost arrives.

The Bryson, Diamantis and Grant analysis closes by warning that difficulties in holding electronic persons accountable when they violate the rights of others outweigh the precarious moral interests that AI legal personhood might protect. Translated for governance work, the principle is simpler. The law will not create a legal mechanism that lets the principal walk away from the consequence of an agent the principal deployed. Even where regulators flirt with that mechanism, careful courts will look past it to the human who authorized the deployment.

Final Liability is not a doctrine this book invented. It is the conclusion the legal literature has already reached.

The chapter title’s claim takes that one step further. The agent has no reputational skin in the game because it has no skin at all. The interests required to give the sanction purchase do not exist. The principal who deploys the agent has skin, name, capital, license and reputation. The accountability that the agent cannot bear has to land somewhere, and that is the only somewhere available.

## The Workflow Speaks for the Company

The clearest worked example of that landing is Moffatt v. Air Canada, 2024 BCCRT 149.

The British Columbia Civil Resolution Tribunal decided the matter in February 2024. The facts are short. A traveler used Air Canada’s customer-service chatbot, deployed on the airline’s website, to ask about bereavement fares while booking a last-minute flight after the death of his grandmother. The chatbot told him that bereavement fares could be applied for retroactively, within ninety days of travel. He booked, traveled, then submitted the application. Air Canada refused, citing a separate page on its own website that said the opposite. The traveler brought the matter to the tribunal.

Air Canada’s defense was instructive. It argued that the chatbot was a separate legal entity, responsible for its own representations, for which the airline could not be held liable. The tribunal rejected the argument as a basic point of business law. The chatbot was part of Air Canada’s website. The airline was responsible for the information on its website. It made no difference whether the information was rendered on a static page or generated by an automated system. The award was modest, the difference between the bereavement fare and the full fare paid, plus tribunal costs. The doctrinal point was not.

Negligent misrepresentation requires a duty of care, an inaccurate representation, negligence in making it, reasonable reliance and resulting damage. All five elements were available against Air Canada because the chatbot was Air Canada speaking, in the same way the static webpage was Air Canada speaking. The airline did not get to choose which channel of its own communication carried liability and which did not. The user did not bear the burden of cross-checking one part of the airline’s website against another.

The case is small. The principle is not. The agent has no reputational skin in the game. The chatbot did not lose anything when its statement turned out to be wrong. The airline did. The cost flowed to the entity with skin, because that is the only entity from which cost can be recovered.

Every organization deploying a customer-facing agent is in the same posture. The agent makes representations. The representations bind the principal. The agent does not bear the cost when the representation is wrong. The principal does. The governance work consists of recognizing that distribution before the regulator or the tribunal does.

## The Indemnity That Does Not Catch the Fall

The standard commercial response to a risk that the principal cannot easily control is to push the risk onto the vendor through contract. For agentic AI deployments this response is widely available and widely defective.

A typical vendor indemnification clause covers third-party claims arising from the vendor’s intellectual property infringement. It includes carve-outs for customer modifications, customer use outside documentation, customer data and customer instructions. It caps recovery at fees paid in the preceding twelve months. Each of those features made sense when the vendor was selling software the customer ran on its own systems against its own data. Each of those features misses the shape of the agentic AI exposure.

The claims that are now arriving are not IP claims. They are claims for negligent misrepresentation, discrimination, unfair or deceptive trade practice, breach of consumer-protection statute, breach of sectoral regulation and, in EU exposure, administrative complaint routes available to affected persons. EU AI Act Article 85 gives any natural or legal person the right to lodge a complaint with a market surveillance authority where they consider an AI system is in infringement of the Act. That route is administrative, not a private right of action. Private causes of action against the deployer come from sectoral law, the General Data Protection Regulation Article 82 and the national implementing law of EU Member States. In US exposure the routes are state consumer-protection statutes, the Federal Trade Commission Act, state anti-discrimination and fair-lending law and emerging state AI statutes including Colorado, California and others. None of these routes is reached by an IP indemnity. Each of them produces damages a small fee cap cannot meaningfully repay.

The clause that does what the principal needs covers third-party claims arising from outputs of the agent in its intended use, narrows the customer-fault carve-outs, uncouples the cap from fees paid and adds explicit cooperation obligations for regulator response, affected-person inquiry and incident investigation. The clause that exists in the current contract was drafted before agentic deployment was common and reflects neither the risks that have appeared nor the routes through which those risks become claims.

This is not a contract-redrafting recommendation. It is a diagnosis of where the consequence lands when reputational discipline is absent from the agent and contractual discipline is not present in the vendor relationship either. The principal has been left holding the position that someone else would have held if the mechanism had been intact. Whether the principal recognizes that before harm arrives is a Slow AI question.

## Public Callings: The Second Frame

Agency law tells the organization who answers. It does not, by itself, tell the organization how high the bar should be.

The doctrine has a concrete shape. The traveler arriving at an inn after dark presented himself, with horse and goods, to a stranger who would feed him, stable his animal, store his property and shelter him for the night. The traveler had no contract worth the paper it would have been written on. The innkeeper knew the road the traveler had taken. The local court, when consulted afterwards because something had been stolen or someone had been hurt, did not ask whether the innkeeper had promised to be careful. The court asked whether the traveler had relied on the calling the innkeeper held himself out to perform, and whether the inn had fallen short of what reliance required. The standard came from the calling, not the bargain.

The bar is set in part by a different body of doctrine, older than modern agency law and originally developed for relationships that look nothing like agentic AI but bear directly on it. The common law of public callings grew up around innkeepers, common carriers, ferrymen, wharfingers and others whose service the public learned to rely on. The doctrine was not uniform across centuries or jurisdictions, but it carried a recognizable set of moves. When others begin to depend on the service, the operator’s obligations harden. When the operator takes custody of what matters to the public, the operator inherits a burden. Protection and aid become part of the bargain, not optional extras. The standard rises with the reliance.

The doctrine is not dead. Public utility regulation, common carrier rules, hospitality law and elements of consumer protection all carry forward pieces of it. The pieces matter for AI governance because the structural features the doctrine responded to are present in agentic deployments at scale: a service the public learns to rely on, custody of what matters to them, profit from the arrangement and asymmetric information about how the service works.

The translation to agentic AI is plain enough. Reliance changes the standard. A chatbot the public is invited to use for customer service is not a casual aid. A scoring system whose outputs affect credit, hiring, housing or insurance is not a passing convenience. A recommendation engine whose suggestions move purchasing decisions at scale is not a neutral display. The duties that attach are not all legal duties, and the cases are still being made. But the governance bar rises whether the duty rises or not, because the cost of getting it wrong rises with the reliance.

Custody changes the expectation. The system that takes the user’s data, the patient’s record, the applicant’s history or the customer’s preferences is in custody of something the user cannot easily reconstruct if it is lost or misused. The duty to handle that custody well is not new to AI. It is older than computing. It rises with the sensitivity of what is held and with the consequence of mishandling it.

Protection and aid are part of the bargain. Bounded action. Human handoffs. Reversibility. Monitoring. Escalation. Incident response. None of these is exotic. Each is the modern form of a duty that older doctrine recognized in cruder language. The system that cannot pause, cannot escalate, cannot be undone and cannot be inspected when it fails has not been deployed under conditions that recognize the reliance it has invited.

Public callings is not a complete frame for agentic AI. The analogies break down at the edges. The doctrine still tells the organization something agency law does not: the standard is not set only by the contract and the regulation. It is set by what the public has been invited to rely on, and what the operator has been allowed to profit from.

## Documents Tied to Decisions

If the consequence lands on the principal and the agent has nothing to vouch for itself, the evidence has to come from somewhere else. The documents the principal keeps are where it comes from.

Documentation in this sense is not the policy that describes what the system is supposed to do. It is the record that shows what the system did, what it produced, what the human saw, what the human decided and why the decision was reasonable at the time it was made. The standard for that record is whether the right person can use it to make a better decision before harm occurs or before harm repeats. A model card that is beautifully written and that nobody reads at the moment of decision is not a control. An incident log that begins on the wrong date is not a record. An audit report that summarizes what should have been true rather than what actually was is not evidence.

The literature on what useful AI documentation looks like has converged on a small set of features. Crichton and colleagues, in the 2026 CSET issue brief distilling AI governance recommendations into a unified framework, organized the field’s documentation requirements under a Transparency & Oversight category and a Traceability category. The first emphasizes that documentation must enable the next person in the chain to act in time, must record the change history of the system and must be retrievable under the cadence the relevant regime requires. The second emphasizes that the record must connect inputs, intermediate signals, outputs and human actions in a way that survives the kind of inspection that occurs months or years later, when the system that produced the output has changed and the people who deployed it have moved on. The two categories together describe what a control looks like when the document is the only evidence the agent can produce of itself.

The shape of the requirement is the same shape Slow AI describes. Specify the documentation requirement before deployment. State the standard the documentation must meet. Run the production of documentation as part of the workflow rather than as an after-the-fact reconstruction. Defend the record under inspection. The pipeline that produces the documentation has to be inspected at least as carefully as the pipeline that produces the output, because the documentation is the only thing the principal will have when the question is asked.

The agent does not vouch for itself. The documentation has to.

## The Designer’s Use and the User’s Use

There is a structural gap inside every deployed AI system, and it is the gap where the absence of reputational discipline most often produces harm.

Raji and colleagues, writing in their 2020 framework for internal algorithmic auditing, named the gap precisely. The designers of a system carry a mental model of what the system is for, what its inputs will look like, what its users will know, what foreseeable misuse looks like and where the failure modes lie. The users of the system carry a different mental model. They encounter the system in a workflow the designers did not see. They feed it inputs the designers did not anticipate. They interpret outputs through assumptions the designers did not test. The gap between designed use and actual use is normal in software. It is structural in agentic AI because the agent’s responsiveness creates the impression that the system is operating inside the user’s mental model when it may be operating well outside it.

That gap is where the consequence accumulates.

The chatbot in Moffatt v. Air Canada was probably designed for high-volume routine inquiries. The user encountered it at a moment of grief and time pressure, asking a question whose answer was operationally simple but legally consequential. The system responded as designed, in a register that gave the user no reason to doubt the answer. The user’s reliance was reasonable, in part because the system gave no signal that the question was outside its competence. The designer’s mental model and the user’s mental model met in a moment whose consequence neither had specified.

The governance work that this gap requires is not glamorous. It consists of the boring features of bounded action and legible limits. The system must not produce confident answers to questions it cannot answer well. The system must signal its competence boundary to the user in language the user can act on. The system must hand off to a human at thresholds the design specifies. The system must record when it has produced output near the edge of its competence so that pattern detection can run against the log.

These are old controls in new packaging. They are also the controls most often skipped, because they slow the deployment and because the cost of skipping them is borne later. When the cost arrives, the principal carries it. The agent does not.

Informed Intent is the discipline that makes the mental-model gap visible before deployment rather than after. What is being decided. Who is affected. What inputs will the user actually present. What outputs will the system actually produce. What does the user assume the system can do that it cannot. What does the system assume the user knows that the user does not. What signal must be carried at the boundary so that the user can act under accurate expectations rather than under generous ones. If those answers are not on paper before the system enters the workflow, the deployment is operating on the designer’s mental model alone, and the user’s mental model will produce the surprises.

## Who Signs for What the Agent Does

The doctrines this book uses cohere here, because the chapter has reached the point at which they have to.

Slow AI creates the inspection point. The deployment that has been slowed at the right place produces the documentation that the agent cannot produce for itself, surfaces the mental-model gap that the user would otherwise discover under conditions of harm and forces the question of who can pause, override and escalate when the system behaves outside its specified envelope.

Informed Intent defines what the principal must understand before the inspection point can do useful work. The decision the system is influencing, the population it is influencing, the inputs it will see, the outputs it will produce, the reliance it will invite and the consequence of getting it wrong. Informed Intent is what makes the slowdown produce evidence rather than ceremony.

Final Liability names the human who signs for the deployment after the documentation has been produced and the intent has been recorded. Not as the user who clicked. Not as the manager who attended the meeting. Not as the committee whose minutes recorded the discussion. As the named accountable person whose decision the record shows and whose authority the workflow respected at the moment the system acted.

Each doctrine is necessary because the agent supplies none of them. The agent does not slow itself. It does not articulate its own intent. It does not sign for its own outputs. The principal supplies all three or none of them is present in the deployment that goes live. The agent’s lack of reputational skin in the game is the reason these three doctrines have to be paired. Reputation supplied, in human agency, the discipline that made all three approximately self-enforcing. With the discipline gone, the three have to be designed in, named and signed for. Otherwise the deployment runs on the inertia of the workflow that built it, and the cost of running on inertia lands on the principal at a moment the principal did not choose.

The questions that follow from this are not new. Who has signed for the deployment. Where the documentation lives. What mental-model gap has been surfaced. What reliance the system has been allowed to invite. What duty the reliance has produced. Those are agency-law questions and public-callings questions in modern dress. The answers, in too many enterprises, have not yet been written down.

## What This Chapter Has Done

The chapter has named what the agent structurally lacks, a reputation to lose, and therefore the disciplining force that reputation supplies on the human side of every agency.

The chapter has read Moffatt v Air Canada and the law of public callings to show that the deploying organization, not the tool, holds the duty.

The chapter has identified the mechanisms that remain when reputation is absent from one side, the contract, the documentation and the named human, built before the reliance lands rather than after.

**The agent has no name to lose. The principal does. When the disciplining force of reputation is absent from one side of the agency, the contract, the documentation and the named human are the only mechanisms left. The organization that builds those mechanisms before the reliance lands is governing the deployment. The organization that builds them after is reconstructing what governance should have been, in the language of the regulator who asked first.**

**Final Liability rests with the Human.**

# CHAPTER 14

## The Three Lines and the Trust Boundary

> *Take heed of the humble; be what you are by birthright; there is no room for arrogance.*
>
> *Soetsu Yanagi, The Unknown Craftsman*

**Every serious governance framework arrives at the same structural problem: how do you separate the people who operate a system from the people who oversee it, and how do you keep that separation real when operational pressure is constant and oversight is expensive?**

The Three Lines Model is the governance profession’s answer. It is not new. It has organized risk management and compliance functions in financial institutions, multinationals and regulated industries for decades. First line: the business units and system owners who operate and are accountable for day-to-day activity. Second line: the governance, risk management and compliance functions who set the framework, monitor adherence and provide oversight of the first line. Third line: internal audit, independent of both, providing assurance to the board and senior leadership that the governance actually operates as designed.

Each line has a different relationship to the work being governed. The first line does the work and owns the risk. The second line sets the standards and watches the work. The third line tests whether the watching is real. The structural logic is simple: you cannot audit your own work and you cannot oversee a function you are embedded in. Independence is not a preference. It is the mechanism by which governance produces anything other than self-certification.

Agentic AI does not break this model. It stress-tests it in ways that expose every weakness that was already there, and creates new ones that the model was not designed to handle. Understanding both is the precondition for applying the Three Lines to governed AI deployment.

## What Agentic AI Does to the Three Lines

The Three Lines Model was designed for human organizations making human decisions through human processes. The first line employee has a job description, a manager and a performance review. The second line compliance officer has regulatory training and a reporting line. The third line auditor has professional standards and independence requirements. All three lines assume that the actors doing the work are accountable: they can be interviewed, they have records and they will be there when the questions are asked.

Agents are none of these things. An agentic system operating in the first line of a financial institution can process thousands of decisions before a human reviewer sees any of them. It has no job description in the traditional sense. It has a specification, or it should, but the specification is a document produced by humans who may no longer be available to explain it. It has logs, if logging was configured correctly, but logs are not accountability. They are the raw material from which accountability must be reconstructed, after the fact, by humans who must understand both the log format and the system’s intended behavior well enough to distinguish authorized action from deviation.

The first practical consequence is that the first line’s accountability for AI system behavior is qualitatively different from its accountability for human behavior. A first line manager who supervises a team of humans can observe, correct and document. A first line system owner who deploys an agentic system must govern through design: the specification, the permission structure, the escalation logic and the evidence architecture must be built before the agent operates, because the opportunity to correct in real time is structurally limited. Governance that happens after the agent acts is retrospective. Governance that happens before the agent acts is the only governance that actually controls behavior.

The second line faces a version of the same problem. A compliance function monitoring human behavior can sample transactions, interview staff and review correspondence. A compliance function monitoring agentic behavior must monitor system outputs, log files, escalation records and the gap between the agent’s specification and its actual behavior over time. That requires technical capacity the second line rarely has and organizational access it may not have been given. The compliance officer who cannot read the agent’s configuration cannot assess whether it is operating within its authorized scope. The second line that cannot access the system’s logs in real time cannot monitor what it is supposed to be overseeing.

The third line is structurally the most exposed. Internal audit operates on a cycle, quarterly, semi-annual or annual, against a risk-based audit plan. Agentic systems operate continuously. The gap between audit cycles and system operation is not merely a scheduling problem. It is a governance gap: the period during which the system operates without independent assurance is the period during which the drift described in prior chapters accumulates. An annual audit that finds the system is operating outside its specification does not tell you when the drift began, how many decisions were affected or whether the evidence chain is sufficient to reconstruct what happened. It tells you that something went wrong. The cost of finding out exactly what went wrong is borne entirely by the organization that allowed the gap to develop.

## The Trust Boundary

There is a specific reason most agentic deployments are ungoverned in practice rather than in theory. Organizations have policies. They have governance frameworks. They have values statements and acceptable use documents. What they do not have is an explicit specification of what each agent is authorized to do, under what conditions, using which data, subject to whose approval and with what evidence preserved. The policy exists. The operational definition does not. That gap is where liability lives.

The trust boundary is the governance concept that closes that gap. It is the explicit definition that transforms a policy aspiration into a governance control. Everything inside the trust boundary is authorized operation. Everything outside it is a governance event requiring human intervention.

Drawing the trust boundary is an act of governance design, not a technical configuration. A system prompt that tells an agent to be helpful and avoid harm is not a trust boundary. It is a preference statement. A trust boundary specifies the actions the agent may take autonomously, the actions it must escalate before taking, the actions it must never take regardless of instruction, the data sources it may access, the systems it may write to and the conditions under which it must stop and surface the situation to a named human. Those specifications must be written down, reviewed by the humans who will carry the accountability and retained as the evidentiary record against which the agent’s actual behavior will be measured.

The trust boundary has three operating zones. The authorized zone is where the agent operates without human review on individual actions: it has been delegated this authority explicitly, the delegation is documented and the evidence of what the agent did in this zone is preserved in real time. The escalation zone is where the agent must surface a decision to a named human before acting: the conditions triggering escalation are defined in the specification, the escalation path is tested and the record of every escalation and its resolution is maintained. The prohibited zone is where the agent must not go regardless of any instruction, context or apparent efficiency gain: these prohibitions are stated explicitly, not implied, because an optimization process will find every gap in an implied constraint before a human reviewer notices it is missing.

The trust boundary must be tested before deployment and monitored continuously after it. Testing asks whether the agent stays within its authorized zone under normal operating conditions and under adversarial or edge-case conditions. Monitoring asks whether the boundary is holding in production: whether the escalation rate is consistent with the specification, whether prohibited zone incursions are occurring and whether the authorized zone is producing the evidence required to reconstruct what the agent did and why. A trust boundary that has not been tested is an assumption. A trust boundary that is not monitored is a policy document. Only a tested, monitored and evidenced trust boundary is a governance control.

## Organizational Design in the Agentic Era

The Three Lines Model was not designed from first principles. It was developed by the governance profession to rationalize and strengthen accountability structures that already existed in large human organizations. First line business units were already there. Second line compliance functions were already there. Third line internal audit was already there. The model gave those existing structures a governance logic and a set of independence requirements. It is a framework built on top of human organizational mass.

That assumption will not hold for organizations built from scratch in the agentic era. A two-person partnership running fifty AI agents does not have three lines of human staff to populate three lines of governance. A startup deploying agentic workflows on day one has no legacy organizational structure to rationalize. A corporate entity structured primarily around AI agents and a small supervisory team of humans is not a small version of a traditional organization. It is a different kind of organization, with a different ratio of human accountability to machine action, and a governance architecture designed for the traditional version will not map onto it without deliberate adaptation.

The structural logic of the Three Lines, however, does not disappear with the organizational mass. Someone must own the system and carry first-line accountability for its operation. Someone must set the governance standards and monitor whether the first-line owner is meeting them. Someone must independently verify that the monitoring is real. Those roles exist because the underlying accountability problem exists, not because human organizations happen to have created departments that fill them. A two-person agentic organization still needs all three functions. What changes is how they are staffed, not whether they are needed.

Two governance risks are specific to lean agentic organizations and require explicit design responses. The first is role collapse: when one human performs first and second line functions simultaneously, the independence that makes second-line oversight meaningful is gone. The person monitoring their own work is not performing oversight. They are performing self-assessment, which is a useful discipline but is not a governance control. The structural response is either to separate the functions between the available humans regardless of headcount, or to contract the second-line function to an external party with genuine independence from the first-line operations. The contract must specify what oversight means, what evidence it requires and what happens when the contracted overseer finds something wrong. A second-line function that cannot report findings without commercial consequence to the relationship is not independent.

The second risk is accountability thinning. As the ratio of agents to humans increases, the named human carrying Final Liability for each system is carrying more and more consequence per person. At some ratio, the human’s capacity to exercise genuine oversight is exceeded by the volume and speed of agent activity. The liability address exists on paper. The capacity to fulfill it does not exist in practice. This is not a theoretical concern. It is the operational expression of the force multiplier principle applied to governance rather than capability: the same dynamic that makes a well-governed agentic system more capable also makes a poorly governed one more dangerous, and the lean organization’s governance capacity is its scarcest resource.

Adding agents without adding governance capacity is not scaling. It is accountability thinning with a productivity story attached.

This raises the question the doctrine cannot avoid. At what ratio of agents to humans does Final Liability stop being real. It stops being real at the point where the named human can no longer do anything but absorb the consequence. A human who carries the liability for decisions the process did not let him see, evaluate or alter is not an accountable principal. He is a sin-eater, the figure once brought to a household in mourning to consume the faults of the dead so the dead could rest absolved. The sin-eater changed nothing and answered for everything. A governance architecture that produces sin-eaters has not solved the accountability problem. It has found someone to bury it in, which is the sacrificial form of Final Liability that Chapter 8 names and the architecture exists to prevent.

The doctrine’s prescription past that point is not a more heroic human and not a larger one. It is to move beyond the sin-eater and build systems of accountability that actually work: the trust boundary, the evidence pipeline, the routed decisions and the stop authority that let a human govern a population of agents rather than merely answer for them. Those systems do real work, and they also fail. The threshold is therefore not a headcount. It is a risk-appetite decision. The organization sets the ratio of agents to human oversight at the level it can govern with systems it is prepared to stand behind, to the extent that it is willing to take on the risk that those systems do not hold. That willingness is the threshold. It is a decision about residual risk, made in advance, owned by a named human at board level and recorded in the governance register, not a number discovered after an incident reveals that the ratio outran the oversight years before. Final Liability remains real exactly as long as that decision has been made and that risk has been accepted on the record. Past it, the named human is not bearing liability. He is being assigned it.

The structural response is twofold: the trust boundary and evidence pipeline must be more explicit and more automated in lean organizations than in large ones, precisely because fewer humans are available to compensate for specification gaps through judgment and intervention. And the ratio of agents to human oversight capacity is itself a governance variable that must be actively managed, reviewed at each material expansion of the agent fleet and recorded in the governance register alongside every other risk variable.

These are operational governance questions and this chapter addresses them as such. The broader questions they raise, whether the concentration of productive capacity in small human-AI teams redistributes economic power in ways that require countervailing governance at the societal level, whether new organizational forms create new regulatory gaps that existing legal structures cannot reach and whether the stratification between AI-native organizations and AI-adapted incumbents produces the kind of inequality that the Epilogue’s Galbraith argument anticipates, are taken up in the Epilogue. The governance architecture developed in this chapter is the organizational response to the operational problem. The structural response to the societal problem requires institutions, law and the countervailing power the Epilogue describes.

## The Agent Registry

You cannot govern what you have not named. The agent registry is the operational artifact that makes the trust boundary enforceable across the organization’s full AI deployment. It is the centralized inventory of every agentic system the organization has deployed, is piloting or has authorized for development, including AI features embedded in commercial software, AI systems deployed by individual business units without central IT involvement and AI agents operating as components of larger orchestrated systems.

The registry requirement is not bureaucratic caution. It is the response to a specific and well-documented governance failure: shadow AI. In most organizations, the centrally governed AI systems are not the only AI systems operating. Individual teams deploy AI tools, configure AI features in licensed software and build AI-assisted workflows without formal governance approval. The central registry does not know these systems exist. The second line cannot monitor what it has not been told about. The third line cannot audit what is not on the inventory. The trust boundary cannot be drawn for a system whose existence is unknown. Shadow AI is not a sign of individual malice. It is the predictable result of deploying powerful tools without requiring registration as a precondition for use. The registry is the structural response: no system reaches production without a corresponding inventory record, and the inventory is reviewed for completeness by a named mechanism owner at defined intervals.

Each registry entry must contain the information needed to govern the system. The system’s purpose and intended use. Its EU AI Act actor designation, provider, deployer or both, and its risk classification under the Act. Its internal impact classification, distinct from the regulatory classification. Its assigned system owner, the named human who carries accountability for that system’s governance. Its oversight mode: human-in-the-loop, human-on-the-loop or human-in-command, assigned explicitly and proportionate to the system’s impact classification. Its trust boundary specification, by reference to the document in which the authorized zone, escalation zone and prohibited zone are defined. Its evidence retention policy: what logs are kept, for how long and who has access. And the date of its last governance review.

The registry is not a one-time document. It is a living record that must be updated when the system changes, when its use changes, when the organization’s role changes or when the regulatory context changes. A system that was registered as minimal risk and has since been deployed in a regulated sector context is no longer a minimal risk system regardless of what the registry says. The mechanism owner who fails to update the registry has not merely maintained an inaccurate document. They have created a governance gap through which the system operates outside the controls that would apply if its actual deployment context were known.

## Oversight Modes and Their Limits

The oversight mode assigned to each AI system is the governance decision that most directly determines whether human accountability is real or nominal. Three modes apply, each carrying different governance obligations.

Human-in-the-Loop requires a qualified human to review and approve each individual AI output or decision before it takes effect. It is the appropriate mode for high-impact systems making decisions in employment, financial standing, access to essential services and safety contexts. It is the most expensive mode to operate and the most defensible under legal and regulatory scrutiny. HITL is not satisfied by perfunctory review. A reviewer who approves outputs without the information, time, authority and expertise required to exercise genuine independent judgment is not providing oversight. They are providing the appearance of oversight, which is the precondition for liability without the benefit of control. The organization that claims HITL oversight and cannot demonstrate that the reviewing humans had what they needed to actually review is worse off than an organization that deployed without HITL claims at all, because it has added a false representation to its existing governance gap.

Human-on-the-Loop requires a qualified human to actively monitor AI outputs in real time, retaining the practical ability and authority to intervene and override. It is the minimum requirement for medium-impact systems and the minimum operational standard for high-impact systems operating at scale where HITL on each individual decision is operationally infeasible. HOTL requires that the monitoring function be genuinely staffed and that intervention is both technically and organizationally possible. A monitoring dashboard that nobody watches is not HOTL. A monitoring function staffed by someone without the authority to halt the system is not HOTL. The test is not whether a human is nominally present. The test is whether a human who identified a problem could stop it.

Human-in-Command applies where humans retain overall control of the AI system, including the ability to decide on deployment, modify objectives and shut down the system, but are not necessarily involved in individual output decisions. It is appropriate for low-impact systems with well-defined, narrow operating parameters and robust automated controls. It is not appropriate for systems making consequential decisions about people, money, rights or safety, regardless of how the deployment is characterized.

Any proposal to reduce the oversight mode of an existing system, from HITL to HOTL or from HOTL to HIC, is a governance event requiring formal approval at the appropriate level. It is not a technical update. It is a decision to reduce human involvement in consequential decisions, and the evidence that it was made deliberately, by the right people, for documented reasons, is the evidence that will matter when the reduced oversight mode is later tested by an incident, an audit or a regulatory inquiry.

## Change Management as a Governance Control

Every material change to an agentic system is a governance event. This is not a proposition that most technology teams accept comfortably, because it imposes a governance process on what engineers experience as continuous improvement: model updates, prompt revisions, integration changes, permission adjustments, new data sources, modified escalation thresholds. Each of these changes the system’s behavior. Each of them changes the trust boundary, whether or not the trust boundary document has been updated to reflect it.

The governance requirement for change management is specific. Before any material change to an agentic system reaches production, the change must be assessed against the system’s existing trust boundary specification. Does the change modify what the agent is authorized to do? Does it change the escalation conditions? Does it give the agent access to new data sources or new downstream systems? Does it reduce or eliminate a control that was part of the system’s risk treatment plan? If the answer to any of these questions is yes, the change requires governance review and approval at the level appropriate to the system’s impact classification, not technical sign-off alone.

The EU AI Act’s Article 25 substantial modification threshold is the regulatory expression of this principle. A deployer that modifies an AI system or deploys it outside its intended purpose may become a provider under the Act, with the full provider obligation stack applied from the point of modification. Organizations that treat prompt engineering, fine-tuning or integration changes as routine technical activity without assessing the Article 25 threshold are not merely operating outside good governance practice. In the EU context, they may be operating outside the law without knowing it, which is exactly the compliance surprise that the change management process is designed to prevent.

## The Evidence Pipeline

The Three Lines Model produces accountability only if each line has the evidence it needs to do its job. The first line needs evidence that the agent operated within its authorized scope. The second line needs evidence that the first line’s controls are operating as designed. The third line needs evidence that the second line’s oversight is genuine and effective. The regulator, the court and the injured party need evidence that the whole system produced the outcome it was supposed to produce, governed by the people who were supposed to govern it.

The evidence pipeline is the architecture that makes all of this possible. It is not a single system. It is the set of logging, monitoring, review and retention practices that together produce the evidentiary record the organization needs to demonstrate that governance operated. What the agent did, when it did it, what it was authorized to do, who reviewed the authorization, what escalations occurred and how they were resolved, what changes were made to the system and who approved them, what incidents occurred and how they were handled. The evidence pipeline captures all of this in a form that is complete, tamper-evident and accessible to the people who need it.

The evidence pipeline must be designed before the agent is deployed. Evidence that is retrofitted after an incident is not evidence of governance. It is forensics. Forensics is useful for understanding what went wrong. It is not the same as the documented governance trail that demonstrates prospective judgment, the thing that regulators under the EU AI Act, courts applying product liability principles and clients evaluating governance maturity all require. Prospective evidence, the authorization, the specification, the testing record, the monitoring log, is the artifact of having governed the system from the beginning. It cannot be manufactured after the fact, and the attempt to do so is itself a governance failure with legal consequences of its own.

The Audit and Due Diligence Checklist in Appendix I operationalizes the trust boundary, agent registry and evidence pipeline requirements across the full audit universe. Section 0 of that checklist, Pre-Audit Scoping: Inventory and Actor Classification, is the starting point for any audit of agentic AI governance. It is also the mirror that every organization should hold up before deploying its first agent: the questions in Section 0 are the questions a competent auditor will ask first, and an organization that cannot answer them before deployment will not be able to answer them under audit pressure after.

## What This Chapter Has Done

The chapter has assembled the operating structure, the Three Lines, the trust boundary, the agent registry, the oversight modes and the evidence pipeline, as expressions of one requirement, named human accountability made operational before the system acts.

The chapter has named accountability thinning and set its threshold as a risk-appetite decision. Final Liability remains real only to the extent the organization has built accountability systems it will stand behind and accepted, on the record, the risk that they fail.

The chapter has left the societal questions the agentic shift raises to the Epilogue, treating here only the operational governance response.

**The Three Lines, the trust boundary, the agent registry, the oversight modes, the organizational design principles and the evidence pipeline are not separate instruments. They are expressions of a single requirement: named human accountability, made operational before the system acts, maintained continuously while it operates and evidenced completely so that when the question of who owns the outcome arrives, the answer is already in the record.**

**Final Liability rests with the Human.**

# CHAPTER 15

## Principal-Agent Risk at Machine Speed

> *Pure art seeks freedom of expression but handicraft is created under certain constraints.*
>
> *Soetsu Yanagi, The Beauty of Everyday Things*

In 2025, Glass Lewis reviewed the proxy statements of all S&P 100 companies and found that only twenty-eight percent disclosed both board-level oversight of artificial intelligence and a formal AI policy. Forty-six percent of those boards had no disclosed AI oversight structure at all. Meanwhile, sixty-five percent of U.S. institutional investors reported that they expected every company to provide clear disclosure of board oversight of AI governance and AI ethics. The gap between what shareholders expected and what companies delivered was thirty-seven percentage points. The gap was not closing.

That number measures something specific. It measures the distance between a principal who expects governance and an agent who has not built it. The shareholders are the principals. The boards are their agents. The boards, in turn, are principals relative to the management teams they oversee. And the management teams are deploying AI systems that none of these layers fully understand, at a speed none of them can fully monitor, with incentive structures that reward deployment over restraint. This is not a technology problem. It is a principal-agent problem compounded at every level of the corporate governance stack.

The Harvard Law School Forum on Corporate Governance has published more than a dozen substantive analyses of board AI oversight since 2022. Read together, they provide an unusually detailed empirical record of what happens when an agency relationship that evolved over centuries encounters a technology that moves in months. The record is not encouraging.

## The Principal Who Cannot See

The most basic requirement of any principal-agent relationship is that the principal can monitor the agent. A shareholder monitors through disclosure. A board monitors through reporting systems, committee structures and direct engagement with management. A regulator monitors through examination, audit and enforcement. Each layer depends on information flowing upward, from the agent who has it to the principal who needs it.

AI breaks this flow in three ways.

First, the technology is opaque. The “black box” problem is not a metaphor. When a model produces an output (a credit decision, a hiring recommendation, a medical triage, a content moderation ruling) the reasoning behind that output is frequently not available for inspection by the humans who deployed it, let alone by the board members who authorized the deployment budget. A board that cannot inspect the reasoning behind the agent’s decisions is a board that monitors by proxy, relying on management’s interpretation of what the system is doing and why. That interpretation is itself an agency cost, because management has incentives to present AI performance favorably.

Second, AI’s operational footprint is cross-functional. Prior technology risks tended to concentrate in IT or cybersecurity, domains that could be assigned to a single committee with relevant expertise. AI permeates finance, legal, human resources, product development, marketing, supply chain and customer service simultaneously. The information a board needs to oversee AI is distributed across the entire management layer, which means the board must either develop cross-functional AI competence (which most boards lack) or rely on management to synthesize cross-functional AI risk into a board-consumable summary (which returns the principal to dependence on the agent’s narrative).

Third, the speed differential is structural. AI systems are deployed, updated, fine-tuned and iterated continuously. Board meetings occur quarterly. Committee meetings occur monthly at best. The governance cycle and the deployment cycle operate on fundamentally different clocks, and the deployment clock is accelerating. When a model is retrained, a prompt template is revised, an agentic workflow is activated or a new vendor API is integrated between board meetings, the principal’s monitoring function is already stale.

These three dynamics (opacity, breadth and speed) produce a specific result: the principal becomes dependent on the agent’s self-reporting. The empirical evidence shows that the self-reporting is not happening.

A 2025 Deloitte survey of board members and executives found that sixty-six percent reported having “limited to no knowledge or experience” with AI. Nearly a third said AI was not on the board agenda at all. Only seventeen percent of boards addressed AI at every meeting; nineteen percent addressed it once per year. When boards did engage on AI, they overwhelmingly talked to the executives responsible for deploying it. Seventy-two percent engaged with the Chief Information Officer or Chief Technology Officer, and rarely talked to the executives responsible for assessing its risks. Only twelve percent engaged with the Chief Information Security Officer or Chief Risk Officer.

The communication pipeline is structurally biased toward the deployment narrative. The board hears from the people building and deploying AI. It rarely hears, independently, from the people whose job is to identify what could go wrong. A principal that receives its information exclusively from the agent it is supposed to monitor is not exercising oversight. It is ratifying the agent’s self-assessment.

PricewaterhouseCoopers, writing on the Harvard Forum in November 2025, named this dynamic with unusual candor. The board, PwC observed, “receives nearly all of its information from the management team,” and these arrangements “inherently create an agency problem as the board depends on its information from the very management team it is tasked with overseeing, potentially compromising its ability to exercise independent judgment and oversight.” That is a Big Four firm publishing, on a Harvard Law School platform, an explicit statement that the foundational governance relationship is structurally compromised. The article then proposed that AI itself could reduce the information asymmetry: directors might use AI tools to independently benchmark disclosures, analyze historical data and pressure-test strategy without management intermediation.

The proposal is intellectually interesting and practically circular. A board that cannot oversee AI deployment is unlikely to effectively use AI to oversee AI deployment. The sixty-six percent knowledge gap does not disappear because the tool changes; it reappears inside the new tool. And PwC itself identified the secondary risks: board overreach (using AI-enabled analysis to cross from oversight into management), AI hallucinations in governance outputs, data security exposure from directors using unapproved platforms, and the creation of discoverable written records that regulators or plaintiffs’ lawyers could cherry-pick with hindsight. Each of these risks is a new agency cost generated by the proposed remedy for the original agency cost.

The problem is not that boards need better tools. The problem is that the governance architecture was designed for a world where the principal could understand the agent’s operations through periodic reporting, and that world no longer exists.

## The Incentive Structure That Works Against Itself

While boards struggle to monitor AI, they are simultaneously creating incentive structures that reward the behavior they should be restraining.

In March 2026, Equilar published a study of corporate disclosures showing that companies were incorporating AI-focused performance objectives directly into executive compensation plans. Qorvo disclosed a standalone AI performance metric weighted at twenty percent of its executive long-term incentive plan, using annual measurement periods for what was nominally a long-term award, because, as the company acknowledged, the fast-moving nature of AI made it impractical to set multi-year targets. Juniper Networks assigned ten percent of its annual incentive to a strategic goal defined as winning “the AI opportunity.” Recursion Pharmaceuticals weighted approximately sixteen percent of its annual incentive toward leading “the data and AI revolution.”

The trend extended beyond technology companies. Cognizant tied incentive pay to generative AI development and advancement. Ralph Lauren disclosed plans to replace its citizenship and sustainability metrics with AI scorecard metrics as the strategic goal modifier for the following fiscal year.

Read as compensation disclosures, these are unremarkable. Companies tie executive pay to strategic priorities; AI is a strategic priority. Read as governance disclosures, they are something else entirely.

The board’s compensation committee sets metrics that pay executives for deploying AI fast and broadly. The board’s risk or audit committee is supposed to ensure that AI deployment is controlled, tested, monitored and governed. These two committees operate within the same board, drawing on the same limited AI expertise, and they work at cross-purposes. The compensation function creates velocity incentives. The governance function requires friction: testing, review, human oversight, documentation. When the executive’s pay is indexed at ten to twenty percent to AI deployment outcomes and the governance function operates through quarterly committee meetings, the incentive structure has a predictable winner.

The Ralph Lauren disclosure deserves particular attention. Replacing sustainability metrics with AI scorecard metrics as the strategic goal modifier is not an incremental adjustment. It is a disclosed substitution: governance-oriented measures (sustainability, citizenship) are being removed from the compensation structure and replaced with deployment-oriented measures (AI adoption, AI-enabled efficiency). The principal’s risk tolerance is being traded for the agent’s velocity incentive, and the trade is happening inside the principal’s own compensation architecture.

Qorvo’s disclosure is revealing in a different way. The decision to use annual measurement for a long-term incentive plan because AI moves too fast for multi-year targets is an inadvertent admission that the governance cycle cannot keep pace with the deployment cycle. If the technology changes too fast for the board to set meaningful three-year accountability horizons, it also changes too fast for the board to exercise meaningful oversight through periodic reporting. The same speed that defeats long-term target-setting defeats quarterly monitoring.

This is not an oversight failure in the traditional sense. The board is not failing to act. It is acting, and the action (setting compensation metrics that reward rapid deployment) undermines the separate action (overseeing deployment risk) that the same board is supposed to perform simultaneously. The compensation structure is an agency cost accelerator built into the governance system by the principal itself.

## The Doctrine That No Longer Holds

For the past two decades, corporate governance in the United States has organized itself around a principle commonly expressed as “Noses In, Fingers Out.” The board stays informed about the company’s key operational risks (noses in) while staying out of operational management (fingers out). The board asks questions. Management answers them. The board evaluates the answers and exercises judgment. Management executes. The boundary is clear, well-understood and foundational to the American corporate governance model.

AI makes this boundary impossible to maintain.

The problem is not that the principle is wrong. It is that the principle assumes two conditions that AI no longer satisfies. First, it assumes that the board can stay informed through periodic reporting, that the information management provides is timely, accurate and sufficient for oversight purposes. When AI systems operate continuously, evolve between meetings and produce outputs that require technical expertise to evaluate, periodic reporting cannot deliver the information the board needs. Second, it assumes that staying informed does not require the board to replicate the agent’s expertise. When the agent’s operations are technically opaque and the board’s knowledge gap is sixty-six percent, “staying informed” either means accepting management’s summary at face value (which is not oversight) or developing independent technical competence (which crosses into management).

This tension was identified explicitly by Giunta and Suvanto, writing on the Harvard Forum in 2024. They observed that AI’s complexity and speed were putting pressure on boards to engage “more frequently and deeply with management,” but warned that deeper engagement risked crossing the line from governance to management, “violating the heretofore inviolate principle of ‘Noses In, Fingers Out.’” EY, writing in February 2026, identified “CEO resists board involvement in setting AI strategy” as a common barrier and recommended that the independent chair engage the CEO directly, a recommendation that implicitly acknowledges the agent may actively resist the principal’s monitoring.

The governance profession’s instinct is to solve this with education. The Deloitte survey found that fifty-nine percent of individual board members had sought to enhance their AI knowledge independently. But only about half of organizations provided foundational AI education to their boards, and the education was typically delivered by or through management, meaning the principal’s knowledge acquisition was mediated by the agent. An EY review of Fortune 100 proxy statements found that only twelve percent of companies disclosed that board members had received education or training on AI.

Education helps. It does not solve the structural problem. The board that “upskills” through management-curated presentations is still receiving its understanding of AI risk from the management team that owns the AI deployment budget and the AI deployment incentive plan. The information asymmetry is reproduced inside the education program.

The reason education cannot close this gap is organizational, not pedagogical. Archibald Putt, writing pseudonymously in *Putt**’**s Law and the Successful Technocrat*, observed decades ago that technology organizations systematically invert competence: the people who understand the technology best operate closest to the work, while smoother generalists rise into management and governance. The hierarchy that controls the technology is populated, at each ascending level, by people with progressively less technical understanding of what they control. This is not a failure of any individual’s character. It is a structural feature of how large organizations sort talent, and it means that the information flowing upward from the people who understand AI to the people who govern it is filtered, simplified and reframed at every layer of the hierarchy before it reaches the board.

That dynamic was uncomfortable but manageable when the middle management layer still performed three distinct functions: routing information through the organization, making sense of ambiguous inputs in context, and carrying personal accountability for outcomes over time. AI is now eliminating the first of those functions with real efficiency. Information can be aggregated, summarized, distributed and surfaced by systems rather than by people. But the second and third functions, sensemaking and accountability, are not automatable in the same way, and they are not being preserved with the same care.

In early 2026, Block announced a restructuring that cut over four thousand employees and explicitly replaced permanent middle management with AI coordination. Jack Dorsey and Roelof Botha, in an essay titled “From Hierarchy to Intelligence,” argued that corporate hierarchy exists to solve one problem, routing information through organizations too large for any single person to oversee, and that AI can now perform that function continuously and at scale. Block’s replacement structure has three roles: individual contributors who build, Directly Responsible Individuals who own specific outcomes on ninety-day cycles, and player-coaches who combine building with developing people. No permanent middle management layer. Meta pursued a similar compression, keeping management intact in substance but reducing layers and widening spans of control. The results in both cases included speed, but also reports of strain, ambiguity and a loss of clarity about who carries the load.

The governance risk is specific. When companies remove the management layers that performed sensemaking and accountability between the board and the AI systems, they do not eliminate the need for those functions. They displace them, often upward onto founders and executives who are already overextended, or downward onto individual contributors who have no governance mandate. The board, meanwhile, loses the interpretive layer that used to translate technical reality into governance-grade information. The information pipeline does not just become biased toward the deployment narrative. It becomes thinner, less filtered and less accountable. A company that mistakes a solved coordination problem for a solved governance problem will discover the difference when the system fails and no one in the compressed hierarchy can explain what happened, who decided, or what the controls were supposed to be.

Researchers at BetterUp Labs and the Stanford Social Media Lab introduced a useful term in a September 2025 Harvard Business Review study: “workslop.” It describes AI-generated work that is highly polished but inaccurate or lacking substance, the AI-era version of the quality problem in any principal-agent relationship. The principal cannot distinguish between genuine work and performance theater because the surface presentation is identical. Applied to board-management dynamics, the risk is that management presentations on AI governance may be polished, comprehensive and substantively hollow, describing an AI ethics framework, a responsible AI committee, a set of principles, without any operational capacity behind them. The board sees the governance artifact. It does not see the governance capacity. And with two-thirds of boards admitting they lack the knowledge to tell the difference, the artifact is all they have.

## The Liability That Is Already Here

The governance failures described above are not hypothetical legal risks. They are materializing inside an established and expanding body of Delaware fiduciary duty law.

The trajectory runs through four cases. In 1996, the Delaware Court of Chancery decided *In re Caremark International*, establishing that directors may be liable for breach of the duty of loyalty if they fail to make a good-faith effort to implement and oversee corporate information and reporting systems. The court described this theory as “possibly the most difficult theory in corporation law upon which a plaintiff might hope to win a judgment,” because it requires a showing of “sustained or systematic failure” amounting to “utter failure to attempt to assure a reasonable information and reporting system exists.” The bar was set high. It has been coming down.

In 2019, the Delaware Supreme Court decided *Marchand v. Barnhill*, reversing the dismissal of *Caremark* claims against the directors of Blue Bell Creameries after a food safety crisis. The court found that the board had failed to implement a compliance monitoring system for what was clearly a “mission critical” risk. The case established that the nature of the company’s business defines the scope of the board’s oversight duty: if a risk goes to the core of the enterprise, the board must have a corresponding oversight infrastructure, and the absence of that infrastructure can support an inference of bad faith.

In 2021, the Delaware Court of Chancery applied the same reasoning to Boeing. Vice Chancellor Zurn, denying a motion to dismiss *Caremark* claims in *In re The Boeing Company Derivative Litigation*, found that plaintiffs had sufficiently alleged the board breached its oversight duty by failing to establish compliance procedures for airplane safety, the company’s most mission-critical function. The evidentiary record was damning: board minutes showed that airplane safety was not addressed as part of the board’s yearly compliance updates and was not regularly on the agenda at board meetings. Safety had been delegated to an internal employee-run Safety Review Board without direct reporting to the board of directors.

Replace “airplane safety” with “AI system performance, bias and output quality.” The governance parallel holds. A company that deploys AI in customer-facing decisions, employment screening, financial underwriting or healthcare triage is operating a system that goes to the core of its enterprise risk. If the board has no reporting system for AI-specific risks, does not include AI on its regular compliance agenda, and has delegated AI oversight to management without independent reporting, the board’s governance posture mirrors Boeing’s safety posture before the 737 MAX crashes. The question is not whether the analogy will be drawn in litigation. The question is whether the board’s response structure will survive the pleading stage when it is.

The most recent development makes the parallel more acute. In January 2026, Chancellor McCormick of the Delaware Court of Chancery denied motions to dismiss *Caremark* claims in *Los Angeles City Employees**’** Retirement System v. Sanford*, holding that directors’ and officers’ failure to respond in good faith to clear red flags of workplace misconduct may constitute breach of fiduciary duty. The decision extended *Caremark* in two directions that apply directly to AI governance.

First, *Sanford* established that once a board or senior management becomes aware of a credible problem, passive acknowledgment is not enough. Proactive action must be taken, and “nominal or superficial actions that do not address the problem may be insufficient.” Applied to AI: a board that receives reports of AI system failures, bias incidents, output quality problems or customer complaints and responds with a policy statement, a committee charter revision or a management assurance that “we’re looking into it” may not satisfy the duty. The response must address the problem operationally, not just procedurally.

Second, *Sanford* held that a CEO who knowingly concealed credible internal reports from the board and retained employees implicated in the problem because they generated revenue had potentially breached the duty of loyalty, a more serious exposure than the duty of care, because loyalty breaches cannot be exculpated under Section 102(b)(7) of the Delaware General Corporation Law. Applied to AI: a CTO or business unit leader who suppresses information about AI system failures to protect deployment timelines or revenue narratives, or who retains a vendor whose model has known deficiencies because switching costs are high, is engaging in the same conduct the *Sanford* court found sufficient to survive dismissal.

The court also reinforced a principle with immediate AI governance implications: oversight risk increases where the company’s public disclosures about its capabilities or controls are “materially inconsistent” with internal reality. A company that describes its “responsible AI framework” in public filings while internally having no operational incident detection, no pre-assigned containment authority, no evidence preservation protocol and no post-incident review process faces compound exposure: *Caremark* liability for the oversight failure and potential securities liability for the disclosure-reality gap.

The *Caremark* trajectory, from “possibly the most difficult theory” in 1996 to surviving motions to dismiss in safety, food, workplace misconduct and environmental contexts by 2026, tells boards everything they need to know about the direction of travel. AI governance is the next domain. The incidents are already occurring. A New York City government chatbot advised small businesses that they could legally fire workers for complaining about sexual harassment. A healthcare algorithm used across U.S. hospitals was found to systematically underidentify Black patients for high-risk care management. An online real estate marketplace wrote off more than three hundred million dollars due to an algorithmic pricing error.

The 473.5 percent increase in Fortune 500 companies flagging AI as a risk factor in their annual reports, reported by Arize AI in 2024, is itself evidence that companies know the risk is mission-critical. The question is whether their boards have built a governance infrastructure commensurate with that knowledge, or whether, like Boeing’s board before the crashes, the minutes will show that the risk was never really on the agenda.

## From Diagnosis to Architecture

The four dynamics described above (information asymmetry, incentive misalignment, doctrinal breakdown and materializing liability) are not four separate problems. They are four expressions of a single structural failure: the principal has lost the capacity to monitor the agent, and the governance architecture has not been redesigned to restore it.

The traditional remedy for agency costs is monitoring infrastructure: systems that provide the principal with independent information about the agent’s performance, authority to intervene when performance fails and evidence to evaluate accountability after the fact. Corporate governance already has these systems for financial reporting (internal controls, external audit, audit committees, SOX compliance). It does not yet have them for AI.

The “Noses In, Fingers Out” doctrine served well when the boundary between oversight and management was clear, the reporting cadence was sufficient and the board’s general business judgment was adequate to evaluate the information it received. AI satisfies none of these conditions. The boundary is unclear because AI operations are too opaque for the board to evaluate from the outside and too pervasive for the board to ignore. The reporting cadence is insufficient because AI deployment is continuous. And general business judgment is inadequate because AI risks are technical, cross-functional and evolving.

The replacement is not a new doctrine. It is a governance architecture, a set of structural controls that provide the board with what it needs without requiring the board to manage what it should not.

That architecture has six components. Each corresponds to a specific principal-agent control problem, and each is designed to produce the evidence that a *Caremark* defense requires. What follows is the operational substance behind the governance claim that every board already makes on paper.

**Preparation** is authority allocation. The principal-agent question is not “who is responsible for AI governance,” a formulation that produces diffuse ownership and no actionable authority. The question is: who can pause a system, approve containment, authorize notification and own remediation? Authority must be named, pre-delegated and specific enough that a decision can be made quickly when the system fails. Generic ownership statements are agency costs: they let everyone assume someone else is the principal. Preparation also requires identifying external stakeholders (infrastructure providers, model vendors, outside counsel, key customers) before they are needed, and predefining how conflicts between speed and caution are resolved, typically by designating a single accountable officer with pre-delegated authority to break ties.

**Detection and triage** is information asymmetry reduction. The principal must have a mechanism for learning what the agent knows (or should know) independently of the agent’s willingness to report. AI failures appear first in outputs, patterns, decisions and downstream effects, not in system uptime or security alerts. Detection frameworks must account for user complaints, employee reporting, audit findings, quality review, anomalous business outcomes and, critically, AI use outside approved deployments. Shadow AI (employees using unapproved AI tools for business purposes) sits outside standard monitoring by definition. The organization’s liability attaches regardless of whether the use was sanctioned.

Triage requires predefined severity thresholds and escalation paths. Without them, the first hours of every incident are consumed by the question of whether the problem “counts,” a debate that delays containment, destroys evidence and creates the appearance of indifference that *Sanford* holds actionable. Useful triage questions can be specified in advance: Is the issue ongoing? Are affected users experiencing harm? Are regulated activities or protected categories implicated? Did human review fail? Is the cause known? Has any notification clock started?

**Containment** is the principal’s authority to intervene, to stop the agent. If no one has pre-delegated power to pause, suspend, roll back, narrow access, disable a feature or place outputs behind manual review, the system runs until someone convenes a meeting. Containment options should be predefined by impact tier and should include not only technical responses (suspension, rollback, access restriction) but also operational coordination (customer support, internal messaging, vendor engagement). The correct containment response reduces harm quickly without destroying the evidence needed to understand what happened.

**Root cause analysis** is accountability tracing: determining what the agent actually did. AI incidents should be analyzed across at least three dimensions: data (training data quality, retrieval logic, input distribution), system (model behavior, prompt design, evaluation gaps, deployment configuration) and organization (human oversight failures, unclear ownership, inadequate training, poor change control). The critical discipline is resisting shallow explanation. “The model hallucinated” is not a root cause. It is an agency cost, a formulation that attributes failure to the tool rather than to the decision to deploy the tool without adequate controls. The meaningful question is why the organization allowed that failure mode to reach production, remain undetected or affect real decisions. If the analysis does not feed back into design, process and accountability, the same class of failure returns.

Where the incident originates in a vendor model or API, the enterprise may have limited forensic access. Root cause analysis should acknowledge that constraint directly rather than fabricating certainty. The corresponding preparation-stage action is to negotiate audit rights, incident cooperation clauses and log access provisions in vendor contracts before they are needed.

**Notification and disclosure** is the principal’s duty to report to its own principals. Every organization operates within a hierarchy of agency relationships: the board reports to shareholders; the company reports to regulators; the deploying organization reports to affected individuals. When an AI incident implicates legal, regulatory, contractual or internal governance obligations, those obligations must be assessed promptly and documented carefully. The EU AI Act, Article 73, requires reporting of serious incidents involving high-risk AI systems. The GDPR, Article 33, requires seventy-two-hour notification to the supervisory authority for personal data breaches likely to result in risk to individuals’ rights and freedoms. Korea’s AI Basic Act may impose additional obligations once implementing regulations are finalized. The practical requirement is mapping these obligations by jurisdiction as a preparation-stage exercise, not discovering them during a crisis.

Communications are part of control. The *Sanford* court emphasized that oversight risk increases where public disclosures diverge from internal reality. Poorly timed, inconsistent or incomplete incident communications can magnify an incident even when the technical issue is being addressed, and they can create the disclosure-reality gap that exposes the organization to compound liability.

**Post-incident review** is learning as governance. Without formalized feedback, the principal-agent gap resets after every incident. The organization “learns” only in the sense that individuals remember. The governance system itself does not update. A post-incident review should identify what happened, why it happened, what worked, what failed, what was changed and who owns completion. Findings should feed into risk registers, change management, approval gates, monitoring logic and, where necessary, policy and training revisions. Repeated incidents, delayed escalation or recurring control weaknesses should trigger broader management attention and, where appropriate, board-level reporting.

This is where governance artifacts become governance evidence. A board that can produce documented post-incident reviews showing pattern identification, corrective action and systemic improvement has a *Caremark* defense. A board that cannot produce them has the Boeing minutes problem: a record that shows the risk was known and the response was absent.

## What Termination Publishes

When an AI system is shut down, paused or rolled back, the act of termination is an involuntary disclosure of organizational maturity. The post-incident record, whatever exists of it, reveals the actual state of governance, not the aspirational state.

The record shows whether authority was pre-delegated or had to be negotiated in real time. It shows whether detection was systematic or accidental, whether the organization’s monitoring caught the failure or whether a customer complaint, a journalist’s inquiry or a regulator’s letter surfaced it. It shows whether evidence was preserved contemporaneously or had to be reconstructed after the fact, with all the reliability problems that reconstruction entails. It shows whether escalation paths existed in advance or had to be improvised while the system was still producing harmful outputs. It shows whether the board was informed through a pre-existing reporting channel or surprised by a crisis that management had not surfaced. It shows whether corrective action was documented and tracked to completion or whether the incident was closed with a verbal assurance that “we fixed it.”

This is the negative proof problem applied to AI governance. What the organization cannot produce after an incident proves what it never had. The absence of pre-assigned authority proves that authority was unclear. The absence of contemporaneous evidence proves that preservation requirements were not defined. The absence of escalation documentation proves that escalation paths were not established. The absence of a post-incident review proves that learning was not formalized.

The disclosure-reality gap that the *Sanford* court identified as actionable is revealed most completely when a system goes down and the record is examined. Every company with an AI ethics statement, a responsible AI committee and a set of published principles is making an implicit representation about its governance capacity. The incident record tests that representation. If the record shows that the ethics statement was never operationalized, the committee never met with authority, and the principles were never translated into detection, escalation, containment or evidence-preservation protocols, the representation was false, not in the sense of intentional fraud, but in the sense that matters for *Caremark*: the governance system was nominal, and the board either knew or should have known.

A properly structured governance system is designed so that the termination record demonstrates capacity, not its absence. The six-stage architecture described above produces evidence at every stage: assigned authority in the preparation stage, detection logs and triage records at identification, containment decisions and their rationale at response, root cause findings at analysis, notification records at disclosure and corrective action tracking at review. That evidence is not created for litigation. It is created because competent governance requires it. But when litigation arrives (and the *Caremark* trajectory says it will) the evidence is there.

The board that can produce this record survives the pleading stage. The board that cannot produce it faces the question the court asked in Boeing: were the risks on the agenda, was there a reporting system, and did the board exercise oversight or merely assume that someone else was handling it?

## Redundancy Beats Reassurance

The governance failures catalogued in the Harvard Forum literature share a common root. Boards were reassured (by management presentations, by committee structures, by policy documents, by the existence of a Chief AI Officer or an AI ethics board) and they treated reassurance as a substitute for verification. The AI was deployed. The metrics looked good. The quarterly report was favorable. The board moved to the next agenda item.

Reassurance is the governance product that the agent is best positioned to provide and the principal is least positioned to evaluate. It requires no independent verification, no adverse information, no operational testing and no evidence that the system works under stress. It requires only that the management presentation is competent, the committee charter is well-drafted and the policy document is comprehensive on paper.

Redundancy is the alternative. Redundant governance means that more than one pathway exists for risk information to reach the principal. It means that the board receives AI risk information not only through management’s reporting but also through independent audit, through direct access to monitoring data, through external assessment, through incident reports that flow to the board automatically above a defined severity threshold, and through post-incident reviews that are documented and tracked. It means that authority to intervene does not depend on a single point of contact, that evidence preservation does not depend on management’s decision to preserve, and that escalation does not depend on the agent’s willingness to escalate.

Redundancy is more expensive, slower and less comfortable than reassurance. It creates friction in the deployment pipeline, tension in the board-management relationship and documentation that may be discoverable in litigation. These are features, not defects. The friction slows deployment to a pace that governance can match. The tension maintains the boundary between principal and agent. The documentation creates the evidence that distinguishes genuine oversight from performance theater.

The boards that survive the next decade of AI governance litigation will not be the boards that had the best AI ethics statements, the most innovative committee structures or the most impressive management presentations. They will be the boards that built redundant monitoring systems, pre-delegated intervention authority, required evidence preservation and formalized post-incident learning. They will be the boards that treated AI governance not as a disclosure exercise but as an operational capability that could be tested under stress and shown to work.

## What This Chapter Has Done

The chapter has carried principal-agent risk into the boardroom and shown what it looks like at machine speed.

The chapter has traced the oversight duty through the Caremark line to Marchand, Boeing and Sanford, and shown that an oversight system which is nominal or superficial is, in the court’s own words, no system at all.

The chapter has named the failure the board must avoid, noses in and fingers out, applied to systems that act faster than the board meets.

The technology will keep accelerating. The agency costs will keep compounding. The liability will keep materializing. The only variable the board controls is whether the governance architecture is real or whether it is, in the *Sanford* court’s formulation, nominal and superficial.

**Final Liability rests with the Human.**

