**Running the governance is not the same as operating it. Running it means designing whether and how the enterprise can act in the first place. The General Counsel function, properly understood, designs the architecture inside which every other function makes its decisions. The architecture is not a deliverable. It is an ongoing discipline that determines, for any given proposed action, whether the organization is permitted to take it, capable of taking it well and prepared to defend the decision later. This is what the chapter sets out, and this is what the function must own.**

Earlier chapters in Part III set out the structural conditions that make governance hard at machine speed. Chapter 14 described the Three Lines and the trust boundary. Chapter 15 described what principal-agent risk looks like when agents act faster than principals can supervise. This chapter takes the next step: it describes what running the governance actually requires from the General Counsel function in the agentic era, and why that role can only be performed by the function structurally positioned to perform it.

## Running Is Not the Same as Operating

The verb to run is used in many ways inside organizations. A business unit runs its operations. A technology function runs its systems. A finance function runs its books. A compliance function runs its program. Each of these uses the verb to mean something specific to the function: to operate the assigned activity to a defined standard, on a defined cadence, with defined accountability for defined outputs.

The General Counsel function runs the governance, but the verb means something different here. The governance is not an operation. The governance is the architecture that determines what the operations are permitted and capable of doing. To run the governance is to design and maintain that architecture, not to execute the operations inside it.

The distinction matters because organizations frequently misunderstand it. A governance function that operates the controls, processes the exceptions, signs off the filings and produces the artifacts is performing operational work. The work is necessary. It is not what running the governance means. Running the governance means designing the system inside which the operational work is performed: which controls exist, which thresholds trigger which escalations, which actions require which approvals, which outcomes require which evidence and which exceptions break the architecture badly enough to warrant a redesign.

Operating the controls is downstream of designing them. A function that only operates the controls inherits a design it did not author and cannot defend when the design fails. This is the structural failure mode of most second-line governance functions in practice. The function processes the exceptions but does not own the threshold. The function approves the actions but does not own the criteria. The function produces the artifacts but does not own the evidence architecture they sit inside. When the consequence arrives, the function cannot explain the design, because the design was not theirs. They were operating it.

Strong governance reverses the relationship. The function owns the design and operates only those controls that the design assigns to it. Other controls are operated by other functions, but the design they are operating is the governance function’s design. The architecture binds the operations. The function that owns the architecture runs the governance. Functions that operate inside the architecture, however large or competent, are not running the governance. They are operating within it.

## The Four Things the GC Connects

The reason this work belongs to the General Counsel rather than to another function is structural, not preferential. The four elements that must be bound together to produce governance that can be defended later are authority, risk, evidence and consequence. The General Counsel is the only function in the modern enterprise structurally positioned to connect all four.

Authority is the question of who is permitted to act and what they are permitted to act on. The General Counsel function holds this question because corporate authority is a legal construct: it derives from the corporate form, the board’s resolutions, the delegations of authority, the agency relationships and the contracts that bind the entity to its counterparties. No other function has both the comprehensive view and the structural standing to assess whether a proposed action is within authorized scope.

Risk is the question of what can go wrong, with what likelihood and with what severity. Risk management functions own the registers, the assessments and the tolerances. The General Counsel function holds the question of which risks are unacceptable as a matter of law, regulation, contract or fiduciary obligation, regardless of where the risk register places them. The risk register can rank a risk as moderate. The General Counsel function can determine that the same risk is, in legal terms, unacceptable because it produces an exposure the entity cannot absorb. Both views are valid. The legal view binds.

Evidence is the question of what can be proved later. Compliance and audit functions own pieces of the evidence architecture. The General Counsel function holds the question of what evidence will be required if the action is later challenged, by whom, in what form and within what limitation periods. No other function has both the litigation perspective and the regulatory perspective to assess what the evidence pipeline must produce. The function that does not anticipate the demand cannot design the pipeline that satisfies it.

Consequence is the question of what happens to the entity, the directors and officers, the operating units and the named humans when the action produces a result that is challenged. Insurance, risk transfer and indemnity arrangements address pieces of consequence. The General Counsel function holds the question of which consequences cannot be transferred, which fall on which parties as a matter of law and which the entity must absorb regardless of how the consequences are documented in advance.

These four elements are not separable in practice. Authority without evidence cannot be defended. Risk without consequence is a notional exposure. Evidence without authority is a record of unauthorized action. Consequence without risk identification is an unprepared loss. The function that connects them produces governance. The functions that own pieces of them produce inputs. Many functions produce inputs. Only the General Counsel function structurally connects them.

This is core GC work because the GC alone connects authority, risk, evidence and consequence. The claim is not based on technical mastery, although technical literacy is required. It is not based on enforcement reach, although the function does enforce certain controls. It is not based on hierarchical position, although the function reports to the chief executive and the board. It is based on the structural feature that the four elements must be bound together for governance to exist, and that the General Counsel is the function whose role explicitly binds them.

## The Design Function

Designing the governance architecture is not a one-time event. It is an ongoing discipline. The architecture must adapt to new technologies, new regulations, new business activities, new contractual arrangements, new vendor relationships and new operational realities. Each change exposes the architecture to a question the previous version did not answer. The function that owns the architecture must continually answer the new questions, document the answers and propagate the changes through the operating functions that operate within the architecture.

In the agentic era, the design function has accelerated. New deployments arrive at a cadence the architecture cannot accommodate without continual revision. New vendor relationships, new model versions, new use cases, new agent configurations, new data flows and new automated decisions present design questions that the architecture must answer before the deployment proceeds, not after. The function that runs the governance must therefore operate at a cadence that matches the cadence of deployment, not at the quarterly or semi-annual rhythm that governance functions traditionally adopted.

This is hard. It requires the function to be structurally positioned at the deployment decision point, with the authority to halt deployments that the architecture has not yet accommodated and the capacity to update the architecture quickly enough that the halts do not become operational bottlenecks. Both capabilities are rare. Most General Counsel functions today are positioned downstream of deployment decisions, with authority to advise but not to halt and with capacity to review but not to design at the cadence the deployment cadence requires.

The functions that survive the next phase of agentic deployment will be the ones that have moved upstream, into the design conversation, with the authority and the capacity to do the work the design function requires. The functions that remain downstream will continue to produce artifacts, advise on incidents and document the consequences of designs they did not author. The first set will be running the governance. The second set will be processing the consequences of governance that nobody was running.

## Why the GC, Not Someone Else

Many alternatives have been proposed for who should run AI governance: a Chief AI Officer, a Chief Risk Officer, a Chief Information Security Officer, a Chief Privacy Officer, an AI ethics committee, an external advisory board, a cross-functional steering group. Each proposal has merit in operational terms. None of them solves the structural problem.

The structural problem is that the four elements of authority, risk, evidence and consequence must be connected, and the function that connects them must have the standing to bind the entity, the independence to refuse, the perspective to anticipate the questions that will eventually be asked and the operational reach to make the architecture stick across the entity’s activities. No function other than the General Counsel function combines all four conditions in the modern corporate form.

A Chief AI Officer typically has technical mastery and operational reach but does not bind the entity, does not have the independence to refuse a deployment the chief executive favors and does not anticipate the legal questions that will determine the consequence. A Chief Risk Officer has the perspective on risk but does not bind the entity, does not own the evidence architecture and is rarely positioned to refuse a deployment on legal grounds. A Chief Information Security Officer has technical reach and a particular form of legal exposure but does not anticipate the full range of questions that will be asked. A Chief Privacy Officer has a regulatory perspective but is bounded by the privacy domain. An AI ethics committee has the deliberative function but does not bind, does not refuse and does not own the evidence architecture. An external advisory board has independence and perspective but does not bind, does not refuse and does not operate at the cadence of deployment. A cross-functional steering group distributes the work, which is appropriate, but distributes it in a way that makes it nobody’s structural responsibility to connect the four elements.

The General Counsel function has all four conditions. The function binds the entity through the legal authority of the role. The function has the independence to refuse, structurally protected by the role’s reporting to the board on certain matters. The function has the perspective to anticipate the questions, derived from training and practice in the legal domain. The function has the operational reach to make the architecture stick, derived from the role’s involvement in contracts, authorizations, filings, litigation and regulatory matters. No other function combines all four. The proposals to assign AI governance elsewhere are proposals to assign the work to a function that lacks at least one of the conditions, and therefore lacks the structural ability to perform the binding the work requires.

This is not a claim of GC supremacy. Other functions are essential. The Chief AI Officer designs the technical architecture. The Chief Risk Officer designs the risk framework. The Chief Information Security Officer designs the security controls. The Chief Privacy Officer designs the data protection regime. The AI ethics committee deliberates. The external advisors counsel. The cross-functional group coordinates. Each is necessary. None substitutes for the binding work the General Counsel function must perform. The binding is what produces governance. Without it, the contributions of the other functions are inputs to a governance architecture that nobody is running.

## What Running the Governance Looks Like

In operational terms, running the governance produces a small number of artifacts that are recognizable to anyone who has worked inside a mature legal function. The artifacts are not framework documents. Framework documents are inputs to the work, not outputs of it. The outputs are different.

The first output is the architecture itself: the documented design that specifies which actions require which authorities, which authorities can be exercised by which roles, which evidence each authorization must produce, which controls operate at each gate and which conditions trigger which escalations. The architecture is the thing the operating functions are operating inside.

The second output is the live record of where the architecture has been tested and how it performed. Every material decision, every refused deployment, every triggered escalation, every incident and every regulatory inquiry is data about the architecture. The function that runs the governance maintains the live record and uses it to identify which parts of the architecture are working, which parts are being routed around and which parts need redesign.

The third output is the change log: the documented sequence of architectural changes, with the reason for each change, the date of effect, the impacted areas and the verification that the change has propagated through the operating functions. Architectures that do not have change logs become folklore. The change log is the discipline that prevents the architecture from drifting into something nobody can defend.

The fourth output is the readiness for the asking. At any point, a regulator, an auditor, a litigant, a Client, an investor or a board member may ask: what is the governance architecture for this. The function that runs the governance can produce the architecture, the live record of how it has performed and the change log that documents how it has evolved. The asking does not require preparation. The preparation has been continuous. The asking is a moment that the architecture has been designed to survive.

These four outputs are not glamorous. They are the work the function exists to perform. They are also rare. Most enterprises today do not have any of the four in the form the AI era requires. The architecture exists in fragments. The live record is unkept or scattered across functions. The change log does not exist as a discrete artifact. The readiness for the asking is constructed retrospectively, after the asking has occurred.

The General Counsel function that builds and maintains the four outputs is running the governance. The General Counsel function that does not is doing legal work, which is necessary but is not the same. The latter function will be increasingly asked to defend the consequences of governance that nobody was running. The former function will be increasingly recognized as the structural feature of the enterprise that distinguishes survival from settlement.

## What This Chapter Has Done

The chapter has defined what running the governance means. The General Counsel function connects authority, risk, evidence and consequence into a single architecture inside which every operation occurs.

The chapter has named the four outputs that function must produce and shown that the work is structurally assigned, not optional.

The chapter has drawn the line between binding and a story. The function that performs the work produces the binding governance demands. The function that does not produces inputs to a story the regulator will not accept.

**The General Counsel designs whether and how the enterprise can act. The architecture inside which every operation occurs is the General Counsel’s architecture, and the discipline of maintaining it is what running the governance requires. The work is not optional. It is structurally assigned. The function that performs it produces the binding that governance demands. The function that does not produces inputs to a story the regulator will not accept.**

**Final Liability rests with the Human.**

# PART IV: THE CONTRACT WAS ALWAYS THE WORKFLOW

