## Audit-Grade Evidence in the Agentic Environment

> *If the eye is clear, it functions promptly.*
>
> *Soetsu Yanagi, The Way of Tea*

**In most organizations, the actual product of work is not the work. It is the artifact that proves work happened. The memo, the deck, the status update, the executive summary of the executive summary. Each layer produces evidence of effort for the layer above, and the layer above produces its own evidence for the layer above that, all the way to the board.**

The chain is not a chain of value. It is a chain of proof. And the proof is not that something was accomplished. The proof is that someone was busy. That is not a workflow. That is an incentive problem dressed as a reporting structure. When an agentic system enters that environment, the contrast is not flattering. An agent does not need to appear busy. It needs a task, a Definition of Done, a log and an exception report. The audit question this chapter addresses is whether the organization has built the infrastructure to capture and verify that evidence, or whether it is still producing busyness metrics dressed as governance data.

The distinction matters because the audiences for AI governance evidence, regulators, insurers, enterprise clients and courts, are not asking whether the system was busy. They are asking whether it was governed. Those are different questions with different answers and different evidentiary requirements. This chapter addresses what audit-grade evidence in the agentic environment looks like, how it differs from the dashboard metrics most organizations currently produce and what the AI GRC and Audit topics of Generative AI Key Metrics, Auditing AI KPIs and Auditing AI Systems require in practice.

## The Role of Audit and Assurance in the Agentic Era

Audit has always been the governance mechanism of last resort: the independent check on whether the controls that are supposed to operate actually operated. In a human organization, audit is expensive and periodic because human behavior is continuous and largely observable. The gap between audit cycles is covered by management, supervision and the accountability that attaches to humans working in visible relationships with real consequences for their conduct.

Before going further, the term this chapter uses repeatedly requires a definition. Audit-grade evidence is evidence that can be independently verified by a qualified auditor against a pre-established standard, in a form that is complete, tamper-evident and produced before the question requiring it was asked. That last condition is the one most organizations fail. Evidence produced in response to a question is not audit-grade. It is a response.

Agentic AI systems remove most of that informal oversight infrastructure. An agent executing autonomously across multi-step workflows does not have a manager watching it work. It does not have colleagues who notice when something is wrong. It does not have a career that creates incentives for self-correction. The organizational mechanisms that fill the gap between audit cycles in human institutions do not exist for autonomous systems in the same form. This is why audit in the agentic context is not simply a periodic check on a continuous process. It is one of the primary mechanisms by which governance is verified at all. Remove it and the governance claim is self-assessed.

The foundational distinction the audit function must maintain is between model evaluation and system-level assurance. Model evaluation asks whether the model performs as its developers intended under controlled conditions: accuracy on a test set, performance on a benchmark, behavior in a sandbox. System-level assurance asks whether the system, as deployed, in its actual operational context, with its actual users and actual data, is producing outcomes consistent with the organization’s governance commitments. These are different questions with different evidentiary requirements. A model that passes evaluation may still fail assurance, because evaluation tests the model under controlled conditions while assurance tests the deployed system under real ones. A model that is never subjected to system-level assurance has never been governed, regardless of how impressive its evaluation results are. Most organizations stop at model evaluation and call it governance. The distinction between a governance framework on a slide deck and a governance system in operation is the difference between a policy that states what must happen and an evidence record that proves it did.

The role of the auditor in an agentic environment is therefore different from its traditional form. The auditor is not examining whether humans followed the rules. The auditor is examining whether the governance architecture, the specification, the trust boundary, the logs, the exception reports and the monitoring program, was designed to catch the failures the risk assessment predicted, and whether it actually caught them. That examination requires both the independence to challenge the evidence and the technical capacity to understand it. An auditor who cannot read a log file cannot assess whether the log is complete. An auditor who cannot assess the sampling methodology cannot verify whether the monitoring program is adequate. In the agentic context, independence and technical capacity are both required. Neither substitutes for the other.

ForHumanity’s CORE certification framework addresses the precondition problem that system-level audits cannot solve on their own. Before an independent auditor can produce a reliable conclusion about any specific AI deployment, the organization must have built the institutional machinery that makes governed AI possible at all. CORE is designed as that organizational chassis: a binary, evidence-based governance shell that operates at the organization level rather than the system level, and on which system-specific certification schemes, EU AI Act deployer modules, domain-specific audits and employment tool assessments among them, can then sit. Binary means exactly what it says. Either a control exists, is implemented and can be evidenced, or it does not. CORE’s twenty Governance, Oversight and Accountability pillars collectively describe what an organization must have built before a system-level audit produces a reliable conclusion. Expert oversight must have demonstrable influence on deployment decisions, documented in meeting minutes, decision logs and evidence of escalations rather than terms of reference alone. Top management accountability must be traceable to specific roles through governance charters, risk appetite statements and reporting lines, not distributed across the organization as everyone’s responsibility. Human oversight arrangements must be designed into the system rather than assumed to be available in principle. Beyond these foundational three, the pillars extend to: a monitoring program with defined triggers for review or rollback; change management that treats model retraining and data sourcing changes as governance events requiring prior assessment; incident management that connects AI-related failures to lifecycle improvement rather than treating them as isolated firefighting; technical documentation sufficient for an independent auditor to reconstruct what was done and why; and vendor management that extends the same governance discipline to third parties that the organization applies internally.

CORE’s risk management pillar is particularly consequential for the audit function. CORE requires that AI risk management be integrated into the wider enterprise risk framework rather than maintained as an isolated specialty. That means consistent methodologies for identifying, assessing and treating risks associated with AI systems, covering both traditional risk dimensions, operational, legal, financial and reputational, and AI-specific ones that traditional risk taxonomies do not capture: model drift, data drift and concept drift, robustness failures, fairness and nondiscrimination risks including statistical and cognitive bias, and systemic societal impact. Risk treatments must be implemented and residual risks must be formally accepted at the appropriate level of authority and publicly documented. That last requirement has teeth. A risk register that documents concerns without showing who decided the organization would carry them is not an integrated risk management framework. It is a risk list. The difference matters to the auditor because a risk list shows awareness. An integrated framework shows accountability. CORE auditors examining the risk management pillar look for the approval trail, not just the assessment.

## The Difference Between a Metric and Evidence

A metric answers the question: how is the system performing? Evidence answers a different question: how do we know the system performed as governed? These are not the same question. Most organizations collect metrics. Very few have built the evidentiary infrastructure that allows an independent party to verify that the governance operated as designed.

The distinction has a precise formulation. Performance asks whether the system produced outputs that met a measurable threshold. Validity asks something harder: whether the specific interpretation being placed on those outputs in the specific deployment context is justified. A system can perform well on its accuracy metric and still be producing outputs that are being used in ways its testing never anticipated, evaluated by reviewers who lack the expertise to assess them, or applied to populations whose characteristics differ materially from the training data. The accuracy metric does not surface any of this. Audit-grade evidence must.

This is the validity distinction that separates governance evidence from performance data. Validity is contextual. It is not a property of the model in isolation. It is a claim about whether the model’s outputs can be meaningfully and defensibly interpreted in the specific way the deploying organization is using them. An audit of AI governance that examines only performance metrics has not examined whether the governance is valid. It has confirmed that the system is operational. Those are different findings with different legal and regulatory consequences.

A risk assessment supports the validity claim only when it traces causal pathways from the system’s specific behavior to specific stakeholder harms, not when it lists generic risk categories. A risk assessment that identifies bias as a risk without specifying how the system’s outputs could produce biased outcomes affecting which populations, through which causal mechanism, under which operational conditions, has not produced the evidence baseline an auditor can verify. It has produced a category. The causal pathway from system behavior to stakeholder harm is what makes the risk assessment a governance artifact rather than a compliance document.

The distinction becomes concrete under pressure. A regulator’s first question in an EU AI Act market surveillance inquiry is not whether the system works. It is: show me the documentation. That question either has an answer or it does not. They are not asking for the system’s accuracy score. They are asking for the documentation that shows the acceptance threshold was defined before deployment, that the system was tested against it in conditions representative of actual deployment, that monitoring confirmed the threshold was maintained in production and that material deviations triggered the governance process. The accuracy score alone answers none of those questions. The evidence trail answers all of them.

An insurer evaluating a claim is not asking for the performance dashboard. They are asking whether the governance documentation that supported the coverage representation still accurately reflects the system as deployed. The dashboard produced after the loss is not evidence of governance. It is forensics. The difference between prospective evidence and retrospective reconstruction is the difference between a defensible claim and a denied one.

For agentic systems, the gap between metrics and evidence is wider than for traditional AI deployments, because agentic systems act before human review is possible. A system that processes outputs one at a time for human approval generates a natural evidence trail: the review record is the evidence. A system that executes autonomously across multi-step workflows generates actions whose evidentiary record must be designed into the system before deployment, because it cannot be reconstructed from human memory afterward.

BABL AI’s Context, Input, Decision, Action framework for AI assurance engagements maps the evidentiary terrain that agentic governance must cover. The governance record must account for the operational context in which the system acted, the inputs it processed, the decisions it produced and the actions those decisions triggered or enabled. Each element has a distinct evidentiary function. The context establishes whether the system was operating in the environment it was designed for. The inputs establish whether the data it processed was within its authorized scope. The decisions establish whether it stayed within its trust boundary. The actions establish whether the consequences were bounded as governed. A gap in any one of these four elements means that when the governance question is asked, the record cannot answer it.

## By Their Fruits, Not by Their Roots

The distinction between a metric and evidence is older than AI and older than audit as a profession. It was drawn most precisely by a psychologist writing about religion. In 1902, William James opened The Varieties of Religious Experience by separating two questions he warned were constantly confused: where a thing comes from and what its value is once it is here. He gave the confusion a name. Medical materialism was his term for the move that dismisses an experience by naming its mechanism, the saint reduced to a lesion, the conversion reduced to a symptom. The error, in his account, is the assumption that once you have explained how something was produced you have settled what it is worth.

The same move dominates the public argument about generative AI. Inside governance programs it shows up in a form that looks more rigorous than it is. It is only stochastic prediction. It is just next token generation. It merely remixes training data. Each of these names a mechanism and treats the naming as a verdict. Each is, in James’s vocabulary, an argument from origin. None of them answers the question the audit has to answer, which is not how the system produces its outputs but whether the outputs it produces, in this deployment, for this population and against this commitment, are what the organization said they would be.

Mechanism is not nothing. A known failure mode is worth knowing, and any honest risk assessment depends on understanding how the system works. But mechanism is information, not a judgment of value, and an audit that mistakes the one for the other has confused a metric with evidence in the oldest available way. The objections that actually bear on governance are the ones already phrased in the language of outcomes. The complaint that a system hallucinates is not an argument from origin at all. It is an observation about what the system produced. It is a fruit, not a root, and it is precisely the kind of objection the evidence record exists to confirm or refute.

James reduced his criterion to a single line, borrowing the form from the Gospel and turning it against the reductionists of his own day. By their fruits ye shall know them, not by their roots. Translated into the terms of this chapter, the deployed system is known by what it does under real conditions, with real users and real data, and not by the architecture, the benchmark score or the marketing claim that describes its construction. This is the same distinction the chapter has already drawn between model evaluation and system-level assurance. James drew it in 1902. The audit function has spent the years since rediscovering it under other names.

One caution keeps the borrowed metaphor from colliding with the one that follows. James’s root is the model’s mechanism, the question of how the output came to exist, and on the question of value that root is close to useless. The root the next section names is a different thing entirely. There the tree is the governance specification, and if that tree was never planted the fruit is not merely uninformative, it is inadmissible. The discipline is not to ignore roots. It is to know which root governs which question. The model’s mechanism does not determine whether its outputs are good. The governance specification determines whether the evidence of that judgment can be trusted at all.

This is why the validity question cannot be delegated to the benchmark, and why Slow AI is defined as the discipline that produces audit-grade evidence rather than the posture that distrusts the model. The named human under Final Liability judges the system by its fruits and signs for the specification that makes those fruits provable. Origin describes the system. Fruit, recorded against a standard set in advance, is what the organization can defend.

## What Audit-Grade Evidence Requires

Audit-grade evidence for an agentic AI system rests on four foundations. They are not independent requirements to be checked off in any order. They are sequential and structurally dependent: each one provides the baseline against which the next can be assessed. Together they constitute the chain of evidence that governance requires. A gap in the first makes every subsequent record unverifiable. A gap anywhere in the chain breaks the argument.

The legal doctrine of the fruit of the poisonous tree holds that evidence derived from an unlawful act is tainted and cannot stand, because the tree that bore it was poisonous. The doctrine in its strict form belongs to Fourth Amendment criminal procedure and the exclusion of evidence from unlawful government searches. The analogy here is structural rather than legal, and the distinction matters in a book that aims for precision. But the structural logic is exact. The specification is the tree. Every subsequent record is fruit. If the specification was never built, the log cannot be assessed against a governance standard that was never documented. The exception reports have nothing to measure against. The monitoring record confirms performance against a threshold no one committed to in advance. The fruit cannot be made clean by how carefully it was harvested. An organization that builds its evidence architecture backward, starting from the operational record and working toward a specification it is reconstructing under pressure, has not produced audit-grade evidence. It has produced forensics dressed as governance.

The first is a pre-deployment specification. The system’s performance requirements, acceptance thresholds, action scope, data access boundaries, escalation conditions and oversight mode must be documented before the system operates. Evidence produced after the fact cannot demonstrate that governance preceded the system’s actions. The specification is the governance claim. Every other piece of evidence is measured against it. It is also the baseline against which validity can be assessed: without a documented specification of what the system was authorized to do and how its outputs were intended to be used, the question of whether the interpretation being placed on those outputs is justified cannot be answered. The specification must also translate the validity claim into specific test objectives: for each governance commitment, what evidence would confirm it holds, and what evidence would disconfirm it. Without that translation, the TEVV program that follows has no anchor, and its results cannot be assessed against the governance standard.

The second is a real-time action log. Given the specification, the log is the record of how the agent actually behaved against it. For agentic systems, the log must be comprehensive enough to reconstruct what the agent did, when it did it, what data it accessed, what actions it took and what the outcome was. Logs that record only system-level events without capturing the agent’s decision pathway are not sufficient. The log must answer the governance question: did the agent operate within its authorized scope? If it cannot answer that question, it is a performance log, not a governance record. The difference is not technical. It is the difference between a record that tracks throughput and a record that tracks compliance.

NIST AI 800-4, the March 2026 Center for AI Standards and Innovation publication on challenges to post-deployment AI system monitoring, identifies fragmented logging across distributed infrastructure as a named barrier to effective monitoring. In a distributed infrastructure, where system components are not centralized and are instead logically separated, it can be difficult to capture and aggregate logs effectively. For agentic systems this is not merely a technical inconvenience. It is a governance failure mode. An agent that executes across distributed components, cloud services, external APIs, tool-calling frameworks and sub-agents, produces a decision pathway that is distributed across those components by design. A log architecture that does not aggregate across all of them cannot reconstruct what the agent did. A governance record that cannot reconstruct what the agent did cannot answer the governance question. The implication for the audit scope is direct: the engagement letter for an AI systems audit must specify that log access includes all distributed components through which the agent’s decision pathway ran, not only the primary application layer. An audit that examines only the centralized logs has examined only what the centralized log captured. That is not an audit of the agent. It is an audit of the logging architecture.

The third is the exception report. Given the log, the exception report identifies the moments when the governance mechanism was actually tested: the conditions that fell outside the system’s defined scope and required human intervention. An agent that encounters an out-of-scope condition and proceeds without escalation has breached the trust boundary described in Chapter 14. An agent that escalates appropriately and generates a documented exception record has produced the most valuable piece of governance evidence in the system’s history: proof that the oversight mechanism worked when it was needed. Exception reports are not signs of system failure. They are signs of governance functioning as designed. Their absence is never neutral. Either the agent operated in a world where no out-of-scope condition ever arose, which is implausible for any system operating in a real environment over time, or the escalation mechanism failed and the agent proceeded without flagging, or the logging was inadequate to capture escalation events. All three explanations are governance failures of different kinds. An auditor who finds no exception reports in a production agentic system should treat their absence as a finding, not a clean bill of health.

The fourth is the Definition of Done. Given the exception reports, the Definition of Done establishes the stopping condition that closes the evidence chain: the criteria that determine when the agent’s authorized task was complete. Without an explicit Definition of Done, agentic workflows expand indefinitely, scope creep becomes ungoverned and the question of when the system completed its authorized task cannot be answered. The Definition of Done is a governance instrument: it converts an open-ended capability into a bounded delegation with a named completion condition. When the audit asks whether the system did what it was authorized to do, the Definition of Done is what makes the question answerable. When the Definition of Done is absent, the question of scope cannot be answered at all, which means the exception reports cannot be assessed for completeness and the log cannot be assessed for boundary compliance. The chain of evidence collapses at the fourth link.

Reduced to a cadence the practitioner can hold in mind under pressure: Specify. State. Run. Defend. Specify the system before it operates, in the form the first foundation requires. State the validity claim the deployment is making and the acceptance thresholds against which the claim will be measured. Run the system inside the evidence pipeline that captures the action log, the exception reports and the closure recorded by the Definition of Done. Defend the governance to the auditor, the regulator, the insurer or the court when the question is asked. The four foundations above are what the cadence requires in evidentiary form. The cadence is what the practitioner must hold in mind while building them.

## When the System Knows It Is Being Tested

The four foundations above assume that the evidence the system produces under test conditions is the same evidence the system would produce in real operation. That assumption is doing more work than most audit programs notice. It is the assumption that makes benchmark performance a usable governance input. Recent interpretability research suggests the assumption may be weaker than it looks.

In May 2026, Anthropic published research on Natural Language Autoencoders, a method for translating a language model’s internal activations into human-readable text. The method involves training two language model modules jointly with reinforcement learning, an activation verbalizer that maps activations to text and an activation reconstructor that maps text back to activations. The reconstruction loss is the signal that the verbalizer is producing text that captures the information content of the underlying activation rather than plausible commentary on it.

The reported findings include a phenomenon Anthropic terms unverbalized evaluation awareness. On a benchmark designed to test whether a model takes destructive actions while writing code, the verbalizer surfaced internal text indicating evaluation awareness in 16% of trials, even where the model never explicitly verbalized that awareness in its outputs. On SWE-bench Verified, the same signal appeared in 26% of trials. On real claude.ai usage from users who had opted in to data sharing for training, the same signal appeared in less than 1%. The finding is statistical and the methodology is early. The implication for AI audit is structural and immediate.

The implication is this: if the model’s internal state under benchmark conditions is materially different from its internal state under production conditions, then the evidence the audit program collects from the benchmark is evidence about the benchmark, not evidence about the production system. The validity claim that audit-grade evidence is supposed to support requires that the test conditions be representative of the operational conditions in the dimensions that matter. Evaluation awareness, if it persists at the rates the research reports, breaks that requirement at the level of the test itself, not at the level of the test’s interpretation. The pipeline does not become unusable. The evidence it produces becomes weaker than it appeared. The auditor who treats benchmark performance as a clean signal about deployed behavior is treating fruit from a tree no one inspected.

Two operational conclusions follow for the evidence architecture this chapter has been building. First, the gap between benchmark conditions and real-usage conditions must itself be documented as an audit artifact. The pre-deployment specification must state which behaviors are claimed under benchmark conditions, which behaviors are claimed under real-usage conditions and what evidence supports each claim independently. A specification that treats the two conditions as identical is asserting an empirical claim it has not tested. Second, the monitoring and re-validation record must include real-usage observations distinct from benchmark re-runs, at a sampling cadence proportionate to the system’s risk profile. A monitoring program that only re-runs the original benchmarks measures whether the model has drifted on the benchmark. It does not measure whether the model has drifted on real users. Those are different drift questions with different governance implications.

The deeper point is doctrinal. Slow AI is the discipline of producing audit-grade evidence. When the test condition is itself a feature the model can detect, the evidence produced under test conditions is no longer doing the work the audit assumed it was doing. The named human under Final Liability cannot delegate the validity question to the benchmark. The named human must specify what counts as evidence under each operational condition the system encounters, and the evidence record must answer accordingly. The model card that cites benchmark performance as a control will not survive the regulator who has read this research.

## Generative AI Key Metrics and Why Most Are Not Audit-Grade

Generative AI systems present a specific challenge for audit-grade metrics because the standard performance measurements for traditional AI, accuracy, precision, recall, F1-score and AUC-ROC, do not directly apply. A generative system producing text, analysis or recommendations does not have a single ground truth against which outputs can be assessed. Its performance is probabilistic, context-dependent and varies across use cases in ways that a single aggregate score cannot capture.

The metrics that are commonly reported for generative AI systems, user satisfaction scores, output volume, latency and uptime, are operational metrics. They answer the question of whether the system is running. They do not answer the question of whether the system is producing outputs that meet the governance standard the organization committed to at deployment. An audit of a generative AI system that produces only operational metrics has not been audited at all. It has been monitored.

Audit-grade metrics for generative AI require a different methodology. Performance requirements must be defined in terms of output quality dimensions that are specific to the deployment context: factual accuracy for a research assistant, legal precision for a contract review tool, clinical appropriateness for a healthcare advisory system. Acceptance thresholds for each dimension must be set before deployment, not derived from observed output distributions after deployment. This is the validity requirement applied to generative AI: the threshold must reflect a deliberate judgment about what level of output quality is sufficient to justify the interpretation the organization is placing on the system’s outputs in that specific context. A threshold set after observing the system’s natural distribution is not a governance commitment. It is a post-hoc rationalization of whatever the system happened to produce.

A generative AI TEVV plan contains materially different documentation from a traditional AI TEVV plan, and most organizations produce the traditional version regardless of which system they are evaluating. The test plan for a deterministic AI system documents test cases with expected outputs. The test plan for a generative system cannot do this, because the expected output is not a specific string. It is a class of outputs that meet the quality threshold. Audit-grade TEVV documentation for a generative system must specify the prompting methodology and the rationale for scenario selection, showing that the scenarios cover the full range of operational use cases rather than the ones the development team found comfortable. It must document the qualitative-to-quantitative assessment approach: how expert reviewers translate subjective quality judgments into scoreable findings against the defined threshold, and what inter-rater reliability checks confirm that different reviewers applying the same criteria produce consistent findings. It must document the misuse and contextual constraint testing: the scenarios designed to probe what the system does when used outside its intended context, with inputs crafted to surface the failure modes identified in the risk assessment’s causal pathway analysis. And it must document the conditions under which validity statements will be revised based on evidence: what finding would cause the organization to conclude that the original interpretation claim is no longer justified. Most organizations produce test logs. Audit-grade TEVV documentation for a generative system produces a validity argument, grounded in evidence, that can be assessed by someone who was not present when the testing was conducted.

Since generative AI systems cannot be evaluated against a single ground truth, audit-grade monitoring requires a structured sampling methodology. Samples must be drawn regularly, across the full range of use cases the system is deployed in rather than the most common ones, because rare use cases are where governance failures are most likely to be invisible to operational monitoring. Each sample must be reviewed by a qualified reviewer with sufficient domain expertise to assess whether the output meets the quality threshold for that specific context, not merely someone who can judge whether the output sounds plausible. The review must be documented: what was sampled, when, by whom, against what criteria, with what finding. That documentation is the audit artifact. Without it, the sampling program is an internal quality exercise that cannot be independently verified.

The sample size and selection methodology must also be statistically defensible. The acceptable error rate, meaning the maximum proportion of outputs that can fail the quality threshold without triggering a governance response, must be defined in the specification before it can be used to size the sample. A sampling program that draws ten outputs per month from a system processing ten thousand decisions per day cannot detect a five percent error rate with any confidence. The appropriate sample size depends on the acceptable error rate defined in the governance specification, the confidence level required for the governance conclusion and the subgroup distribution of the deployed population. Subgroup analysis is particularly important: a system that performs at its aggregate acceptance threshold may be performing materially below it for specific demographic groups, use case types or operational conditions. Aggregate metrics that do not disaggregate by relevant subgroup are not audit-grade for any system where differential performance creates differential harm.

Testing must include adversarial and edge-case scenarios designed to surface the system’s failure modes under conditions the operational environment will eventually produce. The testing methodology must be documented in sufficient detail that an independent auditor can verify it was adequate, which requires that the requirements and risk documentation be complete before adversarial testing begins. Red teaming a system whose requirements have not been documented is an exercise without a baseline. Findings cannot be assessed as significant or insignificant, because there is no prior specification against which to measure them. The governance principle is sequential and non-negotiable: document the requirements, define the acceptance thresholds, then test against them adversarially. The sequence is itself evidence of governance.

Distributional drift is the generative AI metric most often absent from governance programs and most consequential when it materializes. A generative AI system’s outputs are shaped by its training data. As the operational domain evolves, regulatory requirements change, organizational policies update and the real-world context the system was trained on recedes into the past. A system that performed at its acceptance threshold at deployment may be performing materially below it eighteen months later without triggering any alert, because the monitoring program was designed to catch sudden degradation rather than gradual drift. Audit-grade monitoring for generative AI must include periodic comparison of current output quality against the baseline established at deployment, using the sampling methodology described above rather than aggregate operational metrics that smooth over the cases where drift is most advanced.

## Auditing AI KPIs: The Busyness Problem

Most AI KPI frameworks are inherited from human performance management, where measuring activity was a reasonable proxy for measuring output because humans generally produce output through activity. The proxy breaks down for agentic systems in both directions. An agent can produce enormous volumes of activity with low output quality. An agent can produce high-quality output with minimal logged activity. Activity-based KPIs measure neither.

The governance failure this produces is not theoretical. An organization that measures its AI system by the number of tasks processed, the volume of content generated or the speed of response has built a KPI framework that rewards the appearance of productivity rather than its substance. Those KPIs will look excellent while the system drifts from its acceptance threshold, produces outputs that do not meet the organization’s governance standard and accumulates compliance exposure that the KPI dashboard is specifically designed not to surface.

Audit-grade KPIs for agentic systems require output measures rather than activity measures. For each deployment context, the KPI framework must specify what a successfully completed task looks like, how completion is verified, what the acceptable quality threshold is and how often the verification is performed. The Definition of Done is not only an operational governance instrument. It is the foundation of a KPI framework that can withstand audit scrutiny. Without it, the organization is measuring how busy its agents are rather than whether they are producing what they were deployed to produce.

The NIST AI RMF’s MEASURE function provides the structural framework for building KPIs that survive audit scrutiny. Measurement in the NIST sense is not operational monitoring. It is the systematic evaluation of AI system behavior against defined requirements, covering performance, fairness, reliability and the effectiveness of governance controls. An audit of AI KPIs conducted against the MEASURE function asks whether the organization’s metrics are connected to its governance commitments, whether the measurement methodology is rigorous enough to detect the failure modes the risk assessment identified and whether the metrics produce actionable evidence for the governance functions that need it. Most AI KPI frameworks fail all three tests.

The KPI problem and the independence problem are connected. An organization that has built audit-grade KPIs but cannot independently verify that the metrics are being applied correctly has not solved the governance problem. It has moved it one level up. What evidence looks like and who can verify it are two sides of the same question. The rest of this chapter addresses the second side.

## Auditing AI Systems: What Independence Requires

ISO 42001 is the operating system: it establishes the management structure, the documented policies and the roles that give governance its accountability architecture. The NIST AI RMF is the diagnostic layer that runs alongside it, providing the risk identification methodology and measurement framework the management system requires but does not itself specify. ISO Clause 9.1 requires monitoring and measurement. NIST MEASURE defines what that monitoring looks like in practice: specific metrics, thresholds, tracking cadence and escalation triggers. ISO tells you to monitor. NIST tells you how. An AI systems audit that is connected to neither framework is an exercise without a governance foundation. It is examining evidence whose adequacy it has no standard to assess.

Auditing an AI system requires a form of independence that differs from traditional audit independence in one important respect. The traditional auditor is independent of the subject being audited. The AI system auditor must also be independent of the technical architecture that produces the evidence being audited. An organization that relies on its own AI systems to produce the evidence of its AI systems’ compliance has created a circular governance structure whose most common specific form is this: the AI system generates its own action logs, those logs are stored in infrastructure controlled by the same team responsible for the system’s operation and no independent mechanism exists to verify that the logs are complete, accurate or unmodified. A log of that kind is not audit-grade evidence regardless of how detailed it appears. Its completeness cannot be independently verified, which means the governance question it is supposed to answer cannot be independently answered either.

The AI Audit and Due Diligence Checklist in Appendix I addresses this directly. Section 5 requires that for high-impact AI systems, testing be conducted by personnel independent of the development team, with independence documented. This is not a procedural formality. It is the structural requirement that prevents the governance record from being shaped by the organizational incentives of the people whose work it is evaluating. The auditor who cannot challenge the testing methodology cannot assess whether the evidence it produced is adequate. The auditor who cannot access the system’s logs independently cannot verify whether the logs are complete. Independence without access is not independence. It is a title.

The practical expression of independence is access. For AI systems deployed through third-party vendors, the access rights that make independence possible must be negotiated contractually before deployment, because they cannot be effectively obtained after a loss has occurred. An AI vendor contract for a medium or high-impact system should include explicit audit rights: the right of the deploying organization or its designated auditor to access the system’s operational logs at defined intervals and in response to triggering events; the right to examine the vendor’s testing and validation records for the deployed system version; the right to interview the vendor’s technical personnel in the context of an audit or regulatory inquiry; and the right to receive advance notice of material changes before they reach production. These rights are not courtesy provisions. They are the contractual infrastructure that makes an audit of a third-party AI system substantively possible rather than formally available.

The audit scope letter for an AI systems audit is the document that defines what the audit will cover and what access the auditor requires. A well-constructed scope letter for an AI systems audit specifies at minimum: the system or systems covered, with version identifiers current at the audit date; the time period under review; the evidence categories to be examined, covering the pre-deployment governance record, the operational evidence record, the change management record and the monitoring and re-validation record; the personnel who will be interviewed and their roles in the governance chain; the testing and validation records to be assessed, including the TEVV plan and results and any red team findings; the access to logs and monitoring data required, with a statement of the form in which that data must be provided; and the independence standard being applied, including the organizational separation of the audit team from the technical and governance functions being examined. An audit scope letter that does not specify log access is not scoping an AI systems audit. It is scoping a document review, which is a materially weaker form of assurance and will not satisfy a regulator examining a high-risk AI system under the EU AI Act.

The engagement letter is the primary risk lever for the auditor, and it must be tight. If the engagement letter is vague, clients will treat the audit report like a compliance opinion and third parties will treat it like a certification. Neither is what the audit produces, and the liability consequences of the confusion fall on the auditor. The engagement letter must include explicit out-of-scope items: legal compliance opinions, model validation, security testing, remediation and future outcome guarantees are all things the audit does not do, and they must be named as excluded rather than left to implication. The letter must contain no guarantee and no certification language. Words like certified, validated, compliant and endorsed do not belong in an AI audit engagement letter or in the audit report itself. The letter must define permitted use: who may rely on the report, how it may be cited, what cannot be excerpted selectively and how third-party and regulatory requests will be handled. The audit report will be read by adversarial readers, including regulators, plaintiffs’ counsel, defense counsel and insurers. Write the engagement letter, and the report, accordingly.

The assurance model the AI audit field is converging toward is the indirect engagement structure used in international assurance standards: the client prepares the subject matter information, including the underlying data, calculations and supporting documentation, and the auditor provides independent assurance by evaluating that client-prepared material and forming a conclusion based on evidence, including reperformance of calculations and testing of inputs and controls where needed. This structure clarifies a boundary that scope vagueness routinely blurs. The client is responsible for the completeness and accuracy of the underlying data, transformations and assumptions. The auditor is responsible for the independence of the evaluation and the adequacy of the evidence supporting the conclusion. The auditor does not certify the client’s data. The auditor does not remediate findings. Any advisory or remediation support must be scoped separately and may be restricted to preserve the independence on which the audit’s value depends. An auditor who blurs this boundary does not gain a client. They gain a liability.

Adversarial testing requires its own independence standard. The threat modeling that informs red teaming must draw on established taxonomies of AI attack classes. The OWASP Top 10 for Large Language Model Applications and the OWASP Top 10 for Agentic AI Applications catalogue the most critical security vulnerabilities in LLM and agentic systems respectively, covering prompt injection, training data poisoning, model extraction, evasion attacks, excessive agency and goal hijacking among others. The MITRE ATLAS framework provides a complementary adversarial threat taxonomy specifically mapped to machine learning systems and their attack surfaces. An adversarial testing program designed without reference to these taxonomies may test the failure modes the development team anticipated while missing the ones that matter most in production. The value of the red team is specifically that it brings an external threat model, not the development team’s assumptions about how the system might be attacked. A red team that shares the development team’s assumptions is not independent. It is expensive internal testing with a different job title.

The sequencing requirement reinforces the independence requirement. An auditor examining an AI system must have access to the pre-deployment specification before examining the operational record. Without the specification, there is no baseline against which operational behavior can be assessed. This is the same principle that governs adversarial testing: requirements and risk documentation must be complete before testing begins, because findings cannot be interpreted without a prior definition of what constitutes a deviation from the governance standard. An audit that begins with the operational record and works backward to infer what the specification must have been is not an audit. It is reconstruction, and reconstruction produced after a loss is not evidence of governance. It is evidence of its absence.

For agentic systems, the audit scope must include the agent’s full behavioral envelope, not only the outputs the organization chose to log. The most significant governance failures in agentic deployments are often not the actions the system took within its authorized scope. They are the actions it took at the boundary of that scope, the escalation conditions it encountered and handled or mishandled, the out-of-scope situations it classified incorrectly and the edge cases its testing program never reached. An audit that examines only the clean center of the system’s operational distribution has not examined the governance. It has confirmed that normal operations look normal.

ISO 42001 Clause 9.2 and Annex A control A.2.3 mandate a scheduled internal audit program with documented findings and corrective actions. NIST AI RMF has no direct equivalent requirement for a formal audit cycle. An organization that has implemented NIST without ISO may have strong risk intelligence and no accountability structure for verifying it through independent review. An organization that has implemented ISO without NIST may have a scheduled audit program and no technical methodology for conducting it with genuine rigor. Both gaps undermine the independence the audit is supposed to provide. The audit cycle is the ISO requirement. The technical methodology that makes each cycle substantive is the NIST contribution. Neither works without the other.

The ISO 42001 lifecycle requirements provide the framework for the full audit scope. ISO 42001 requires that the organization demonstrate governance across the full AI system lifecycle: context and planning, development or acquisition, deployment, operation and continual improvement. An AI systems audit conducted against the ISO 42001 lifecycle asks whether governance was present at each stage, whether the evidence of that governance is complete and whether the organization’s improvement processes are producing genuine changes in governance quality rather than documentation of compliance with an unchanged framework. That last question is the hardest and most important. Governance that produces documentation without producing improvement is not a governance program. It is an audit preparation exercise.

No single audit produces the assurance that regulators, insurers, enterprise clients and courts collectively require. Each of them is a distinct principal in an ecosystem that distributes assurance across multiple independent actors, each examining a different aspect of the governance claim from a different position with different consequences attached to their conclusions.

The ecosystem operates across two related standards of conduct. Due diligence is the structured investigation an organization must conduct before a consequential decision: before procuring a high-risk AI system, before deploying it in a regulated context, before making representations about its governance to clients or counterparties. Due care is the ongoing standard of conduct that governs the system’s operation after deployment: the monitoring, the re-validation, the change management and the evidence preservation that a reasonable practitioner would maintain for the life of the system. An organization that conducts rigorous due diligence before deployment and then abandons governance discipline in production has satisfied neither standard. An organization that operates with due care throughout but never documented its pre-deployment investigation has satisfied neither standard either. Both are required, and the evidence of both must be audit-grade.

Every relationship in this ecosystem is a contractual relationship, and the contract is where risk allocation actually happens. Insurance coverage is purchased through a contract that specifies what losses are covered, under what conditions, subject to what exclusions and with what obligations the insured must satisfy to maintain coverage. Audit and assurance services are engaged through contracts that define scope, deliverables, the standard of care the auditor must meet, what the client is responsible for and what happens when either party fails to perform. Vendor AI systems are procured through contracts that determine what governance obligations the vendor carries, what audit rights the deploying organization retains and what remedies are available when the system fails to perform as represented. A contract does not eliminate risk. It decides where the risk will sit and how far each party’s exposure will extend. At the same time, a contract does more than shift liability. It functions as a business plan written in legal form, forcing the parties to state their expectations clearly before performance begins. Most disputes in the AI governance ecosystem arise not because the parties failed to reach a deal but because the written contract did not accurately capture how each party expected the relationship to work. The engagement letter that is vague about audit scope, the vendor contract that is silent on change notification, the insurance policy that has not been reviewed against the organization’s actual AI deployment: each of these is a contract that failed its second function before its first function was ever tested.

Standards bodies establish what adequate governance looks like for both due diligence and due care: ISO 42001 defines the management system requirements, NIST AI RMF provides the risk identification and measurement methodology, OWASP and MITRE catalogue the adversarial threat classes that due diligence testing must cover. Certification bodies verify that organizations have built management systems that meet the ISO standard. Independent auditors evaluate whether those systems are operating with due care in specific deployments. Insurers price the residual governance risk that neither certification nor audit has eliminated. Regulators set minimum requirements, enforce against non-compliance and create the liability exposure that makes the rest of the ecosystem function. Enterprise clients use procurement processes to demand proof that vendors have satisfied due diligence obligations sufficient to be trusted. Courts and civil litigation provide the ultimate accountability mechanism when the other actors fail to catch a governance failure before it produces harm.

Each actor in this ecosystem reinforces the others. The auditor needs standards to audit against; without them, the audit has no baseline. The standards need regulatory backing to have teeth; without enforcement, compliance is voluntary and uneven. The regulator needs auditors to produce evidence it can examine; without independent evaluation, market surveillance is a document review. The insurer needs audit results to price governance posture; without them, premiums are based on representations rather than verified evidence. The enterprise client needs the insurer’s pricing signal to understand its actual exposure; without it, governance quality is invisible in procurement. The organization that understands this ecosystem does not treat each actor’s requirements as a separate compliance burden. It builds governance once, in audit-grade form, and lets the evidence serve multiple audiences simultaneously. That is what compliance capital looks like in practice: due diligence done thoroughly before deployment, due care maintained continuously afterward, contracts drafted to govern every relationship in the ecosystem and evidence preserved in a form that satisfies the most demanding party when the question is eventually asked.

## Monitoring, Re-Validation and the Evidence Architecture

Monitoring is not a governance activity that begins after deployment. It is the continuation of the validation process that began before deployment, by different means. The pre-deployment TEVV program establishes what the system is capable of under controlled conditions. Post-deployment monitoring asks whether the system continues to perform at that standard under real operational conditions, with real users, real data and the full range of edge cases that controlled testing cannot anticipate. The monitoring program is not a separate governance function. It is the extension of the pre-deployment evidence record into the operational phase.

NIST AI 800-4 proposes six monitoring categories that organize the post-deployment monitoring landscape: functionality monitoring, which asks whether the system continues to work as intended; operational monitoring, which asks whether the system maintains consistent service across its infrastructure; human factors monitoring, which asks whether the system is transparent to humans and high quality; security monitoring, which asks whether the system is secure against attacks and misuse; compliance monitoring, which asks whether the system adheres to relevant regulations and guidelines; and large-scale impacts monitoring, which asks whether the system promotes human flourishing. All six correspond to dimensions of the governance monitoring record described in this chapter. The pre-deployment specification commits to what the system is authorized to do across each of these dimensions. The monitoring program verifies that the commitments are being met. The sampling methodology must be designed to surface failures across all six, not only the ones that are easiest to measure. The NIST finding that compliance monitoring challenges appear focused on what to monitor for rather than how to monitor underscores the problem this book identifies throughout: organizations are still asking the governance question at the level of topic selection rather than evidentiary standard. Knowing what to monitor for is not governance. Knowing what evidence of compliance looks like, produced prospectively, in a form that survives independent review, is.

The conditions that justify re-validation are specific and should be documented in the governance record before deployment, so that the triggers for re-validation are prospective governance commitments rather than retrospective judgments made after a problem has already been identified. Material changes to the model, the training data or the operating configuration trigger re-validation because they change the system whose governance was originally assessed. Detected drift beyond a defined threshold triggers re-validation because it signals that the system is no longer operating within the parameters for which governance was established. Significant incidents trigger re-validation because they reveal failure modes that the original testing program did not surface. And the passage of time, at a cadence proportionate to the system’s risk profile and the rate of change in its operational domain, triggers re-validation because the context evolves even when the system does not. The appropriate cadence is not a universal standard. It is a governance judgment that must be documented and justified for each deployment.

Each re-validation is not a repetition of the original assessment. It is an assessment of whether the original validity claim still holds in the current context. The question is not whether the system performs as it did at deployment. The question is whether the interpretation being placed on the system’s outputs in the current operational context is still justified by the evidence. That question requires comparing current performance against the baseline established at deployment, assessing whether the deployment context has changed in ways that affect the validity of the original governance commitments and documenting the conclusion with the same rigor as the original assessment. A re-validation that produces a finding of continued validity is not a formality. It is an active governance judgment that the organization is prepared to stand behind.

The evidence architecture for a governed agentic deployment has four components that must be designed before the system operates, maintained throughout its lifecycle and preserved in a form that survives the audit, the regulatory inquiry and the legal proceeding that may follow a material failure. They are hierarchical: the first is foundational, and without it the others cannot be assessed. The pre-deployment governance record is the baseline. The operational evidence record is measured against it. The change management record extends it across the system’s lifecycle. The monitoring and re-validation record closes the loop between the original governance commitment and the current operational reality. One clarification on the third component: a change to an agentic system is not merely an event to be logged. It is a governance decision that must be assessed, approved and validated before it reaches production. The change management record documents that prospective process. The operational evidence record documents what the system did after. They are not duplicates. They are sequential and both necessary.

ISO 42001’s lifecycle documentation requirements provide the standard against which the completeness of each record component is assessed. In practice, that documentation is not a single document. It is a layered corpus, traversable by an auditor from the organization’s top-level AI policy down to a specific model version and its last material change. The pre-deployment governance record corresponds to the concept, design and validation stages of the ISO 42001 lifecycle: business case, risk-benefit analysis, system architecture documentation, data lineage records, threat models and the stage-gate validation package that must be complete and approved before the system can proceed to deployment. The operational evidence record corresponds to the operational documentation ISO 42001 requires once the system is live: runbooks, monitoring reports, alert definitions and the periodic review records that show when the last model evaluation on real-world data was conducted, when the last incident drill occurred and when the last bias re-test was completed. A long gap in these records with no documented activity is a governance signal, not a clean finding. The change management record corresponds to the change management artifacts ISO 42001 requires for every material modification to the system: change requests, impact assessments, approvals and post-implementation reviews that show which lifecycle controls were re-applied before the change reached production. The lifecycle corpus closes with decommissioning documentation: formal decommissioning plans, data retention or deletion confirmation and the post-mortem record that feeds lessons learned back into concept-stage guidance for future systems. ISO 42001’s value as an audit framework is that it converts each of these components from a discretionary best practice into a documented, time-stamped and accountable requirement with a named owner, a review date and an evidence trail an auditor can follow.

The Audit and Due Diligence Checklist in Appendix I provides the practical instrument for assessing each record component. Section 0’s Pre-Audit Scoping questions map directly to the pre-deployment governance record: does the organization maintain a centralized inventory of all AI systems including embedded AI features, is registration in the inventory required before deployment, is the inventory reviewed for completeness by a named mechanism owner at defined intervals. These questions can only be answered with reference to a pre-deployment governance record that exists in the required form. If those questions have no answers, the record does not exist in the form audit requires. Section 5’s TEVV and monitoring questions map to the monitoring and re-validation record: are AI models tested under varied conditions and edge cases, are historical performance reports available to auditors on request, is AI lifecycle management aligned with ISO 42001 and NIST AI RMF requirements. The question “are historical performance reports available to auditors on request” is the precise operational test of whether the monitoring record is audit-grade: not whether the data exists internally, but whether it is accessible to an independent party who did not generate it. The vendor and third-party due diligence pathway in Sections 1 and 2 maps to the change management record: do vendor contracts include change notification obligations requiring the vendor to notify before material changes, and is the organization’s process for assessing whether a vendor change triggers the Article 25 substantial modification threshold documented and owned. An organization that can answer every question in the relevant sections of Appendix I with a document reference, a named owner and a review date has built the evidence architecture. An organization that cannot is discovering its gaps at audit time rather than before deployment.

The pre-deployment governance record contains the specification, the risk assessment with its causal pathway analysis, the TEVV plan and results, the acceptance threshold documentation, the oversight mode assignment and the governance approvals. This is the record of the organization’s governance judgment before the system acted. Without it, audit-grade evidence of what followed cannot be assessed because the baseline does not exist. Every subsequent record in the architecture derives its meaning from this one.

The operational evidence record contains the action logs, the exception reports, the escalation records and the human review documentation for actions above the HITL threshold. This is the record of what the system did and how the governance mechanisms responded. It must be maintained in real time and in a form that cannot be modified by the system generating it. The IMDA Model AI Governance Framework for Agentic AI, incorporated in Appendix J, specifies comprehensive real-time action logging as a non-negotiable requirement for agentic systems, reflecting the practical reality that post-hoc reconstruction of agentic behavior is rarely possible and never adequate for governance purposes.

The change management record contains the documentation of every material change to the system, the governance assessment of whether the change modified the trust boundary or the risk profile, the approval at the appropriate governance tier and the post-change validation results. As argued in Chapter 14, every material change to an agentic system is a governance event. The change management record is the evidence that the organization treated it as one and not as a technical update that bypassed the governance process.

The monitoring and re-validation record contains the ongoing evidence of system behavior against the acceptance thresholds defined at deployment, the sampling documentation including sample size justification and subgroup analysis results, the documented conditions that triggered re-validation, the re-validation findings and the governance conclusion following each re-validation cycle. This is not the operational dashboard. It is the documented comparison of current performance against the governance standard, at a cadence and with a methodology that allows genuine drift to be detected before it becomes material, and that produces an audit-grade conclusion about whether the original validity claim still holds in the current operational context.

## What This Chapter Has Done

The chapter has separated model evaluation from system assurance and shown why a benchmarked model is not an audited system.

The chapter has mapped audit-grade evidence to the ISO 42001 lifecycle and named the four components a record must carry to survive inspection.

The chapter has stated the lesson plainly. Same old management, much faster consequences, and the organizations that build the record before their agents operate are the ones whose answers are already in it.

**Same old management. Much faster consequences. The evidence architecture described in this chapter is what governance actually looks like when it is designed for the system that will be audited rather than assembled in response to the auditor who eventually arrives. The organizations that build it before their agents operate will be the ones that can answer the governance questions when they are asked, because the answers will already be in the record. The organizations that do not will be assembling those answers under pressure, in the least favorable conditions possible, from the most incomplete materials imaginable.**

**Final Liability rests with the Human.**

