## How to Use This Template

Every governance decision rests on assumptions. The training data was representative of the deployment population. The vendor’s evaluation results transfer to this operating environment. The escalation path will work when escalation is needed. The user reading the AI’s output will understand it as a recommendation rather than a conclusion. Each of these is a load-bearing claim. Each of them can fail. The Assumption Register is the operational artifact that names them, attaches them to the human who carries Final Liability for them, defines how each is tested and records what happens when one fails.

Per Chapter 20, audit-grade evidence is evidence of process: presence of a design that identified risks and made documented trade-offs. An assumption that has not been named cannot be tested. An assumption that has not been tested is a risk hidden inside a decision. The Register makes the hidden risks visible so the governance function can decide which to accept, which to mitigate and which require the deployment to be reconsidered.

For each assumption: complete all fields. Do not leave fields blank. Where a field is not applicable, state the basis for non-applicability. The Register is reviewed by the named system owner at the cadence recorded in D11; status changes (Active, Watch, Falsified, Superseded, Retired) are recorded in D14 with the date and the human who made the determination. A Falsified assumption is not deleted. It is retained in the Register with its falsification record, because the governance trail that demonstrates the organization detected and responded to the failure is itself evidence.

This template is synchronized with Appendix F (FRIA Section H residual risk and review triggers), Appendix E (Agent Registry trust boundary specification) and the AI Audit and Due Diligence Checklist in Appendix I. Where an assumption is also recorded in another instrument, cross-reference rather than restate; the Register is the system of record for assumption status.

