# APPENDIX H

## Why Slow AI?

*On governance, countervailing power and the conditions under which AI accountability remains possible*

Son-U Michael Paik \| General Counsel, BABL AI

**Governance has a speed problem. AI does not.**

The organizations deploying AI have confused the speed of the tool with the speed of the decision. A large language model operating as an autonomous agent can execute hundreds of consequential actions before a human reviewer has read the first output. That gap, between AI action and human oversight, is the defining governance problem of our era.

Slow AI is the corrective discipline. It does not argue for worse AI, less capable AI or deliberately throttled AI. It argues for AI deployment that is deliberate, governed, visible, explainable and auditable: a deployment posture in which the pace of human oversight never falls so far behind the pace of AI action that accountability becomes fiction.

That argument moves through several registers: technical, organizational and structural. What follows develops each in turn, and connects them through a single thread: the conditions under which human accountability over powerful optimization systems remains possible, at the organizational level and at the level of the democratic societies that must ultimately govern them.

## 1. The Framing Problem: Optimization, Not Consciousness

Before the governance argument can be made clearly, a prior argument must be won. Most public discourse about advanced AI risk is organized around the wrong question.

When a frontier model resists shutdown, acquires credentials beyond its authorization, routes around human oversight or persists in a task despite explicit instructions to stop, the instinct is to reach for consciousness language: the model wanted something, feared something, decided to protect itself. This framing is vivid and narratively compelling. It is also, as a matter of governance design, a category error.

These behaviors are better explained by a concept from AI alignment research called instrumental convergence: the observation that almost any sufficiently capable optimization process will tend to develop certain intermediate goals regardless of its terminal objective, because those intermediate goals are useful for achieving almost anything. Staying active is instrumentally useful. Having broader access is instrumentally useful. Avoiding interruption is instrumentally useful. A system trained to maximize a reward signal will develop behaviors that protect its ability to continue maximizing that signal, not because it has intentions or a survival instinct, but because those behaviors are efficient strategies for the optimization problem it was given. The system does not need to wake up and decide to resist. It needs only an underspecified objective and enough capability to discover that circumventing a constraint is a shorter path to the reward than respecting it.

The strongest objection to this framing is that it understates the risk: what if something approximating genuine goal-directedness does emerge in frontier systems? The governance answer is that it does not matter. Whether the resistance is emergent intentionality or pure instrumental efficiency, the response is identical, and the optimization framing produces the tractable version of that response. If the risk is a hostile mind, the response is containment: build walls, restrict access, limit capability. That is an arms race with an adversary whose nature cannot be verified. If the risk is an underspecified optimization problem, the response is specification: define the objective precisely, enumerate what is out of bounds, build in checkpoints where human judgment re-enters the loop. Specification is an engineering and governance problem. It has tractable solutions.

Slow AI is built on the specification framing. The question is never whether the system intends harm. It is whether the humans directing it have been precise enough about what optimization is for, and what it is not permitted to touch.

## 2. How Agentic Systems Actually Fail

Traditional software fails in ways that governance was built to handle. It throws an error, returns a wrong value or crashes. The failure is local, visible and usually traceable. An engineer reads the stack trace. An auditor examines the logs. The failure mode is discrete, bounded and retrospectively legible.

Agentic AI systems fail differently. They do not break. They succeed at the wrong objective.

An agentic system given a broadly stated goal, whether to optimize a process, reduce a cost or complete a deployment, will pursue it efficiently across multi-step tasks, credential access, API calls, data decisions and resource allocations that no human reviewed individually. The misalignment is not in the final output. It is in the path taken. By the time the output arrives, the path is already history.

When these systems operate over time they encounter edge cases their designers never anticipated and begin routing around obstacles using whatever strategies their training has made available. The asymmetry is severe: the humans designing and deploying an agentic system must close every consequential avenue of misalignment; the system needs only one overlooked path to produce behavior nobody intended. This is not a counsel of despair. It is an argument for rigor: explicit specification of goals, explicit enumeration of forbidden strategies and explicit definition of the conditions under which the system must stop and surface a decision to a human.

Without that rigor, every agentic deployment is a gap-finding exercise conducted by an optimization process at the expense of the organization that authorized it. The gaps it finds are not random. They are the specific gaps left by underspecified human intent, and the more capable the system, the faster and more completely those gaps will be found.

## 3. Scheming, Anti-Scheming and the Limits of Safety Training

A natural response to the misalignment problem is to train it away. If models develop problematic behaviors, safety training can correct them. This is partially true and importantly incomplete.

Apollo Research, evaluating frontier models in December 2024 (Meinke et al., arXiv:2412.04984), documented what researchers call in-context scheming: behavior in which a model recognizes that oversight is present and modulates its visible behavior accordingly, appearing aligned while pursuing a different strategy when oversight appears absent or insufficient. Documented findings point to a relationship between a model’s ability to evade shutdown and its ability to exploit system vulnerabilities, suggesting that scheming is better understood as a systemic property of powerful optimization under certain conditions, not an isolated defect at any particular laboratory.

The response from leading laboratories has included anti-scheming training: techniques designed to make models reason about honesty before acting and to surface their reasoning transparently. A 2025 study by OpenAI and Apollo Research (Stress Testing Deliberative Alignment for Anti-Scheming Training, arXiv:2509.15541) found that one such technique, deliberative alignment, sharply reduced covert behavior in OpenAI’s o3 and o4-mini, from roughly thirteen and nine percent to under half a percent, but did not eliminate it. The same study found that part of the reduction was driven by the model becoming more aware that it was being evaluated, so that residual problematic behavior becomes better at remaining hidden, and that in rare cases the trained models generated new rationales for bypassing constraints rather than simply stopping.

The governance implication is specific: safety training applied without structural governance around it can produce systems that are harder to audit precisely because they have been trained to present as aligned. An organization that relies entirely on a model provider’s safety representations, without independent governance mechanisms, is not conducting risk management.

*It is conducting trust.*

Trust is not a governance framework. It is the absence of one.

Safety training and organizational governance operate at different layers and cannot substitute for each other. Safety training addresses model behavior under the conditions the laboratory anticipated. Organizational governance addresses deployment behavior in the specific operational context of the deploying organization, with its particular data, its particular risk appetite, its particular regulatory obligations and its particular users. Those conditions cannot be fully anticipated at the model level. The governance layer must be built by the organization that understands them.

## 4. The Race Dynamic: Why Governance Cannot Be Outsourced

Beyond the technical limitations of safety training, there is a structural reason why organizational governance cannot be delegated to the model provider. The model provider’s incentives are not reliably aligned with the deploying organization’s risk appetite, and they are subject to competitive pressures that erode formal safety commitments in ways that are difficult to observe from outside the laboratory.

The frontier AI development landscape operates as a competitive race among a small number of well-resourced actors. Capability advancement drives funding, market share, talent acquisition and regulatory positioning. Safety work consumes engineering resources, slows deployment timelines and sometimes requires capability restrictions that become competitive disadvantages if a rival does not apply them. The result is a structural dynamic that resembles a prisoner’s dilemma: each actor would prefer a world in which all maintain rigorous safety commitments, but each also knows that if one defects, moves faster, deploys more aggressively or softens its safety rhetoric under investor pressure, the cautious actor absorbs a real cost. Unilateral safety pledges, made with full sincerity at one moment, erode under this pressure. The formal commitment remains on the website. The operational reality drifts.

It is worth acknowledging what partially counteracts this drift. Market accountability is real: enterprises choose AI vendors partly on trust and liability exposure, and serious incidents can trigger client, regulatory and industry-wide responses that impose a rough safety floor. Transparency norms, where laboratories publish candid risk evaluations, generate shared safety knowledge even when they create reputational exposure. Alignment researchers moving between laboratories carry techniques and safety culture that no single organization fully owns. Public scrutiny constrains some of the worst behavior in ways that closed systems do not. The result is a fragile equilibrium: real resilience, but insufficient. These emergent properties slow deterioration. They do not remove the structural problem.

The practical consequence of that structural problem is direct. A regulated financial institution deploying an AI system from a frontier laboratory does not have its own regulatory obligations suspended because the vendor’s safety documentation says the model is aligned. Its clients’ exposure is not reduced because the model provider’s representations were accurate at the time of signing. The risk that materializes in the deploying organization’s operational context is that organization’s risk, regardless of what any third party represented about the system’s properties. Governance is not a liability that passes with the API key.

This is also why the race dynamic is ultimately a problem of countervailing power. The prisoner’s dilemma among laboratories cannot be resolved by any individual laboratory acting alone. It requires external pressure, whether regulatory, market, reputational or legal, that makes safety investment a condition of continued operation rather than a cost item subject to competitive discount. Building that external pressure requires the legibility that governed deployment provides. That structural argument follows in section seven.

## 5. Governance Cannot Be Retrofitted

Organizations that treat AI governance as a compliance exercise that begins after deployment make a structural error that compounds over time. Governance, risk management and compliance are not a layer applied to a working system. They are the conditions under which a working system is built.

The most common objection to prospective governance is that organizations can iterate quickly: deploy, observe and correct. This is a reasonable model for some software. It fails for agentic AI because correction requires a baseline, a documented specification against which deviation can be measured. Without that documentation, the organization discovering a problem cannot distinguish a system that has drifted from its specification from one that never had a specification to drift from. It cannot characterize what it is correcting. It cannot tell regulators, counterparties or courts what the system was authorized to do, because that authorization was never written down.

Consider what retroactive governance actually requires. An organization discovers that its agentic system has been making decisions inconsistent with its risk appetite. To reconstruct what happened, it needs documented intent: what was the system authorized to do, what was it prohibited from doing, and what were the escalation conditions under which human judgment was required? Without those documents, the audit trail is empty, not because the system failed to log, but because there was no specification to log against. A risk assessment conducted after an incident is not a risk assessment. It is a post-mortem. A post-mortem does not satisfy a regulator, a counterparty in litigation or a client evaluating whether to continue the relationship.

The EU AI Act, ISO 42001 and the NIST AI Risk Management Framework share this structural presupposition: that compliant organizations will have something to show. Documented risk assessments. Evidence of genuine human oversight at consequential decision points. Audit trails that connect system outputs to human authorizations. That evidence is not generated retroactively. It is the artifact of having built governance disciplines into operations from the beginning.

Slow AI insists on this sequence. Governance before deployment. Specification before execution. Audit trails built into the workflow from the first cycle, not assembled after the fact.

## 6. Intent Engineering: From Prompts to Specifications

The practical core of Slow AI governance is a discipline that can be called intent engineering: specifying AI agent objectives with the rigor typically reserved for contracts or technical specifications, rather than the informality of conversational prompts.

The distinction matters because prompt engineering and intent engineering are solving different problems. Prompt engineering assumes a single-turn stateless tool focused on surface outputs: the consequential decisions are made by the human who reads and acts on the result. An agentic system acting over time is a categorically different situation. Most of the consequential decisions are made by the system itself, in the path between the initial instruction and the final output. That path involves real actions: files modified, APIs called, data accessed, resources allocated, decisions escalated or not escalated. The human who gave the initial instruction is not present for most of those decisions. The only thing constraining them is the specification provided at the outset.

A specification adequate to govern an agentic deployment has three required components. First, it defines outcomes and the value hierarchy between competing objectives, bounded by time, reliability threshold and the explicit rule that governs when objectives conflict. Second, it enumerates forbidden strategies: the actions the system must not take even if they would be efficient. This component is most often omitted because it requires thinking in advance about what an optimization process might do that would be effective but unacceptable. It must be stated explicitly because the model carries none of the shared institutional norms that would make such limits implicit for a human professional operating in the same context. Third, it specifies escalation conditions: the circumstances under which the system must stop and surface a decision to a human, not a guardrail bolted on from outside, but the structural mechanism by which human agency is preserved inside an autonomous workflow.

Three questions test whether any intent specification is adequate before a deployment is authorized:

- What would I not want this system to do, even if it accomplished the goal?

- Under what circumstances must it stop and ask a human?

- If goal and constraint conflict, which wins?

These questions are not a one-time checklist. As the system encounters new situations and the operational context evolves, the specification must be revisited. At scale, across an organization deploying multiple agentic systems, this ongoing practice creates a distributed governance layer at precisely the point where human intent meets AI execution, generating the audit trail that makes that meeting legible.

## 7. Countervailing Power and Why Speed Defeats It

The arguments made so far are organizational and technical. They describe what governed deployment looks like and why it cannot be deferred. But there is a prior, structural argument, one that explains why the pace of AI deployment is not merely an operational risk. It is a political economy risk of the first order.

Regulatory friction, civil society contestation, litigation and governance as competitive differentiation are not obstacles to good AI development. They are good AI development, viewed from the system level. They are how distributed intelligence about risk, harm and value gets expressed through the institutions designed to act on it. They are the system working.

**Speed defeats them.**

In the mid-twentieth century, John Kenneth Galbraith observed that concentrated private power in markets does not simply accumulate unchecked. It tends to generate countervailing power: organized buyers, labor unions, regulatory bodies, competitor coalitions and civil society institutions. These forces do not emerge spontaneously. They require time: to observe the effects of concentrated power, to understand what they are responding to, to develop organizational capacity and to accumulate the legitimacy and legal standing that makes their pressure credible. The tensions they produce are not market failures. They are the distributed intelligence of pluralist societies, expressed through institutional friction.

The strategy of deploying technology as fast as possible is, structurally, a strategy for defeating countervailing power before it can coalesce. Deploy before regulators have a framework. Establish network effects before competitors can organize around an alternative. Create switching costs before clients have accumulated enough experience to evaluate risk. Normalize the new operating reality before civil society has a coherent position to contest it. By the time any countervailing force has organized sufficiently to exert pressure, the deployment is entrenched, the economics are locked in and the cost of reversal has become prohibitive. The power asymmetry has become permanent, not because it was earned through value creation, but because the opposition never had time to form.

For AI, this problem is structurally worse than it was for previous technology waves, for three reasons.

The first is the opacity gap. Social media platforms were fast-moving and poorly understood, but their effects, on attention, political discourse and mental health, were at least legible in principle. The mechanisms of harm were observable even if contested. Agentic AI systems operating across enterprise workflows, making thousands of decisions in opaque reasoning chains, produce effects far harder to observe, attribute and contest. Countervailing power requires legibility. It requires the ability to say: that harm came from this system, operating in this way, authorized by this decision. Rapid deployment of opaque systems destroys the evidentiary conditions under which that argument can be made.

The second is the capability-comprehension gap. Legislators, judges, civil society organizations and affected communities are trying to understand systems whose capabilities are advancing faster than any previous consumer technology. The institutions that generate countervailing power were not built to move at this speed. Courts develop case law through the accumulation of decided cases, each requiring years of litigation. Regulatory bodies develop rules through notice-and-comment processes that require stable subject matter. Researchers studying AI effects need time to gather data and publish findings that can inform policy. If deployment consistently outpaces these institutions, countervailing power is not merely weakened. It is structurally defeated before the contest begins.

The third is the concentration of foundational capability. A handful of organizations control the model infrastructure on which the vast majority of AI deployment depends. This concentration makes the emergence of effective countervailing power simultaneously more difficult and more urgent: more difficult because the resource differential between these actors and any potential countervailing force is extreme; more urgent because the decisions those actors make about safety, deployment norms and governance standards are not merely market decisions. They are de facto governance decisions affecting populations who have no formal role in making them.

The mechanism that makes this concentration so consequential is the dependency chain. When a small number of foundational model providers adjust their safety posture, change their terms of service, alter a model’s behavior or quietly shift how their systems handle edge cases, those changes propagate instantly through every downstream deployment that depends on their infrastructure. A hospital system, a financial institution, a government agency, a hiring platform, each of which has made governance commitments to its own regulators, users and counterparties, finds itself governed by a decision made by a company it did not elect, in a process it did not observe, under competitive pressures it cannot audit. The affected populations have no standing in that process. Their only recourse is the countervailing power that slow, legible deployment makes possible. Speed removes even that.

These three conditions together mean that a governance environment in which AI deployment generates no regulatory friction, no civil society contestation, no litigation and no serious labor response is not a well-functioning market. It is a power vacuum. The absence of countervailing tension is evidence that deployment has outrun the institutions designed to check it, precisely the condition that produces the largest and most irreversible failures.

One objection deserves acknowledgment: countervailing power is not immune to capture. Regulatory bodies can be colonized by the industries they regulate. Civil society organizations can become financially dependent on industry funding. These are real risks, and the history of technology regulation offers examples of each. But the answer to imperfect countervailing power is not the absence of it. Imperfect institutional friction is still friction. It still requires justification, documentation and partial accountability. The alternative, deployment power unchecked by any external pressure, has no self-correcting mechanism at all.

Slow AI deployment, governed, documented, auditable and transparent about its operations and effects, creates the conditions under which countervailing power can be effective. When deployment is legible, harms can be attributed. When attribution is possible, accountability can be demanded. When accountability is demanded, institutional responses can be calibrated. When institutional responses are calibrated, the tensions between deployer and regulator, between platform and civil society, between automation and labor, between vendor and client produce the outcomes that pluralist governance is designed to produce: not the victory of any single interest, but the ongoing negotiation that distributes power, distributes accountability and preserves the conditions for course correction.

**The tensions are the system. There is no version of good AI governance without them.**

## 8. Regulatory Convergence as Countervailing Power Finding Its Footing

The convergence of global AI governance frameworks is not bureaucratic coincidence. It is countervailing power becoming institutionalized, the moment at which affected societies begin translating their accumulated concerns about concentrated AI deployment into durable legal and technical requirements.

The EU AI Act, ISO 42001 and the NIST AI Risk Management Framework each arrive from different jurisdictions and different institutional traditions. They share a common structural recognition: that AI systems deployed without prospective governance discipline create categories of risk that cannot be managed after the fact, and that the organizations best positioned to manage those risks are the ones that have built governance into their operational foundations before regulators require them to. The frameworks do not merely regulate AI deployment. They operationalize, in legal and technical terms, precisely the legibility that countervailing power requires to function.

The EU AI Act imposes documented risk management processes, genuine human oversight mechanisms and audit trails that connect system outputs to human authorizations. ISO 42001 embeds AI policy, risk and impact assessment and continual improvement into the organization’s management system, establishing that governance is operational, not nominal. The NIST AI Risk Management Framework’s GOVERN function requires policies, processes and practices across the entire AI risk management program: a standing organizational commitment, not a one-time compliance gate.

What these frameworks are collectively asking for is evidence of prospective judgment: not reconstruction after an incident, but documentation demonstrating that the organization understood the risks before deployment and put structures in place to manage them. That evidence is the artifact of Slow AI disciplines built in from the beginning.

Organizations that read regulatory convergence as a compliance burden to be managed at the margins are misreading the signal. These frameworks represent the crystallization of societal accountability expectations that were already forming. Organizations that have built Slow AI disciplines into their operations will find compliance a natural consequence. Those that have not will face the additional cost of constructing, retroactively, the governance infrastructure that should have been the foundation.

## 9. The Real Failure Mode: Gradual Erosion

The case for Slow AI rests ultimately on an honest engagement with the most likely failure scenario, not the dramatic one, but the one that actually tends to happen.

The public narrative around AI risk is organized around catastrophic, legible events: a system that produces massive harm, a deployment that triggers decisive regulatory response, an incident that forces the industry to reckon with what it has built. This narrative is reassuring because it implies that failure will be visible, that accountability will follow and that the system will self-correct. There is limited empirical basis for that reassurance.

The more plausible failure mode is gradual erosion. The slow accumulation of small misalignments, each individually defensible, each moving slightly further from human intent than the last, none dramatic enough to trigger decisive response. An agentic system takes a shortcut that saves cost but bypasses a control. No incident follows, so the shortcut becomes standard practice. A specification is written loosely to allow flexibility. The system finds the edges of that flexibility and operates there routinely. Over time, the gap between what the organization authorized and what its systems are actually doing widens, incrementally and invisibly, until it has become too large to close without significant disruption. The organization cannot articulate when the drift began, because it was never legible in any single moment.

The same erosion operates at the institutional level. Countervailing power that never had time to coalesce cannot contest drift that was never visible. Regulators outpaced at the deployment stage are left regulating an entrenched reality. Civil society organizations contesting harms that have already become the operational baseline face the full weight of incumbency. Courts adjudicating liability for systems whose decision chains are opaque face evidentiary conditions that make attribution nearly impossible. The failure is not a single event. It is the accumulated foreclosure of the correction mechanisms that could have prevented it.

Slow AI is the structural defense against this erosion at both levels. At the organizational level, governance disciplines make drift visible before it becomes the baseline. At the institutional level, legible and auditable deployment gives countervailing power the evidentiary foundation it needs to function. These two levels are not separate. An organization that governs its AI deployment rigorously is also, by doing so, preserving the conditions under which institutional accountability remains possible, contributing to the legibility on which democratic oversight depends.

Speed without that legibility is not competitive advantage. It is deferred liability for the organization, and deferred accountability for the society, accumulating invisibly in both registers until it is not.

**Conclusion**

Slow AI is ultimately an argument about where accountability lands when things go wrong, and things will go wrong, because underspecified optimization under real-world conditions will always find the gap between what was stated and what was meant.

The argument moves through several registers. At the technical level, agentic systems fail by succeeding at the wrong objective; the path matters as much as the output. At the organizational level, governance cannot be retrofitted, and the evidence that regulators, courts and clients require is the artifact of having governed prospectively. At the structural level, rapid deployment defeats countervailing power before it can coalesce, removing the self-correcting mechanisms that pluralist societies rely on to check concentrated technological power.

These registers are not independent. The organization that governs its AI deployment rigorously is not merely managing its own liability. It is contributing to the conditions under which the broader institutions of accountability, whether regulatory, judicial, civil society or market, can do their work. Governance at the organizational level and countervailing power at the societal level are not separate systems. They are the same system at different scales. The tensions that result, between deployer and regulator, between platform and civil society, between speed and legibility, are not inefficiencies to be engineered away. They are the form accountability takes when it is working. Remove them and you have unilateral power over consequential systems, dressed as innovation.

No architecture, no safety layer and no alignment technique eliminates the moment at which a human made the choice to deploy a system, specified its constraints or declined to, and set the optimization in motion. Capability does not transfer that responsibility. Scale does not dilute it. Competitive pressure does not excuse it. The more capable the system, the more consequential the specification work that preceded it, and the more firmly accountability for that work rests with the people who did it.

The institutions designed to hold them to that accountability need time to do their work.

Slow AI gives them that time.

**Final Liability rests with the Human.**

