# APPENDIX L

## GRC next™: Optionality as Executable Governance

*Reader note. GRC next™ is a separate doctrine from the AI GRC triad set out in this book. Slow AI, Final Liability and Informed Intent govern AI specifically. GRC next™ governs governance, risk management and compliance overall. The two doctrines are designed to coexist: the AI GRC triad makes AI deployments defensible, and GRC next™ keeps the enterprise around AI deployments lawful and operable when conditions change. This appendix sets out the GRC next™ frame, primitives, stress-test logic, maturity model and three working templates.*

## L.1 Frame

GRC next™ treats global optionality as an executable property of an organization. Optionality means the organization can change state safely when conditions change. It can keep operating within agreed boundaries. It can leave or replace concentrated dependencies when those dependencies become unsafe, unavailable or noncompliant. The point is not policy completeness. The point is operational truth. A control is real only if it can be executed under time pressure and proved with evidence.

The doctrine reduces the question of governance to two operational tests.

- Continuity. On a bad day, can each critical service stay within its impact tolerance through the execution of the right switches at the right time?

<!-- -->

- Portability. If the dependency that caused the blast radius is concentrated, can the organization execute an exit plan without breaching tolerance?

These tests matter because modern organizations are built on dense dependency graphs. The largest disruptions tend to come from a small number of shared pipes: a cloud region, an identity provider, a payment rail, a messaging backbone, a specialized SaaS, an outsourced operations center, a single AI model provider. When those pipes fail, policies do not restore service. Switches and exits do.

GRC next™ does not replace security, privacy, resiliency engineering or vendor management. It aligns them around a single audit-grade unit of truth: the critical service with an owner, a tolerance, mapped pipes, executable switches and at least one executable exit for the top concentration dependency.

**Design premise. If you cannot change state, you are not governed. If you cannot prove you can change state, you are not compliant.**

## L.2 Primitives

GRC next™ breaks the problem of optionality into a small set of primitives. Each primitive is concrete, testable and evidence-bearing.

### L.2.1 Services

A service is an outcome delivered to customers, staff or partners. It is not a team and not a system. Examples include customer checkout, card authorization, identity and access, customer support, billing and incident communications. Each critical service has a named role-based owner, defined customers and the jurisdictions that constrain its delivery. Services are the unit for tolerances, mapping, switches, exits, exercises and audit evidence. If a service is unnamed or unowned, risk decisions drift and execution slows.

### L.2.2 Time-based impact tolerances

Impact tolerance is the maximum tolerable disruption before harm becomes unacceptable. It is defined in time and severity terms so it can be used as an execution deadline. Tolerances are business commitments, not only technical RTO or RPO. They must distinguish between down and degraded states when the distinction matters. They anchor pass and fail outcomes for exercises and incident retrospectives. Without tolerances, teams cannot prioritize. With tolerances, incident response becomes a series of decisions against a clock: detect, decide, execute and prove.

### L.2.3 Pipes

Pipes are the end-to-end dependencies required for a service to function. Pipes include internal components, third parties, data flows, identity paths, regions and operational steps. Maps must identify single points of failure, shared dependencies and jurisdiction constraints. Concentration is recorded explicitly: top vendors, regions, products and datasets that dominate service delivery. A map is only useful if it can predict breakpoints and guide switch and exit design.

### L.2.4 Switches

Switches are pre-defined moves that change service state. Failover. Reroute. Degrade. Disable. Throttle. Quarantine. Rotate. Fall back to manual processing. Each switch has a trigger, a decision owner, a delegated authority path, the steps, the comms and the evidence capture points. Authority must be delegated in advance. In a crisis, waiting for approvals burns the tolerance budget. Switches should be drillable and ideally automatable, but automation is optional. Switches translate governance into mechanics. They specify what the organization will do under stress, not what it hopes to do.

### L.2.5 Exits

Exits are executable plans to reduce or remove concentration dependency. An exit is not just a termination right. It is the operational work needed to move, replace or decommission the dependency without breaching tolerance. At minimum, each critical service needs one exit plan for its top concentration dependency. Exits must address data return and deletion, portability formats, integration changes, staffing, costs and timing. Exit plans should be drillable in small slices, such as restoring a sample dataset into an alternate target. Exit readiness improves resilience and negotiation leverage. When portability is real, lock-in is reduced and vendor risk becomes manageable.

### L.2.6 Evidence and improvement

GRC next™ uses an evidence-first posture. No evidence, no credit. Evidence packs show that controls exist, were executed, and improved through corrective and preventive action (CAPA) closure. Evidence should be structured and repeatable, not ad hoc screenshots. Exercises and real incidents should generate artifacts that auditors can follow end-to-end. Improvement is demonstrated by closed CAPA items tied to specific breakpoints and tolerance outcomes. Practical test: if a new leader joined tomorrow, could they read the dossier for Service 1 and confidently execute a switch or exit within tolerance?

## L.3 Stress-Test

The value of GRC next™ shows up under pressure. The doctrine identifies common failure modes and uses severe-but-plausible scenarios to exercise the primitives.

### L.3.1 Common failure modes

- Unowned services. No accountable decision maker. Delayed calls. Inconsistent communications.

<!-- -->

- Tolerances without maps. Leaders know the deadline but teams do not know the breakpoints.

<!-- -->

- Maps without authority. Teams know what to do but cannot legally or procedurally execute fast enough.

<!-- -->

- Runbooks without drills. The plan fails on day zero because it was never exercised.

<!-- -->

- Contract rights without portability. The organization can terminate but cannot move data or integrations in time.

<!-- -->

- Hidden concentration. Shared providers amplify outages across multiple services.

<!-- -->

- Evidence gaps. Controls cannot be proven, audits fail and learning does not compound.

### L.3.2 Severe-but-plausible scenarios

A severe-but-plausible scenario is realistic enough to expose true dependencies and decision bottlenecks, but severe enough to force real tradeoffs. Five recurring patterns:

- Cloud region impairment. First to break: identity refresh or messaging backbone tied to the affected region. Switches: failover, reroute, degrade noncritical features. Exit pressure point: region exit plan or multi-region design for top tolerances.

<!-- -->

- Identity provider outage. First to break: login, token refresh, administrative access. Switches: emergency access, alternate authentication path, manual approvals. Exit pressure point: provider portability, token format and directory federation.

<!-- -->

- Vendor SaaS repeated incidents. First to break: support, billing, HR workflows, audit evidence sources. Switches: manual fallback, queue reroute, feature disable. Exit pressure point: data export, API parity, termination assistance terms.

<!-- -->

- Regulatory constraint change. First to break: cross-border flows or subprocessor restrictions. Switches: traffic pinning, localization, disable analytics. Exit pressure point: jurisdictional exit, subprocessor swap, data residency options.

<!-- -->

- AI model safety regression. First to break: incorrect decisions or unsafe outputs. Switches: disable model, route to rules-based fallback, tighten filters. Exit pressure point: model vendor swap, decommission plan, fallback model warm-pool.

The scenario outcome is evaluated against service tolerances. The exercise is considered successful only if the executed switches keep the service within tolerance and the evidence pack is complete enough to support audit and learning. Exercises should also test delegated authority, communications readiness and exit feasibility for the highest concentration dependency. Small exit drills are often more informative than large tabletop discussions: can the organization export a representative dataset, restore it into an alternate target and run a smoke test with documented results?

## L.4 Decide

GRC next™ translates the concept into a practical operating model. The maturity model gives the organization a way to assess where it stands. The gates prevent false confidence. The starting sequence ensures the program compounds rather than sprawling.

### L.4.1 Maturity model

- L0 Unowned. No named critical services, no owners, no tolerances. Work is reactive and hard to audit.

<!-- -->

- L1 Owned. Critical services and owners exist. Draft tolerances exist. Limited mapping and weak evidence.

<!-- -->

- L2 Mapped. Service dossiers for top services exist. Dependency maps exist. Material providers are linked to services.

<!-- -->

- L3 Exercised. Delegated switches exist. At least one severe-but-plausible exercise has been executed with an evidence pack and CAPA closure.

<!-- -->

- L4 Instrumented. Metrics support detect, decide and execute within tolerance. Periodic exit drills occur. CAPA closure is routine.

### L.4.2 Gates

GRC next™ uses pass and fail gates that prevent false confidence. If any gate fails, organization maturity is capped at L2 until the gap is closed.

- Impact tolerances exist for critical services.

<!-- -->

- Dependency maps exist for critical services.

<!-- -->

- Delegated switch authority exists, not only runbooks.

<!-- -->

- At least one executable exit plan exists for the top concentration dependency.

<!-- -->

- At least one executed severe-but-plausible exercise exists with an evidence pack.

### L.4.3 What to do first

A common failure is trying to map everything. GRC next™ starts narrow and compounds. A practical first cycle:

- Name the top five critical services and assign role-based owners.

<!-- -->

- Write a time-based impact tolerance for each service. Distinguish down and degraded where the distinction matters.

<!-- -->

- Build a dependency map for each service, including third parties, regions and key data flows.

<!-- -->

- Identify the top concentration dependency per service. Choose the single most dangerous one as the first exit target.

<!-- -->

- Create a small switch catalog: the five to ten moves that keep services within tolerance. Add delegated authority.

<!-- -->

- Write one executable exit plan for the first exit target, including data portability steps and timing.

<!-- -->

- Run one severe-but-plausible exercise that forces the switches. Capture an evidence pack. Open and close CAPA items.

The first cycle does not need perfection. It needs truth and drillability. The value comes from repeating cycles, tightening evidence and closing CAPA so future response is faster and more reliable. The outcome of repeated cycles: governance becomes something the organization can run, not something it can only describe.

## L.5 Service Dossier Template

A Service Dossier is the core proof unit of GRC next™. The template is intentionally minimal and drill-oriented. Use one dossier per critical service. Six sections, in order.

### Section 1. Service definition, owner, customers, jurisdictions

Name the service. Define the customer outcome. Assign an owner by role. List customers. List the jurisdictions that constrain delivery.

### Section 2. Time-based impact tolerance

Specify maximum tolerable disruption. Include down and degraded tolerances, recovery objectives and unacceptable harm triggers.

### Section 3. End-to-end dependency map including third parties

List major components, data stores, identity path, regions, key third parties, subprocessors and concentration notes.

### Section 4. Switch entries protecting the service, including delegated authority

For each switch: trigger, decision owner, delegated authority path, steps, communications, evidence capture.

### Section 5. Exit plan for top concentration dependency

Name the dependency by class (vendor, region, product, data). Provide the executable plan: prerequisites, portability steps, target, timelines, costs, risks and communications.

### Section 6. Latest test report and evidence pack, tolerance met yes or no

Link to the latest exercise or incident review. State whether tolerance was met. List CAPA items and closure status.

## L.6 Evidence Pack Template

An Evidence Pack is a structured folder or record that makes execution auditable. It should be consistent across exercises and incidents. The minimum content set:

- Exercise or incident identifier, date, scope, services in scope.

<!-- -->

- Service dossiers referenced, with versions.

<!-- -->

- Scenario description, inject timeline and pass criteria tied to tolerances.

<!-- -->

- Decision log: who decided what, when, under which delegated authority.

<!-- -->

- Switch execution artifacts: runbook steps, automation logs, change tickets.

<!-- -->

- Observability artifacts: metrics, alerts, dashboards used to detect and confirm recovery.

<!-- -->

- Communications: internal updates, external notices, customer impact statements.

<!-- -->

- Third-party coordination: vendor tickets, status pages captured, escalation records.

<!-- -->

- Data artifacts where relevant: export logs, restore logs, deletion confirmations.

<!-- -->

- Outcome summary: tolerance met yes or no per service, time-to-decision, time-to-execution.

<!-- -->

- CAPA register: breakpoints, root causes, owners, due dates, closure evidence.

<!-- -->

- Approvals and sign-off for closing the exercise or incident record.

Keep the pack human-readable. Avoid tool-specific tokens. Ensure the evidence shows a coherent narrative from detection to recovery to improvement.

